<FIRST>u w AM-Iraq-Compensation 2ndLd-Writethru a0634 03-27 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iraq-Compensation, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0634,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Delegation Nears Agreement on Compensation Agreement</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: retransmitting a0402 to eliminate garble at end</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and Iraq have reached
agreement in principle for Iraq to pay compensation for the 37 U.S.
sailors killed aboard the frigate Stark in a May, 1987 Iraqi
missile attack in the Persian Gulf, sources said Monday.
   The compensation package still needs the formal approval of both
governments, said the sources, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Progress on the stalled claim request was made when a U.S.
delegation, led by State Department legal adviser Abraham Sofaer,
went to Baghdad last week. The talks ended Monday and Sofaer was
headed back to Washington, State Department spokeswoman Margaret
Tutwiler said.
   In their talks, the U.S. and Iraqi teams apparently ``are
reaching the final stages of achieving a substantial settlement on
the claims,'' Ms. Tutwiler said.
   She said she did not know when the actual agreement would be
concluded and could not divulge details of its content.
   At the Pentagon, defense sources said an agreement had been
reached but they described the accord as ``tentative _ subject to
review back here in Washington.''
   The United States presented Iraq with a $29.6 million claim for
the families of 37 crewmembers who died on the guided missile
frigate Stark when an Iraqi jet fighter fired two French-made
Exocet missiles at the ship.
   Iraq claimed the missile attack was a mistake born of the
tensions of the Iran-Iraq war.
   The U.S. claim was presented 11 months ago but Iraq rejected the
amount, which includes $800,000 for each of the families.
   The defense sources, who insisted on anonymity, said they could
not discuss the dollar amount in the agreement or how it might be
divided among the families of those who were killed; the sailors
who were injured; and as settlement toward the cost of repairing
the Stark.
   ``But apparently our negotiators are recommending we settle for
a bit less than we were originally asking with the goal of ending
further delays in settling the issue,'' one source said.
   In addition to the $29.6 million sought for the families of the
37 dead sailors, the Navy has asked Iraq to pay $82.9 million to
cover the cost of repairing the Stark and returning it to active
duty with the fleet.
   Pentagon officials have refused to say how much they asked Iraq
to pay to sailors who suffered injuries but survived the attack.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
