<FIRST>r a PM-CondorEgg     03-27 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Condor Egg,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rare Condor Egg Found at Zoo on Easter Morning</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tiny, pale aqua egg was found in the nest
box of a pair of nearly extinct California condors at the Los
Angeles Zoo.
   The egg, measuring 5 inches long, 3 inches in circumference and
weighing about 10 ounces, was spotted early Easter Sunday morning.
   Zoo workers took the egg to an incubator while the parents,
Cuyama and Cachuma, a pair of 6-year-olds, were away from the nest.
   ``What an Easter egg!,'' said zoo spokeswoman Deborah Pollack.
``If fertile, God willing, it will hatch in 54 to 58 days.''
   The pair had an egg last month that proved to be infertile. Zoo
officials also took that egg away for artificial incubation in
hopes that Cachuma would ``double clutch'' or lay a second egg.
   ``We have high hopes for this egg because since the time of the
last one they have definitely improved their (mating) technique,''
Ms. Pollack said. ``It's a big egg, a nice egg. It looks good but
we won't know for sure for another week.''
   She added that there were no cracks in the shell.
   In the wild, the massive birds with a 9{-foot wing span would
normally lay one egg every other year, Ms. Pollack said.
   Molloko is the only California condor chick conceived in
captivity. The bird was born last April and stays in the San Diego
Wild Animal Park.
   There are only 28 California condors left in the world. Fourteen
of them are in the Wild Animal Park and 14 at the Los Angeles Zoo.
</TEXT>
