<FIRST>r w PM-US-PhilippinesFarms     03-27 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Philippines Farms,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Small Third World Farmers Report Gains from Export Crops</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When 448 farm households on the Philippine
island of Mindanao switched to raising sugar for sale to the United
States, their earnings per acre grew to nearly double those of
their neighbors.
   The cash crop brought the equivalent of just over $100 an acre
in a year, compared with about $52 an acre for the corn grown by
neighboring families. These were poor families, with farms that
averaged only about 10 acres. In a country where the average
citizen earns about $660 a year, the difference was huge.
   ``Contrary to conventional wisdom, farmers who produce crops for
export have more income and are better fed than subsistence farmers
who produce only basic food crops for home consumption,'' said the
International Food Policy Research Institute, an independent study
organization.
   The institute project was run by Joachim von Braun, a West
Germam farm economist, with a grant from the U.S. government's
Agency for International Development.
   The study found at least one bad effect from the contracts
offered by the Bukidnon Sugar Co.: some corn farmers sold their
land or gave up leases and took jobs on sugar farms, creating a new
group of landless farm workers.
   Von Braun suggested that the Philippine government should have
gotten the mill to make contracts for sugar with the tenant
farmers, as well as with those who owned land. The government could
also have taken measures to improve the production of small farms
that stayed with growing corn, making credit, fertilizer and new
varieties available, he said.
   Contrary to some people's belief, the researchers saw no damage
to child health _ but little improvement either _ from the change
to cash crops.
   While better income from the sugar provided more food for the
family, it did little to solve the problem of badly nourished
children. Better health and sanitation measures are needed as well,
the report said.
   Von Braun said that as farmers' income rose, the proportion they
spent on traditional foods went down. Spending on meat, housing,
transport and education rose sharply among the most prosperous
farmers in the Philippine group.
   Von Braun studied farmers not only in the Philippines, but also
in the east African republic of Kenya who made a similar switch,
and Guatemalans who tried vegetables instead of corn.
   There were also groups in two more African countries who
switched to farming for the market rather than for home
consumption. In central African Rwanda they planted potatoes and
tea instead of corn. In Gambia, on the Atlantic coast, the shift
was from swamp rice to peanuts and to rice under irrigation.
   The researchers found that when small farmers switched to cash
crops, they often kept some of their land in traditional food crops
as a kind of insurance.
   The study said that makes sense, because the income from cash
crops is not always certain. Sugar prices have dropped from the
levels that first made the switch attractive in the Philippines,
for example.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
