<DOCNO> AP890327-0013 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-27-89 0057EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-CFCSubstitutes     03-27 0751</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-CFC Substitutes,740</SECOND>
<HEAD>EPA Defends `Voluntary' Approach to Ozone-Damaging Chemicals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency says the
hunt to find substitutes for ozone-depleting chemicals will go much
quicker without strict government regulation of the chemical
industry.
   EPA spokesman Chris Rice said the agency's policy is voluntary
cooperation _ instead of strong government control _ because EPA
has received ``excellent cooperation'' from the industry.
   Rice was reacting to a recent General Accounting Office report
that concluded the EPA's policy is failing to ensure the safe
testing of chemicals that will take the place of
chlorofluorocarbons, or CFC's.
   By not starting the lengthy regulation process now, EPA will
find itself unable to quickly restrict use of many substitutes
shown to endanger human health and the environment, the GAO said.
   The GAO, Congress' investigative agency, said EPA should use its
powers to demand unpublished test results and quickly slap controls
on substitutes believed to endanger the environment or humans.
   The United States and the 12-nation European Community have
pledged to ban chlorofluorocarbons by 1999 _ surpassing the goals
of the 1987 Montreal Protocol which requires they be halved by the
end of the century.
   CFC's, and related chemicals called halons, are stable and
non-toxic when released into the atmosphere, but 10 to 100 years
later, when they rise 15-20 miles to the stratosphere, their
chemical bonds are broken apart.
   Scientists say their chlorine atoms destroy ozone, allowing more
of the sun's ultraviolet rays to reach Earth, causing more skin
cancer and eye cataracts, and suppressing human immune systems.
   The recent General Accounting Office report called the decision
to rely on voluntary cooperation a course that would allow eventual
production of CFC alternatives ``by anyone, in any amount, and for
any use, without prior notification ... or an EPA safety review.''
   But the EPA's Rice countered, ``We feel using that cooperative
relationship is going to obtain the information we need on a much
quicker track.
   ``We have very great concern over toxicity testing'' Rice said,
adding that EPA has ``not ruled out'' using its full authority to
regulate the industry ``if we're not getting the cooperation we
need.''
   ``It's a question of how you do it as quickly as possible while
everyone is clamoring for new compounds as quickly as possible,''
said Kevin Fay, of the Alliance For Responsible CFC Policy,
representing CFC producers and users.
   ``The concern is you've got some policy makers in Congress
saying we've got to go faster, and you have regulatory structures
that would slow it down,'' he said, comparing the dilemma to
sitting at an intersection with both red and green lights.
   The Toxic Substances Control Act allows EPA not only to demand
industry's test results, but to order advance notice from any
company planning to convert chemicals designed for other use into
CFC substitutes.
   ``Given the importance of the safety issue, we believe that
EPA's approach to assessing the safety of CFC ... chemical
substitutes should include the use of (the) two TSCA authorities,''
the GAO said in a report requested by the chairman of the House
Energy and Commerce Committee, John D. Dingell, D-Mich.
   The GAO said dependence on voluntary cooperation is a mistake
because, ``EPA's previous attempt to gather testing information''
from CFC producers in December 1987 ``resulted in incomplete data.''
   By ordering the test results, EPA officials could determine if a
chemical presented ``an unreasonable health or environmental risk''
and if so, could require testing to determine the specific risks.
   If necessary, the agency could take actions ranging from
labeling requirements to a complete ban.
   Advance notice of new uses for chemicals would let EPA ``review
the safety of these new uses and quickly control'' any substances
posing a danger.
   If EPA determined the information was inadequate to ensure the
safety of the new use, the agency could require more testing and
prevent the new use while data is gathered.
   CFC's are used as coolants in refrigerators and freezers in
home, office and automobile air conditioners; propellants in
aerosols; blowing agents for plastic foam products and insulation;
cleaning agents for metals and electronic equipment; fast-food
cartons, and sterilizing agents for medical instruments.
   Related chemicals, halons are used in fire extinguishers where
foam or water treatment would not work: ships, planes, military
vehicles, computer facilities, telephone switching centers and
libraries.
   Substitutes for CFC's will be tested for at least two more years
before commercial production could begin, Fay said. No substitutes
have yet been found for halons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890327-0014 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-27-89 0111EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Sudan-Famine     03-27 0695</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sudan-Famine,0719</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Relief Effort Faces Daunting Problems in Sudan</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY20 of March 26</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALIA BALIGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MUGLAD, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Starvation and disease, abduction and
slavery are some of the atrocities that six years of civil war have
inflicted on millions of people of southern Sudan.
   Consider Akwa Karfath Kawal, a woman of African descent who fled
hunger in her hometown of Aweil and ended up in a squalid refugee
area just outside Muglad in western Sudan.
   Armed Arabs abducted her five sons en route, she says, forcing
them into slavery as cattle herders.
   Another woman, Miriyal Mayowin, lost two toddlers to starvation
and one to the Arabs during the trek out of the south.
   ``There is nothing in Aweil but destruction and we were hungry,
so we left,'' she said. ``We ate shrubs as we walked ... but there
was no water.
   ``So many died.''
   More than 12,000 refugees in this maze of huts made of sticks
and plastic sheets tell similar tales.
   Dressed in rags, these Dinka tribesmen and their brethren in
other camps have been changed by the war from cultivators and
cattle breeders to paupers dependent on relief.
   The Dinka, largest of Sudan's 115 tribes, form the backbone of
the rebel army. They are Christians and animists.
   Rebels began fighting in 1983 for more autonomy from the
government, which is dominated by the Moslem Arab majority in the
north.
   On Sunday, a new broad-based Cabinet met for the first time in
Khartoum and endorsed a peace plan to end the war.
   And in April, the world will try to assuage the suffering of
Sudan's people with an ambitious emergency relief program
coordinated by the United Nations.
   Relief workers for both Western donor governments and private
organizations say the $132 million program will save the lives of
some of the hundreds of thousands of southern Sudanese who face
starvation.
   But they say the outside world has neglected the war and its
ruin for so long that a logistical nightmare will further
complicate the already precarious security situation. They doubt
the logjams can be sufficiently overcome to prevent another
disaster like last summer, when at least 250,000 people died after
monsoon rains isolated them without food.
   Everyone agrees the need is real and urgent, even the rebel
Sudan People's Liberation Army. Though the rebels have refused a
call by the United Nations for a one-month truce to let the food
pass, they have pledged not to attack supply convoys in certain
protected corridors.
   The plan is to stockpile 100,000 tons of food, medicine and
other supplies in places accessible to 2.25 million southerners in
both government and rebel-held areas. The supplies are to be in
place before the rainy season starts in May and paralyzes
transportation.
   ``It's an enormous quantity and a short period of time,'' said
one relief worker. ``Above all, this is Sudan.''
   Relief and government officials agreed to the plan for bringing
in supplies by train, plane, Nile River barge and truck convoy. The
government also promised to undo complicated bureaucratic
procedures for the relief organizations.
   For their part, Western relief workers offer endless stories
about bureaucratic inefficiency, generally on condition they not be
identified.
   A British-based organization says it had to wait a year before
four jeeps were cleared through Sudanese customs.
   A Dutch diplomat says he tried to transfer $4 million in aid to
the emergency operation. He was handed forms to fill out and told
that the transfer would probably take weeks.
   Much of the food must be transported to government-held southern
areas on Nile barges or trains. However, the barges and trains have
made no more than one trip in the past year because of security
problems and nervous railway workers.
   The government says of Sudan's 22 million people, 4 million are
southerners. It says half have been displaced by the war to camps
in Ethiopia or northern Sudan, and half still need relief in the
south.
   Southerners, however, claim they are 6 million.
   Western relief workers suspect that the discrepancy _ 2 million
people _ represents the number who died as a result of the war.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
