<FIRST>r i PM-Paraguay     03-27 0518</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Paraguay,0532</SECOND>
<HEAD>Paraguan Opposition Party Picks Candidate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH LOVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The country's chief opposition leader
was picked at a weekend convention to run for president in May 1
elections, but his party vowed to boycott a new government in the
event of election fraud.
   Domingo Laino, head of the Authentic Radical Liberal Party,
accepted his party's nomination Sunday night and vowed in his
speech to defend Paraguay's peasants and adopt economic policies to
meet their needs.
   ``We will work with the clean hands and moral strength of the
people,'' said Laino, 53, an economist and former university
professor. He was exiled for seven years by the recently deposed
government of Gen. Alfredo Stroessner.
   Laino was expelled by Stroessner's government in 1981 after
writing a book about the business activities of Nicaraguan dictator
Anastasio Somoza. The Nicaraguan, a friend of Stroessner, was
granted asylum in Paraguay after his ouster in 1979. He was
assassinated a year later on an Asuncion street.
   ``Who is to say that on May 1, there will not be a new
government composed of the glorious Authentic Radical Liberal
Party?'' said Laino. He was the only candidate proposed for the
presidency at the convention.
   Laino was carried from the convention hall on the shoulders of
supporters following his acceptance speech. Delegates also approved
candidates for the House of Deputies and Senate.
   The May 1 elections will pick a president to fill the four years
remaining in the five-year term of Stroessner, who was ousted Feb.
3 by Gen. Andres Rodriguez. The coup leader, who had served as an
aide to Stroessner, declared himself provisional president,
dissolved Congress, and called for new elections.
   The Colorado Party, the country's largest and best-organized
party, has governed since 1947. It is expected to ratify Rodriguez
as its presidential candidate at a convention set for April 1.
   ``We know that many sectors of the government harbor hidden
intentions of legitimizing the current de facto government,'' said
Laino, a member of the House of Deputies from 1967 to 1977.
   In recent weeks, the party has repeatedly criticized what it
views as irregularities in voter registration, and it has suggested
the Rodriguez government might be trying to steal the election.
   Stroessner, who had led Paraguay since a 1954 coup, was elected
to an eighth consecutive term in February 1988 elections widely
regarded as fraudulent.
   A plan adopted by Laino's party calls for rejecting any seats
won in Congress if it deems the May 1 balloting to be fraudulent.
   Even if the elections are viewed as fair, the party still would
withdraw from Congress if electoral law reforms and changes in
voter registration lists are not made before municipal elections
scheduled for October 1990. The party claims voter lists are
inflated in favor of the Colorado Party.
   It also conditioned its participation in Congress on revocation
of a law which allows a president to serve an unlimited number of
terms. It also demands repeal of two laws frequently used under
Stroessner to crack down on dissidents and a ban on soldiers
belonging to political parties.
</TEXT>
