<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     03-27 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WATERLOO, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Canada goose seems to have fallen hard
for a Shetland pony _ a true wild goose chase, says a stable hand.
   Mike Gottsch, who was working at the Jump Over the Moon Training
Center during spring break from college, said the goose flew onto
the ranch about a month ago and soon began following the pony
through pastures. It even ate corn from the pony's trough.
   ``He just got attached to him and won't leave him alone,''
Gottsch said.
   Sometimes the goose honks, hisses and bites the pony, said Stan
Miller, who boards several horses at the stables. But the bird also
will tag along from pen to pen and sometimes rides on the animal's
back.
   A silver identifying band often used by wildlife authorities is
attached to the bird's right leg. Gottsch said no one has contacted
officials about the goose.
   The unusual relationship has raised some eyebrows.
   ``People, they can't believe it,'' Gottsch said. ``They think
it's a domestic we've raised or something.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was a convention that seemed stranger
than fiction.
   The Tacoma Sheraton was invaded by 1,500 science fiction fans
for Norwescon XI, a convention that featured a masquerade ball,
seminars on the physical properties of alien worlds, chain mail
fabrication and Star Trek.
   The activities turned the heads of hotel guests not attending
the convention.
   On one stairway, a starfighter and a Venusian princess brushed
by two businessmen, while nearby a barbarian adjusted his battle
gear.
   ``What is this?'' one businessman asked the other.
   The conference ended Sunday.
</TEXT>
