<DOCNO> AP890327-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-27-89 0203EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Pope-Text     03-27 0643</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pope-Text,0650</SECOND>
<HEAD>English Text of John Paul II's Easter Message</HEAD>
<UNK>With PM-World Easter</UNK>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Following are excerpts from the official
Vatican translation in English of Pope John Paul II's Easter Sunday
message, which was delivered in Italian:
   In this Passover is inscribed the new and eternal covenant. The
covenant of the God of Life with man, condemned to death. The
covenant with humanity. The covenant with the world. With ``the
world which is the theater of the history of the human race.'' With
the world which Christians believe was created and is kept in
existence by the love of the Creator. With the world subject to the
slavery of sin but which _ with defeat of the Evil One _ by the
disobedience of Christ even unto death has been set free.
   In Christ crucified and risen this liberation remains in God for
all human beings. In Christ crucified and risen the world has been
restored to God so that it may be fashioned anew according to God's
design and reach that fullfillment willed by God from all eternity.
...
   Over these tragedies and triumphs of today's world, of the man
of today, God continues to pass through the Resurrection of his
Son, the Son of Man. He passes and sets free, as at the time of the
Exodus, as at the moment when Christ rises, and transforms the
world.
   God passes and frees from the fear that oppresses so many of our
brothers and sisters in the face of the uncertainty of the future,
everywhere in the world, he passes where death expresses once more
its horrors, where suffering imprints its marks on flesh and on
souls, he passes where there do not exist conditions worthy of a
truly human life through the lack of housing, promiscuity,
vagrancy, where selfishness withers the fruitfulness of marriage
and the family breaks up, where the innocence of children is
exploited and corrupted, where violence is done to their
defenseless goodness, where the shameful commerce of vice is
carried on and women are still its main victim.
   God passes and sets free, the Passover of the Resurrection, from
the perils of intolerance whatever name it bears where the
proclamation of Easter has not reached or is hindered, where
consciences are oppressed, where Christ's faithful cannot openly
invoke him or suffers persecution because of the love of him and
his Church and because of their faithfulness to their rites and
their own age-old religious traditions. He passes in the countries
where Christians cannot gather about the altars to celebrate the
Eucharist where the flock waits for its own pastor, whose guidance
it misses and longs for.
   For religious freedom, though it is deeply felt by consciences
and is written in the constitutions of states and in international
conventions, is often today trampled upon in many different ways.
God likewise passes where on the troubled and bloodstained horizon
of various countries the longed-for peace is yet to be seen where
men, though they are brothers, fight one another in a scene of
destruction and hatred as is still happening in the beloved and
tormented Lebanon. ...
   In his blood all is reconciled: man with God, with himself, with
nature: at this point there gains new strength and awareness.
...This is the truth which Easter proclaims to today's world which
in so many ways seems to be rushing headlong toward
self-destruction and death ...
   Easter, the Passover of the Lord, lasts unchangeably. It cannot
be blotted out, either in the history of the human race or in the
history of the whole creation. It lasts unchangeably. Christ's
Resurrection has not been ``added'' to history. It is the history _
the whole history _ of man, which is inscribed in this unique day
which the Lord has made so that he can make all things new.
</TEXT>
