<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Review Expected to Lead to Tougher U.S. Chemical Export Curbs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Bush administration official says new
regulations may be created to help block the export of chemicals
and equipment for making poison gas weapons to developing nations.
   Paul Freedenberg, undersecretary of commerce for export
administration, said the State and Commerce departments are working
with the Central Intelligence Agency on a policy review.
   ``We're reviewing the strengthening of controls,'' Freedenberg
said Sunday. ``Most likely we won't need legislation, we just need
further regulation. And more importantly, I think it's likely that
we'll be looking for international cooperation.''
   Freedenberg said the United States and 16 other industrialized
nations have pledged to prevent the export of critical poison-gas
chemicals and manufacturing equipment to four ``problem countries''
_ Iran, Iraq, Libya and Syria.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Time Flies When You're Having Fun Doing Your Taxes</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Internal Revenue Service has a new
question for you: How long does it take to complete IRS tax forms?
   The IRS spent five years and $1.9 million study to figure out
that the average taxpayer should be able to fill out Form 1040, the
dreaded individual income tax return, in exactly 3 hours and 7
minutes.
   This year, for the first time, IRS instructions for more than
350 tax forms includes an estimate of how long it takes to complete
each one. The notices also include the name and address of an
official to contact if someone wants to complain about a form or
dispute a time estimate.
   The idea is that if enough people complain, bureaucrats will
feel pressured to simplify the forms _ or perhaps to shorten some
or eliminate them altogether _ in the interest of easing the burden
of government paperwork.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>GOP Spending Doubled Democrats' in 1987-88 Elections</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democrat Party narrowed its spending gap
with Republicans in the 1987-88 election cycle, but figures show
the GOP still raised and spent more than double the Democrats.
   The Federal Election Commission reported Sunday that the
Republican Party raised $263.3 million and spent $257 million in
1987-88, compared to $127.9 million raised and $121.9 million spent
by the Democratic Party.
   By contrast, when President Reagan ran for re-election in
1983-84, the Republicans raised a record $297.9 million and spent
$300.8 million, while the Democrats raised $98.5 million and spent
$97.4 million.
   During the most recent election cycle, direct contributions to
candidates totalled $3.4 million for the Republicans and $1.7
million for the Democrats, the FEC said.
</TEXT>
