<FIRST>r a PM-HaitianStandoff     03-27 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Haitian Standoff,0472</SECOND>
<HEAD>Haitian Refugees Bolt Against Coast Guard On High Seas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high-seas standoff between the Coast Guard and
250 U.S.-bound Haitians packed aboard a rickety 50-foot sailboat
ended peacefully after a 30-hour confrontation that included
threats babies would be thrown overboard.
   The Haitians agreed Sunday to the leave the boat and be returned
to their country. No injuries were reported.
   One refugee woman was rescued after leaping into the sea and
others vowed to throw their infant children overboard unless they
were allowed to continue toward the United States, said Coast Guard
Petty Officer Gary Starks.
   ``It was really an ordeal and there were some very tense
moments,'' said Starks. ``There was no idea what would happen and
none of the Haitians had life jackets. There was a potential for a
significant loss of life.''
   The sailboat was discovered about 9 a.m. EST Saturday by the
Coast Guard cutter Escape, which was transporting nearly 100
Haitians intercepted the previous day back to the impoverished
nation, officials said.
   A rope was used to immobilize the rudder of the refugee vessel
and four other Coast Guard cutters were sent to the scene before
the Haitians surrendered about 120 miles southeast of Miami, Starks
said.
   The cutters Escape and Steadfast were traveling toward
Port-au-Prince today, Coast Guard officials said.
   Starks said none of the refugees had weapons and no one was
injured, although three ill Haitians were transported to the Coast
Guard base in Miami Beach. Some of the Haitians aboard the Escape
refused to eat in an act of sympathy with the other refugees, he
said.
   The standoff revealed the growing frustration driving record
numbers of refugees to seek Florida's shores, a Haitian leader said.
   ``This incident is just a hint of what could become common,''
said the Rev. Gerard Jean-Juste, director of the Haitian Refugee
Center in Miami and a spokesman for the city's Haitian community.
   ``Some of those on the boats are army defectors and will do just
about anything to keep from going back to Haiti,'' Jean-Juste said.
   Jean-Juste said the influx of Central American immigrants into
South Florida is fueling resentment among Haitians, who are
routinely returned to their homeland after being stopped at sea.
   Under Immigration and Naturalization Service policy, brief
hearings are held with refugees intercepted at sea and only those
deemed political asylum candidates are allowed to enter the United
States. Other so-called ``economic refugees'' are returned to their
native country.
   Only five of the more than 20,000 Haitians interviewed at sea
since 1981 have been brought into the country for asylum hearings.
This month, about 1,400 Haitians have been stopped at sea, more
than any other month in the eight-year interdiction program.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
