<FILEID>AP-NR-03-27-89 0345EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Korea     03-27 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea,0563</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutors Say Dissident Faces Arrest For Visiting North</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government prosecutors said today that
a dissident leader who made an unauthorized visit to communist
North Korea to discuss reuniting the two Koreas will be arrested if
he returns to Seoul.
   In a separate action, police detained 23 dissident writers and
supporters who tried to reach the North Korean border today for a
reunification meeting with communist delegates at the Panmunjom
truce site.
   Seoul officials had prohibited the meeting.
   Prosecutor Bae Jae-wook said the Rev. Moon Ik-hwan would face
prosecution under tough national security laws for making his
unauthorized visit to the north to meet top communist officials.
Moon could face up to 10 years imprisonment if convicted.
   Moon's surprise arrival Saturday in Pyongyang after a trip to
Japan and China shocked capitalist South Korea. The two Koreas are
bitter rivals who have clashed repeatedly, and their border is
sealed.
   South Korean officials criticized Moon for a speech he made in
Pyongyang describing North Korean leader Kim Il Sung as a
``respectable president.''
   Kim, who rules one of the world's most repressive police states,
is widely feared in the south for having started the Korean War.
Many South Koreans believe he still wants to conquer their country.
   Unification Minister Lee Hong-koo said Moon's unauthorized visit
was an attempt to undermine President Roh Tae-woo's efforts to
improve relations with North Korea. Lee said Moon's visit aided
North Korea by giving the impression that some South Koreans
support the Pyongyang government.
   South Korean dissidents, rejecting their government's efforts to
improve relations with the north, have been trying to start a
dialogue with the north on reuniting the peninsula. The dissidents
claim to speak for people in the south despite their lack of public
support.
   Pro-Western South Korea and communist North Korea were divided
at the end of World War II and fought the Korean war from 1950 to
1953. They are technically still at war because no peace treaty was
signed, and more than 1 million heavily armed soldiers face each
other across the 150-mile border.
   Roh ordered a major crackdown last week on radical groups after
charging they were attempting to stage a leftist revolution.
Government officials said Moon's visit was part of those attempts
to undermine the administration.
   Dissident groups calling for Roh's overthrow have been staging
violent protests, but they are not viewed as a major threat to the
government.
   Roh last week indefinitely postponed a promised referendum on
his performance, citing a threat of radical violence.
   Senior South Korean army commanders deplored Moon's visit at a
meeting today and demanded he be punished, Yonhap, the South Korean
news agency, reported.
   The main opposition parties all said today that Moon should not
have gone to North Korea without government permission.
   However, the United National Democratic Movement, the South's
main dissident alliance, expressed support for Moon at a press
conference.
   ``We hope he will return home with fruitful results,'' the
alliance said in a press statement.
   The two Koreas have been holding intermittent talks since last
August on improving relations. Little progress has been made
because each side has tended to push its own proposals and ignore
the other's initiatives.
</TEXT>
