<FIRST>r a PM-FlagArtRevenge     03-27 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Flag Art Revenge,0432</SECOND>
<HEAD>People Angry At U.S. Flag Exhibit Can Get Revenge</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos CX7, CX9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHERI PRASSO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People who were outraged over an art exhibit that
featured a U.S. flag on the floor now can get some measure of
revenge: They can walk on a likeness of the artist at another
exhibit.
   The new piece was put together by a junior high school art
teacher who was angered by the original by student ``Dread'' Scott
Tyler of the School of the Art Institute of Chicago.
   The protest exhibit features a life-size sketch of Tyler drawn
on cloth in the manner of a police outline of a homicide victim.
The cloth is on the floor and a U.S. flag hangs above it on a wall
of a small North Side museum.
   Viewers are encouraged to step on the sketch of Tyler's face
while they write comments on ``How to Display `Dread' Scott Tyler.''
   The original work, part of a minority students' exhibit that is
now closed, was titled ``What is the Proper Way to Display a U.S.
Flag?'' It featured a U.S. flag positioned on the floor in front of
a book asking viewers to write their opinions about how the flag
should be displayed.
   Tyler's display touched off several protests, including one
attended by 2,500 veterans and supporters that led to the arrests
of four people.
   Art Institute officials defended the flag display and the
student's right to freedom of expression. But veterans and
protesters succeeded in temporarily shutting down the exhibit
several times. It closed March 16 after a month of controversy.
   Tyler could not be reached for comment on the protest exhibit.
He has an unlisted telephone number.
   ``I was upset by seeing my flag on the floor,'' said Gary Mann,
33, the art teacher from suburban Deerfield. As he spoke, visitors
walked over his work at the cramped, storefront Vietnam Museum.
   One visitor to Mann's work, wrote, ``An artist he is not, this
Dread Scott. He is an unpatriotic snot. He knows not what this
country is about.''
   Vietnam Museum owner Joe Hertel said he contacted Mann and asked
him to exhibit the display at his museum after hearing news reports
on it.
   ``It showed contempt for the artist who showed contempt for the
flag,'' said Hertel, a Vietnam veteran.
   Mann, who said he graduated from the School of the Art Institute
in 1976, plans to move the exhibit to various Veterans of Foreign
Wars' halls around the state.
</TEXT>
