<FIRST>r i PM-Philippines     03-27 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines,0604</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aquino Says Communists Can Serve If Freely Elected</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Corazon Aquino said today
on the eve of nationwide village elections that pro-Communist
candidates who are voted into office in the balloting can serve if
they are freely and fairly chosen.
   The military claims the rebels will use the vote to expand their
base.
   Also today, the rebels claimed they have recovered from setbacks
suffered during Mrs. Aquino's administration, and police said three
men shot up the home of an anti-communist activist near Cebu,
killing three people, including the man's wife.
   On Tuesday, voters in the country's 42,000 villages, or
``barangays,'' will select about 287,567 local council members.
   The military claims the rebels are backing pro-Marxist
candidates in hopes of solidifying their control in thousands of
rural villages.
   Mrs. Aquino was asked if the government would prevent rebel
supporters from claiming council seats. The Communist Party of the
Philippines is banned, but Tuesday's balloting is supposed to be
non-partisan.
   ``Well, if they have been elected legitimately, there has been
no force, they will hold office,'' Mrs. Aquino told reporters. ``We
have to abide by the law.''
   Col. Gerardo Flores, intelligence chief of the Philippine
Constabulary, said the rebels hope to capture 60 percent of the
village council seats in areas under their control.
   The rebels claim to control about 8,500 villages nationwide. But
the Commission on Election puts the figure at about 2,800. The
difference is believed to be in definitions of ``control.''
   ``In remote, inaccessible areas, there is hardly any government
presence,'' said election commissioner Haydee Yorac. ``So the party
members are the ones who exercise the most serious influence.''
   Hilario Davide, chairman of the election commission, said troops
would be deployed in about 3,500 districts considered ``hot spots.''
   In a statement marking Wednesday's 20th anniversary of the
communist New People's Army, rebel Chief of Staff Romulo Kintanar
claimed a force of 30,000 fighters deployed in 65 of the
Philippines' 73 provinces, 800 of 1,500 cities and 12,000 villages
and neighborhoods.
   ``NPA units have largely recovered from setbacks in 1985 and
1986 and have reconstituted guerrilla formations which had been
reduced for a time,'' Kintanar said.
   Civilian and military authorities claim the rebels are losing
strength because of more effective counterinsurgency operations and
improvements in the Philippine economy.
   They also maintain that the rebels lost much of their appeal
following the February 1986 ouster of President Ferdinand Marcos'
authoritarian administration and the rise of Mrs. Aquino to power.
   Mrs. Aquino has vowed to crush the insurgents before her term
expires in 1992. The New People's Army was founded on March 29,
1969 by leftist intellectuals and remnants of the pro-Soviet HUK
guerrillas, who waged an unsuccessful insurgency in the 1950s and
1960s.
   Kintanar was captured in March 1987 but escaped last year from
the stockade at Manila's Camp Crame after attending a birthday
party for his former jailer.
   In Cebu, 350 miles south of Manila, police and witnesses said
gunmen late Sunday sprayed semi-automatic rifle fire on the home of
Rogelio Nara, 37, in the village of Kan-Irag in the mountains above
the city.
   Nara's wife and two male relatives were killed and two others
were wounded, including Nara's nine-year-old daughter, police said.
Nara is a member of the Movement for Democratic Reforms, one of
hundreds of government-backed anti-communist vigilante groups
operating nationwide.
   Police said the attackers could have been rebels or relatives of
a man killed by Nara several years ago.
</TEXT>
