<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     03-27 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up In Japan, Stocks Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose against the Japanese yen today,
while stock prices lost ground on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 132.30 yen, up 1.03 yen from last Friday's
close. The U.S. currency opened at 131.68 yen and moved in a range
of 131.67-132.30 yen.
   The dollar opened slightly higher than last Friday's close of
131.27 yen, but active buying of the dollar by insurance companies
pushed it further, currency dealers said.
   They attributed the dollar's bullishness to the market's reduced
wariness toward rising interest rates.
   ``There seem to be no strong incentive to sell the dollar right
now,'' said Masato Sanjo, a dealer at the Tokyo office of
Manufacture Hanover Trust. ``The bullish dollar appears to have
become more like a long-term trend.''
   Another currency dealer with the Bank of Tokyo said there was
some demand for the dollar in early trading but otherwise the
market was ``very quiet'' as most overseas markets were observing a
three-day Easter holiday from last Friday.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 20.14-point
loser last Friday, shed another 56.12 points, or 0.18 percent, to
close at 31,512.40.
   On the stock market, dealers said the anticipation of the
introduction of the capital-gain tax starting April 1 led to heavy
sale of shares, resulting in a lower Nikkei index.
   Investors currently pay a 0.55-percent securities tax when
selling shares, but from April 1, they will pay 1.3 percent in
taxes _ 1 percent in capital gain tax and 0.3 percent for the
securities tax.
   Also, in anticipation of the indictment of former chairan of
Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corp. for bribery charges in a
stock-trading scandal, NTT shares closed at an all time low of 1.53
million yen. Its previous low was 1.58 million marked on last
Wednesday.
   But dealers expressed optimism, saying market environments are
not as bad as the Nikkei indicates.
   ``The fact that Nikkei fell only less than 0.2 percent despite
all the bad news indicates the deep-down bullishness of the
market,'' said a dealer at a major brokerage in Tokyo. ``Once all
the bad news is out, it will be time for the spring rally.''
</TEXT>
