<FILEID>AP-NR-03-27-89 0601EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-InmateAbuse     03-27 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Inmate Abuse,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sheriff's Department To Comply With Grand Jury Recommendations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Sheriff's Department has agreed to comply
with grand jury recommendations for ending abuse of jail inmates by
a so-called ``Rambo Squad'' that allegedly stripped, chained and
beat inmates, a spokesman said.
   The grand jury investigated allegations by more than 100 people
who said they had been abused or held naked in jail cells after
being arrested for misdemeanor offenses which usually were
alcohol-related.
   No indictments were issued, but the panel's report, released
last week following a nine-month investigation, criticized San
Diego County Sheriff John Duffy and his top assistants for failing
to provide the leadership to stop a group of deputies at the El
Cajon jail from preying on inmates.
   The grand jury found that the deputies found ``delight in
cruelty to others.''
   The panel also cited coverups and mismanagement by jail
supervisors, and said many deputies looked the other way while
inmates were being assaulted or harassed.
   Department spokesman Lt. Alan Fulmer said Duffy has reviewed the
20-page report and ``there is absolutely nothing he disagrees
with.''
   ``He thinks all the recommendations are good, and he would like
to implement them as soon as possible,'' Fulmer said.
   The panel's recommendations include the creation of an
Inspections and Control Division; a strengthening of the
department's Internal Affairs Division; required filing of detailed
reports of physical confrontations between prisoners and deputies;
and tougher standards for the selection and performance of jail
training officers.
</TEXT>
