<FIRST>r a PM-SpringBreak     03-27 0194</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spring Break,0199</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teen Injured In Balcony Fall, Thousands Cited In Spring Break Revelry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALM SPRINGS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Abandoning hopes that raucous spring
break festivities might subside, police called in more patrols over
the Easter weekend, made hundreds of arrests and braced for a
second wave of vacationing students.
   ``We've got some tired officers,'' Sgt. Steve Harrison said
early today.
   Rest appears out of the question anytime soon as vacation
schedules call for a new load of college and high school students
this week, he said.
   ``USC (University of Southern California), Stanford and others
are heading into town apparently,'' Harrison said. ``We had hoped
it was over with.''
   The first phase of the annual rite of spring has already left
the desert resort town 110 miles southeast of Los Angeles littered
with beer bottles, cans and other trash, he said.
   During the 10-day period beginning March 17, three people died
in traffic accidents and a 19-year-old woman was injured when she
fell from the balcony of a hotel.
   Arrests reached 1,640 over the weekend. Charges ranged from
drunken driving to assault. Officers have handed out an estimated
6,000 traffic citations, Harrison said.
</TEXT>
