<FIRST>r a PM-EasterRdp     03-27 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Easter Rdp,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>Celebrants Hunt Eggs, Remember Homeless, Hostages</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Bede in 4th graf is cq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Children hunted for eggs and Americans paraded under mostly
sunny skies to celebrate Easter, while services around the nation
echoed with more somber calls to remember the homeless and U.S.
hostages in the Middle East.
   San Francisco's Glide Memorial United Methodist Church served a
home-cooked breakfast to about 100 homeless people and poor
children dressed up in frilly Easter dresses and stylish blue jeans
donated by the church. Afterward, they hunted for Easter eggs.
   ``It's all for the kids,'' said the Rev. Cecil Williams.
   Near Albany, N.Y., the Rev. Bede Ferrara, a Roman Catholic
priest who describes himself as a traveling Franciscan preacher,
set up a shrine in his home in Clifton Park for the U.S. hostages
in the Middle East.
   ``We have photos of each American hostage on display and the
number of days they've been in captivity. We have an empty basket
which symbolizes that their baskets are empty this Easter,'' he
said.
   A more light-hearted atmosphere swept along New York City's
Fifth Avenue, where thousands enjoyed sunny 60-degree weather and
promenaded in the annual Easter parade. Jacqueline Kerstens
attracted a crowd with a 6-pound, 4-foot-tall bonnet that was a
basket of silk flowers _ lilies, apple blossoms and forsythia.
   In the nation's capital, President and Mrs. Bush attended a
christening at St. Alban's Chapel for their latest grandchild,
Ashley Bush, who was born Feb. 7 to the Bushes' son Neil and his
wife, Sharon.
   In Dallas, crowds at the Biblical Arts Center walked through a
life-size reproduction of Paul's Gate at Damascus and Christ's tomb.
   ``Easter is about the resurrection of Christ and the fact that
he died for all of us who believe in him. It's not about the bunny
and the painted eggs,'' said Ronnie Roese, the non-denominational
center's director.
   Nonetheless, more than 20,000 people flocked to a farm in Homer,
Ga., to hunt for about 140,000 dyed hens' eggs and candy eggs in
what was said to be the world's largest Easter egg hunt.
   A California condor laid a 5-inch-long, 10-ounce Easter egg.
Officials at the Los Angeles Zoo spotted the blue egg shortly after
sunrise.
   ``What an Easter egg!,'' exclaimed zoo spokeswoman Deborah
Pollack. ``If fertile, God willing, it will hatch in 54 to 58
days.'' Only one of the endangered condors has ever been conceived
in captivity.
</TEXT>
