<FIRST>r a PM-FalseThreat     03-27 0179</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-False Threat,0183</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Arrested For Falsely Reporting Bomb On Pan Am Plane</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who falsely claimed he had placed a bomb
aboard a Pan American World Airways jet flying from New York to
London and demanded $1 million in ransom was arrested, police at
John F. Kennedy Airport said today.
   The man called the airport police information center Sunday
evening and told the operator he had placed a bomb on Pan Am Flight
102, said Port Authority Police Officer Sal Borgese.
   Borgese said the caller never gave a reason for the threat or
identified himself as belonging to any group.
   While an officer kept the caller on the line, police traced the
call to a pay telephone at the airport's Pan Am terminal, where
they found Scott Sasonkin, 23, Borgese said.
   Pan Am spokesman Jeff Kriendler said the caller later denied
putting a bomb on the plane and the flight was not affected.
   Sasonkin was being booked on charges of attempted grand larceny,
falsely reporting an incident and aggravated harassment, Borgese
said.
