<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0483 03-27 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0483,0453</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syrians, Christians Pound Each Other Around Beirut</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs to update casualties. Picks up 3rd graf pvs
``the rocket and artillery....''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian and Christian army gunners
hammered each other's positions in and around Beirut today after
random bombardment of the capital forced residents to spend the
Easter holiday underground.
   Police said three civilians were killed and 13 wounded in the
hostilities overnight and during the morning. The casualties raised
the toll to 97 dead and 339 wounded since the latest round of
fighting in Lebanon's 14-year-old civil war broke out March 8.
   The rocket and artillery barrages in the capital tapered off at
daybreak. But heavy duels resounded in the mountains overlooking
Beirut, police said.
   It was the fourth consecutive night that barrages on both
Christian east Beirut and Moslem west Beirut have confined
civilians to basements and bomb shelters.
   The Syrians and their allies have also ordered a blockade of
east Beirut and nearby Christian communities, home of about 1
million people.
   Syrian forces and allied Druse gunners pounded east Beirut with
rocket barrages of up to 60 rounds per minute during the night. The
bombardment set fires at a fuel tank at the Beirut port and the
city's main power plant, police said. The Christian army units
retaliated with barrages from 155mm howitzers.
   Until the damaged plant is repaired, authorities will be able to
provide electricity for just four hours a day.
   The fighting pits army Commander Gen. Michel Aoun's
predominantly Christian units against an alliance of Syrian troops
and militiamen of Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt's Progressive
Socialist Party.
   Aoun contends the Syrians, who intervened 13 years ago as
peacekeepers, have turned into an occupation force by taking sides
with Moslems and Druse. He heads a Christian military Cabinet in
Lebanon's divided government. Syrians back the rival Moslem
government.
   The Christian leader has declared a ``war of liberation'' to
drive out the 40,000 Syrian troops. He has vowed to fight on even
at the risk of destroying Beirut.
   Acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, who heads the Moslem Cabinet,
today rejected Aoun's accusations.
   ``The Syrian army entered Lebanon in 1976 at the request of the
then reigning Lebanese government. This request was later endorsed
by the Arab League, of which Lebanon is a founding member,'' Hoss
said.
   He said any demand for a Syrian pullout should be made by a
united Lebanese government ``which is not present at the moment.''
   The latest violence began after Aoun imposed a blockade on
milita-run ports. The militias skim taxes that would otherwise go
to the government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
