<FIRST>r a PM-AbortionProtests     03-27 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion Protests,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abortion Rallies Over, Operation Rescue Leader Jailed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUINN LOTA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 300 anti-abortion protesters
remained in jail this morning, where their leader claimed police
used excessive force in making arrests and accused the media of a
``pro-death'' bias.
   The Operation Rescue protesters spent Easter behind bars,
sometimes singing hymns, refusing to take the legal steps that
would have allowed them to leave jail because they wanted to
dramatize their cause.
   The group's jailed leader, Randall Terry, spent part of the day
calling journalists to complain that they failed to show pictures
of aborted fetuses that might show the public what abortion really
entails.
   He opened the New York-based group's Holy Week protests Thursday
by appearing at a news conference with a small, white coffin that
contained what he said was an aborted 19-week-old fetus. After
opening the coffin lid he left, challenging the media to televise
the remains.
   ``The media is the greatest perpetrator of this holocaust
because they're hiding the truth from the public,'' Terry said
Sunday. ``It's not a matter of taste. The majority of the media
elite are pro-death and reduce this to a war of words, and it's a
war of bodies, dead bodies.''
   The protesters are the latest of more than 21,000 to be arrested
nationally since 1987, mostly for blocking clinics where abortions
are performed.
   As part of their effort to focus attention on the Supreme
Court's reconsideration of its 1973 decision legalizing abortion,
252 men and at least 50 women stayed in jail Sunday by refusing to
provide their names to police or to sign misdemeanor trespassing
citations.
   Terry, a former car salesman, and three others could face more
serious charges: They remained jailed today for investigation of
felony conspiracy to encourage others to commit a crime.
   ``This felony charge is a joke,'' he said. ``How can you have a
felony conspiracy to commit a misdemeanor trespass? That's
ludicrous.''
   He alleged Los Angeles police used excessive force when they
arrested 750 protesters during a six-hour standoff outside a clinic
Saturday. More than 1,000 anti-abortion activists were arrested
during three days of protests in Cypress, Long Beach and Los
Angeles.
   Officers' treatment of protesters, he charged, ``was completely
uncalled for and unprofessional. You don't twist people's arms to
the point were they're screaming in pain and sticking two fingers
up their nose.''
   One demonstrator's arm and wrist were broken in a scuffle with
police Saturday, Operation Rescue said. Los Angeles police Cmdr.
William Booth said Sunday that the group was exaggerating the
incidents.
   Police Chief Daryl Gates said officers used a ``pain compliance
hold'' in the arrests. And he said he would ask the city attorney
to sue Operation Rescue for the $60,000 to $100,000 the
demonstration cost the city.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890327-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-27-89 0946EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Drugs-Surplus     03-27 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drugs-Surplus,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Reserve Bank Sees Surplus Due To Drug Trade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The cash surplus at the Federal Reserve Bank
here has jumped from $165 million in 1985 to $3.8 billion in 1988,
and authorities believe the 23-fold increase is largely because of
laundered drug money moving through banks.
   ``It is a good indicator that we are awash with dope money being
laundered through Los Angeles, not just from the Los Angeles area
but from elsewhere in the country,'' U.S. Attorney Robert Bonner
said.
   ``Staggering amounts of cash are being funneled into the Los
Angeles area for laundering here.''
   Despite hefty fines levied against some of the state's largest
financial institutions, drug officials say the illegal money is
being funneled into the Federal Reserve after being laundered
through banks.
   Laundering is the process of passing money through enough
transactions that it is hard to trace. It may arrive at a bank as a
legitimate business deposit. The money may then be transferred to
foreign bank accounts controlled by drug kingpins without
traffickers having to smuggle cash out of the country.
   Miami, which had a reputation of being the hub for drug
laundering, saw its Federal Reserve surplus drop from a high of $6
billion in 1985 to $4.8 billion in 1988, still the largest surplus
in the country.
   U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration spokesman Ralph Lochridge
said the trend ``validates Los Angeles as the new money-laundering
and drug financial center in the United States.''
   The Federal Reserve System is the nation's central bank,
managing the money supply by controlling how much cash member banks
must keep liquid instead of loaning out. About 40 percent of the
nation's banks belong to the Federal Reserve System.
   When deposits at a Federal Reserve district branch exceed the
branch's cash shipments back to its member banks, that district is
said to have a cash surplus.
   Only 10 of the 35 branches of the Federal Reserve reported cash
surpluses last year. After Miami and Los Angeles, the others are
Jacksonville, Fla., with a $1.9 billion surplus; San Antonio, $511
million; El Paso, Texas, $484 million; Nashville, Tenn., $399
million; Denver, $367 million; New Orleans, $118 million; Helena,
Mont., $45 million; and Salt Lake City, $15 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890327-0050 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-27-89 0954EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Turkey-Elections     03-27 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Turkey-Elections,0597</SECOND>
<HEAD>Premier's Party Suffers Big Defeat in Local Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EMEL ANIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Turgut Ozal's Motherland Party
suffered a crushing defeat in nationwide local elections, winning
only three mayoral races in Turkey's 67 provincial capitals,
unofficial returns showed today.
   The governing party finished third in the provincial assembly
elections behind the leftist Social Democrat Populist Party, the
chief opposition group, and the conservative True Path Party of
former six-time Premier Suleyman Demirel, according to nearly
complete tallies provided by state radio and the Anatolia news
agency.
   Opposition parties described Sunday's elections as a referendum
on Ozal's free-market economic policies. Ozal had said he would
quit if opposition gains were large enough to make it difficult for
him to govern.
   But today, Ozal said he would stay on until the next elections
scheduled for 1992. ``he nation gave us a mandate until 1992, we
will be serving the nation until then,''the 61-year-old premier
told a news conference.
   ``The people knew the party in power would not change as a
result of these elections. They wanted to give us a message: to
bring down inflation faster,'' Ozal said.
   He said ``A little warning was intended by the voters but it
went a bit too far.''
   Ozal promised changes in the Cabinet sometime this week.
   Voters elected more than 326,000 mayors, provincial assembly
members, city council members, village leaders and neighborhood
representatives.
   In the provincial assembly elections, the Social Democrats
gained 28 percent of the nationwide vote, and the True Path had
25.5 percent, the returns showed. Ozal's party was in third place
with 22 percent.
   Among the smaller parties, the Democratic Left Party of former
Premier Bulent Ecevit got 9 percent, the Moslem fundamentalist
Prosperity Party 9.5 percent, the Nationalist Labor Party 4.5
percent, the rightist Reformist Democracy Party 1 percent, and the
rest was scattered among independent candidates.
   Demirel said Ozal should quit because of the results.
   ``He said he would pack up and go, and if he is true to his
word, he should do so,'' Demirel told reporters. ``I am sure he
will not try to run the country on support based on 22 percent of
the votes.''
   Erdal Inonu, who heads the Social Democrat Populist Party, also
claimed a win over the Motherland Party.
   Inonu, a nuclear physics professor turned politician, declared,
``The people accomplished a real spring cleaning, making it clear
who they wanted to see in power.''
   Several Motherland members asked for early parliamentary
elections. ``Not early but immediate elections should be held,''
said Fahrettin Kurt, minister of energy.
   Five years ago in local assembly elections, Motherland gained 41
percent of the vote, the Social Democrat Populists won 22 percent,
and the True Path won 13 percent. The rest of the votes were
divided between three other parties.
   On Sunday, the Social Democrats won 30 mayorships out of 53
already decided; the True Path won 15 and the Motherland party won
three. In the last local elections, the Motherland Party captured
54 mayorships in the 67 provincial capitals. Also on the ballots
Sunday were mayor's races in 1,917 small towns.
   Social Democrat candidates ousted Motherland mayors in Turkey's
three largest cities: Istanbul, Ankara and Izmir.
   Political analysts attributed Ozal's loss to inflation, which
reached 75 percent last year, his family's high-spending lifestyle,
charges of nepotism, and allegations of corruption in high places.
   Ballots are counted by hand. Complete unofficial results are not
expected until Tuesday.
</TEXT>
