<HEAD>Reports Say Iran's Navy Seized Yacht</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NABILA MEGALLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Media reports said Iran's navy seized a
yacht with as many as five members of Kuwait's royal family and
four Britons aboard, but officials in Kuwait, Bahrain and Britain
denied knowledge of the incident.
   Diplomatic sources in Dubai said Iranians have told them the
vessel was taken when it strayed into Iranian waters, but that
``the boat and its occupants have been released.''
   Media reports said members of the Kuwaiti royal family were
aboard the boat, but one diplomatic source said he was told by an
Iranian diplomat that no Kuwaiti royal family members were aboard.
   Diplomatic sources told The Associated Press the boat had four
British male crew and technicians and two prominent Arabs. The
sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, would not elaborate
on their identity.
   Tehran made no public comment on the reports, which surfaced
Sunday in a report by the Kuwaiti newspaper Al-Anbaa.
   The newspaper reported the yacht was seized by the Iranians in
the Persian Gulf on Thursday while sailing from Bahrain to Kuwait.
   The Independent Television News of Britain quoted diplomatic
sources in Kuwait as saying the royal family members were Kuwaitis
and the four Britons were women.
   The British Foreign Office said: ``All our investigations and
inquiries have drawn a complete blank.''
   Asked whether that meant no yacht was seized, a Foreign Office
said: ``Not that we can tell.'' He spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Officials in Kuwait and Bahrain also denied knowledge of the
reported seizure.
   Shipping executives and fishermen in Kuwait have referred to
cases of ``piracy'' in which they say Iranians have captured at
least two expensive boats in recent months. The boats' occupants
reportedly were free unharmed.
  
