<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Liquor     03-27 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Liquor,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Will Decide Liquor-Labeling Issue in North Dakota Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to decide
whether states may impose labelng and reporting requirements on
liquor sold at U.S. military bases within their borders.
   The court said it will review a ruling that such North Dakota
regulation of liquor sold at two military bases in that state
violates federal policy.
   A North Dakota law requires all liquor sold in the state to be
distributed through a state-controlled system.
   State officials sought to require out-of-state liquor
distributors to put a label on each bottle sold at the Grand Forks
and Minot Air Force Bases. The labels were to say the liquor is for
consumption only at the military installations.
   The state also wanted suppliers to report monthly on how much
liquor they shipped into the state.
   The rules were designed to prevent liquor intended for the two
military enclaves from being sold elsewhere in North Dakota.
   The federal government challenged the regulations, arguing they
violated a federal policy aimed at assuring liquor sold at clubs
and stores on military bases would be purchased by the government
for the lowest possible price. Profits from the military base sales
are used to pay for recreational activities.
   Federal officials said it could cost the government $200,000 to
$250,000 more each year if the labeling and reporting regulations
were enforced in North Dakota. They said the rules would force them
to purchase more liquor from North Dakota distributors at higher
prices.
   The 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled last September that
the state regulations must give way to the federal policy.
   The appeals court rejected the state's argument that it was
empowered to impose the regulations by the 21st Amendment to the
Constitution, which repealed Prohibition and gave states sweeping
control over liquor distribution.
   ``We conclude that the 21st Amendment provides no basis for
regulating the means by which Congress has sought to order military
liquor procurement and to provide for the welfare and morale
activities of military personnel,'' the appeals court said.
   The National Beer Wholesalers' Association supported North
Dakota's appeal. The association said there is ``uncontradicted
evidence ... that North Dakota was seriously concerned about the
problem of diversion of liquor from military reservations.''
   The case is North Dakota vs. U.S., 88-926.
</TEXT>
