<FIRST>r i PM-China-Minister     03-27 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Minister,0427</SECOND>
<HEAD>China's Foreign Minister Defends Human Rights Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's foreign minister said today some U.S.
officials were ill-informed about human rights questions in China
and threatened progress toward close bilateral relations.
   On Sino-Soviet relations, meanwhile, Qian Qichen told reporters
that even after Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev visits China in
May, there will be some way to go before differences between the
two countries are resolved.
   Since diplomatic ties were formed a decade ago, relations
between the United States and China ``enjoy vast potential and the
prospects are very good,'' Qian said.
   But he warned against interference in Chinese internal matters
that he said ``was not in the interest of friendly relations.''
   Qian called for a ``new pattern'' of relations based on mutual
trust, and had sharp words for members of the U.S. Congress who
have criticized China's lack of democratic reform and its human
rights record in Tibet.
   ``A small number of people in the American Congress are actually
very ill-informed about the situation in Tibet. They have very
strong prejudice.''
   The Chinese government last week criticized both the European
Parliament and the U.S. Congress for statements over the
declaration of martial law in the Tibetan capital of Lhasa
following pro-independence riots there this month.
   Human rights, Qian said, are a matter of basic questions such as
providing adequate food and education and ``are inseparable with
the actual condition of the country involved.''
   He also said U.S. congressional criticisms of China's family
planning policies that try to keep couples from having more than
one child were ``fairly absurd.''
   The United States in recent years has withheld funds for U.N.
family planning programs on the grounds that money going to China
backs up strict birth control policies that have led to forced
abortions.
   Qian said China, which supports the anti-Vietnamese resistance
in Cambodia, backs the dispatch of a U.N. peacekeeping force after
Vietnam ends its 10-year occupation. But, he said, China is not
preparing to send peace troops to Cambodia.
   The question of Cambodia will be high on the agenda when
Gorbachev meets Chinese leaders in Beijing, Qian said.
   The summit, the first between the two countries in 30 years,
will normalize long-strained relations, Qian said, but doesn't mean
that all major obstacles to better relations will be removed.
   Soviet support for Vietnam's invasion of Cambodia is regarded by
China as the most serious obstacle to better ties between Beijing
and Moscow.
</TEXT>
