<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Gebbie     03-27 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Gebbie,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justices Let Stand Damage Award to Former Oregon Medical Examiner</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today let stand a $300,000
award won by Oregon's former chief medical examiner from the woman
who fired him following news reports that he had sold body parts to
finance parties in the morgue.
   The justices, without comment, refused to hear arguments by
Kristine Gebbie, administrator of the State Health Division, aimed
at overturning the award won by William J. Brady.
   A federal jury ruled that Gebbie deprived Brady of his
constitutionally protected liberty interests without due process of
law when she fired him in 1985.
   Brady had maintained a bank account, in his name but with the
knowledge of everyone in his office, for money paid for pituitary
glands and other body parts removed during autopsies in the state
coroner's office.
   The money was used for various amenities in the medical
examiner's office.
   When Gebbie announced Brady's firing on Oct. 3, 1985, she issued
a press release in which she said Brady had ``knowingly violated
public trust and confidence'' through his ``systematic 16-year
diversion of public funds.''
   In upholding the jury verdict last Oct. 31, the 9th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals said Brady presented undisputed evidence that
Gebbie charged him with:
   _Violating the public trust.
   _Diverting state funds for his own use.
   _Establishing a ``slush fund.''
   _Causing the state to be billed for toxicological reports made
in connection with private autopsies he performed.
   The appeals court added, ``There was sufficient evidence
presented from which a jury could reasonably infer that the charges
were both contested and false.''
   In the appeal acted on today, Oregon Solicitor General Virginia
Linder argued for Gebbie that the appeals court ruling places
government employers in an ``untenable position.''
   The appeal said the 9th Circuit court's ruling gives no clear
guidelines for ``government's responsiveness to the performance of
its high-level officials and its ability to speak to the public it
serves.''
   The appeal also contended that Gebbie was entitled to qualified
immunity from Brady's lawsuit because ``she acted in unquestioned
good faith and the law concerning liberty interests and
name-clearing hearings is far from settled.''
   The case is Gebbie vs. Brady, 88-1299.
</TEXT>
