<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Larsen     03-27 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Larsen,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Leaves Intact Dismissal of Suit Against Pennsylvania Newspapers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to review a
Pennsylvania judge's lawsuit against two newspapers that reported
on what was to have been a confidential state investigation of him.
   The court, without comment, let stand rulings that dismissed
state Supreme Court Justice Rolf Larsen's suit against The
Philadelphia Inquirer and The Pittsburgh Post-Gazette.
   As a result of various articles appearing in both newspapers
about Larsen, the state's Judicial Inquiry and Review Board began
an investigation in mid-1982.
   In his suit, Larsen said the articles portrayed him as being
involved in ``political activity, racism, favoritism and
influence-peddling.''
   Completed in May 1983, the state board's investigation
exonerated Larsen of any wrongdoing.
   During the investigation, both newspapers published reports
about the board's supposedly secret proceedings. Some articles even
contained excerpts of hearing transcripts.
   Those reports were the basis of Larsen's suit, in which he
charged the newspapers with obtaining the transcripts illegally and
publishing only selected excerpts that placed him in a false light.
   The suit, which sought monetary damages, also claimed that the
articles invaded Larsen's privacy and violated the confidentiality
provisions of state law.
   A state trial judge dismissed most of the lawsuit's counts, and
that dismissal was upheld by a state appeals court.
   The appeals court relied heavily on a 1978 ruling by the
nation's highest court in a Virginia case.
   In that decision, the justices said the free-press protections
in the Constitution's First Amendment mean newspapers cannot be
criminally punished for publishing truthful information about
secret governmental proceedings.
   The decision struck down a Virginia law that made it a crime to
report about a state judicial commission's confidential
investigations into judges' fitness to hold office.
   The Pennsylvania appeals court ruled that allowing Larsen's
civil suit would, like Virginia's criminal law, violate free-press
rights.
   ``The imposition of monetary damages (civil sanctions) can be
just as inimical to and an encroachment of one's First Amendment
guarantees as criminal sanctions,'' the state court said.
   The Pennsylvania Supreme Court refused to hear Larsen's ensuing
appeal last Oct. 31.
   In the appeal acted on today, lawyers for Larsen argued that the
state courts wrongly concluded that the newspapers' free-press
rights would be harmed if Larsen were allowed to sue over
violations of state confidentiality provisions.
   Lawyers for the newspapers urged the justices to reject the
appeal. They noted, among other things, that the state court
rulings left Larsen free to amend his complaint to explain his
assertion that confidential information was obtained ``illegally.''
   The case is Larsen vs. Philadelphia Newspapers, 88-1274.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
