<FILEID>AP-NR-03-27-89 1025EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-HeatWave     03-27 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Heat Wave,0225</SECOND>
<HEAD>Warmer Than Normal For Early Spring</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The central part of the nation is basking in temperatures more
like early summer than early spring as a pair of weather systems
pull air up from the Gulf of Mexico.
   Temperatures in the 70s and 80s, as much as 30 degrees warmer
than normal, were predicted today over the Great Lakes, the Ohio
Valley, the central half of the Mississippi Valley and the central
Plains.
   On Sunday, Fort Wayne, Ind., tied its record of 75 degrees and
Ottumwa, Iowa, tied its record of 78. Dodge City, Kan., hit a
non-record 85 degrees and Moline, Ill., hit a non-record 80. In
Chicago, it was 76, one degree shy of the record.
   But the warmth will gradually diminish and move eastward over
the next couple of days, with the central states cooling by 10 to
20 degrees and the East Coast warming, said Lyle Alexander of the
National Weather Service's public service unit in Kansas City, Mo.
   ``The eastern seaboard should be expecting temperatures around
70 through Friday, especially around the Washington area,'' he said
today.
   The warm air is being pumped northward by the clockwise flow
around a high pressure area off the central Atlantic Coast and the
counterclockwise flow around a low over Texas, he said.
</TEXT>
