<FIRST>u i PM-Yeltsin 2ndLd-Writethru a0485 03-27 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yeltsin, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0485,0575</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yeltsin Elected To Moscow Seat</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates throughout to recast, update to conform to developments,
provide results from election commission. No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Soviet-Elections, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maverick populist Boris N. Yeltsin savored his
political comeback today as election officials announced he had
trounced a Communist Party loyalist for Moscow's sole at-large seat
in the new national legislature.
   ``It's hard to say what my spirit is more full of, joy or
concern about what I realistically can do to help Muscovites,'' the
58-year-old Yeltsin told several hundred applauding workers at the
State Construction Committee, where he is first deputy chairman.
   Igor N. Orlov, chairman of Moscow's election commission, said
Yeltsin won 89.4 percent of the vote Sunday. His opponent, Yevgeny
Brakov, received 6.9 percent of the vote.
   Yeltsin, who was ousted as Moscow Communist Party boss in 1987,
has accused the party's elite of trying to discredit him and had
said he feared votes might be tampered with to cheat him out of
victory.
   The former protege of President Mikhail S. Gorbachev campaigned
against the privileges afforded high-ranking Soviet officials and
called for faster reforms to improve living standards for everyone.
   His opponent, Brakov, the 51-year-old director of the ZIL
limousine plant, has carefully followed the party line in most
matters. The cars made at his factory are a prized perquisite of
high-ranking officials.
   Brakov had said his top priority is to end food shortages by
providing more machinery to farmers and improving storage and
processing facilities.
   Large pro-Yeltsin rallies were held in the capital in the
closing days of the campaign and the former Moscow party leader
became something of a symbol for people expressing a desire for
truly representative government.
   ocal Moscow election officials spent all night counting votes
after Sunday's election for the new Congress of People's Deputies _
the country's first contested elections in more than 70 years.
   ``We have been sitting and waiting since last evening for the
final votes; we are unshaven and have had no sleep,'' Viktor
Kubivsky, a member of Moscow's Volgograd district, said by
telephone.
   Andrei Rudyakov, a city council member, said the votes,
initially counted at local election districts, were being recounted
at the city election headquarters and the information was fed into
computers for final tabulation.
   He said representatives of Yeltsin and Brakov were at the
council building to oversee the recount.
   Of more than 2,000 Soviets interviewed by Western correspondents
at polling places after the voting, 1,734 were for Yeltsin and 162
for Brakov. Others either refused to disclose how they voted or
expressed opposition to either candidate.
   After casting his ballot, Yeltsin claimed many Soviets were
worried about voting fraud, and he complained that the elections
were not completely democratic.
   ``People are worried about the election results, worried that
there will be deviations at election stations during vote
counting,'' he told reporters. ``Everything is troubling them.''
   He said the campaign was ``not fully democratic'' but was a
``big step forward'' from previous one-candidate balloting. He said
the real test of democracy will be whether the vote count is fair.
   Gorbachev, who brought Yeltsin into Communist Party leadership
in 1985 and two years later oversaw his ouster on charges of making
political mistakes and displaying personal ambition, said criticism
of party officials is normal during campaigns.
</TEXT>
