<FIRST>r i PM-GandhiInquiry     03-27 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gandhi Inquiry,0539</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Releases Report On Gandhi Killing, Aide</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NILOVA ROY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today released a report
that accused an aide to Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi of links to the
assassination of his mother. Officials said investigators later
found the aide was not involved.
   The findings of a special commission report on Prime Minister
Indira Gandhi's 1984 slaying were withheld for three years, but a
newspaper account of the report prompted opposition legislators to
demand its release.
   When Rajiv Gandhi initially refused, opposition legislators
walked out of Parliament and some were suspended for a week for
misbehavior.
   The commission report, released to Parliament, accused Rajendra
Kumar Dhawan, Mrs. Gandhi's personal secretary, of facilitating the
assassination. But it added: ``The possiblity of someone else being
involved along with Mr. Dhawan cannot be excluded.''
   A government memorandum also released today said investigators
had checked the accusations and found Dhawan ``had no hand in the
conspiracy for the assassination of Mrs. Gandhi and that there was
nothing to indicate that Mr. Dhawan was in any way involved in the
crime or conspiracy.''
   Dhawan, 52, left his post shortly after Mrs. Gandhi's death but
returned to government last month as a key adviser to Rajiv Gandhi.
He was not immediately available for comment.
   Mrs. Gandhi was shot in the garden of her New Delhi residence by
two Sikh bodyguards as she walked to a television interview.
   One of the Sikhs, Beant Singh, was shot and killed by other
bodyguards minutes after the assassination, and the other, Satwant
Singh, was convicted of murder and hanged on Jan. 6. A third Sikh,
Kehar Singh, was convicted of conspiracy and also hanged.
   In releasing the report to Parliament, Home Minister Buta Singh
said another special investigating team also had ``unraveled a
conspiracy.'' He said additional charges would be filed, but did
not say when or against whom.
   According to the report, the commission did not rule out
involvement of an unspecified foreign agency that might have used
the assassins ``as unwitting instruments.''
   India has long accused neighboring Pakistan of training and
arming Sikh militants. Pakistan has denied the charge.
   Parliament passed a resolution in 1986 allowing the government
to withhold the report in the interest of national security. But on
March 14, the Indian Express newspaper published parts of the
report that alleged Dhawan lied during questioning and gave
unconvincing explanations about entries in his diary, including the
name of one of Mrs. Gandhi's assassins.
   Gandhi released the report only after members of his Congress
Party threatened to do so.
   The government says Mrs. Gandhi was killed in revenge for an
army raid she ordered on the Golden Temple in Amritsar, the holiest
Sikh shrine.
   At least 1,200 people, many of them Sikhs, were killed in the
June 1984 raid, which was aimed at ousting Sikh extremists who had
turned the shrine into an armed fortress.
   Sikh militants began fighting in 1982 for an independent
homeland.
   Sikhs, who comprise 2 percent of India's 880 million people,
claim discrimination by the Hindus, who make up 80 percent of the
population.
</TEXT>
