<FIRST>r i PM-Iran-Execution     03-27 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Execution,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rajavi's Sister Reportedly Executed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's main rebel opposition group said
today that the sister of its leader, Massoud Rajavi, has been
executed after being tortured in an Iranian prison.
   Tehran had no immediate comment on the allegation.
   In a statement sent to The Associated Press in Nicosia, the
Mujahedeen Khalq, or the People's Warriors, said Monireh Rajavi was
arrested with her husband, Asghar Nazemi, in 1982.
   The statement said the couple's only offense was that the woman
was the sister of Rajavi, who in addition to being the Mujahadeen
Khalq's leader, also is commander of the National Liberation Army,
a coalition of Iranian dissident factions based in Iraq.
   It said Nazemi was executed in 1985 and his wife was tortured
for several years before being executed. She was 38 years old, the
statement said.
   The rebels did not identify the prison where she was held or
give the date and method of the alleged execution. Iranians usually
execute women by firing squads. Men are usually hanged.
   The Mujahedeen Khalq statement said the couple has two daughters
but it did not say where they live or how old they are.
   The London-based human rights group, Amnesty International, as
well as other human rights organizations and some governments have
condemned Iran for executing thousands of political prisoners since
August. In that month authorities began a crackdown against
dissidents after a cease-fire halted eight years of war with Iraq.
   The Tehran government has said most people executed recently
were drug traffickers.
</TEXT>
