<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Chaplain 1stLd-Writethru a0503 03-27 0707</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Chaplain, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0503,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Lets Stand Iowa Ruling on Hospital Chaplain</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts grafs 15-24, In other action, with other cases.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today let stand a ruling
that a public hospital does not violate the constitutionally
required separation of church and state by having a chaplain on its
payroll.
   The court, without comment, refused to hear an appeal by three
Iowa atheists who said taxpayers should not be forced to fund a
chaplain's salary at a county-run hospital.
   The 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals last September upheld the
employment of a chaplain at Polk County's Broadlawns Medical Center
in Des Moines.
   Three avowed atheists _ Larry Henry Carter, his daughter,
Courtney, and Maurice LaBelle _ said their rights were violated
because the government was sponsoring religious activity.
   The Supreme Court ruled in 1983 that paying chaplains to lead
daily prayers in Congress and state legislatures does not violate
the Constitution. The court cited a long tradition, 200 years old
in the case of Congress, to support its ruling.
   The Iowa atheists noted that the chaplain at Broadlawns, Maggie
Alzeno Rogers, was hired in 1985 and her duties are more than
ceremonial.
   A deacon of the United Church of Christ, Ms. Rogers counsels
patients, their families and hospital workers and conducts
religious services and Bible study classes at the hospital. She is
paid $23,000 a year.
   The 8th Circuit court said her duties serve a secular purpose,
enhancing the hospital's ``wholistic treatment approach.''
   ``The purpose of the chaplaincy was the same as that of the
hospital generally, to help patients get well or at least to
provide the best care possible for those who would not get well,''
the appeals court said.
   It added that there was evidence Ms. Rogers' presence did not
advance religion unconstitutionally because she refrained from
proselytizing _ seeking religious converts.
   The appeals court also said Ms. Rogers may have reduced
entanglement between the church and state at the hospital because
there is less need for hospital officials to supervise volunteer
chaplains who worked at Broadlawns before she was hired.
   It is part of Ms. Rogers' job to make sure that the volunteer
chaplains are not proselytizing, the appeals court said.
   It also noted that many patients at the hospital are committed
involuntarily or are prisoners treated there. Comparing Ms. Rogers
to a military chaplain, the appeals court said many patients would
have no alternative religious counseling if she were not available.
   The appeals court said, however, that Ms. Rogers should be
permitted to give only secular counseling to hospital employees.
   In other action, the court:
   _ Said it will restudy how far states may go in limiting a
jury's discretion to choose life or death for convicted murderers.
   The court agreed to decide whether Pennsylvania's death penalty
law violates the Constitution by improperly limiting jury
discretion.
   Pennsylvania's death penalty statute says: ``The verdict must be
a sentence of death if the jury unanimously finds at least one
aggravating circumstance ... and no mitigating circumstance.''
   _ Refused to review a Pennsylvania judge's lawsuit against two
newspapers that reported on what was to have been a confidential
state investigation of him.
   The court, without comment, let stand rulings that dismissed
state Supreme Court Justice Rolf Larsen's suit against The
Philadelphia Inquirer and The Pittsburgh Post-Gazette.
   _ Agreed to decide whether states may impose labeling and
reporting requirements on liquor sold at U.S. military bases within
their borders.
   The court said it will review a ruling that such North Dakota
regulations of liquor sold at two military bases in that state
violates federal policy.
   _ Let stand a $300,000 award won by Oregon's former chief
medical examiner from the woman who fired him following news
reports that he had sold body parts to finance parties in the
morgue.
   The justices, without comment, refused to hear arguments by
Kristine Gebbie, administrator of the State Health Division, aimed
at overturning the award won by William J. Brady.
   A federal jury ruled that Gebbie deprived Brady of his
constitutionally protected liberty interests without due process of
law when she fired him in 1985.
   The chaplain case is Carter vs. Broadlawns Medical Center,
88-1286.
</TEXT>
