<FIRST>u a PM-HahnMinister     03-27 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hahn Minister,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>Onetime Jessica Hahn Minister Gets Six-Month Jail Sentence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH EDWARDSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Eugene Profeta, the preacher
Jessica Hahn said she turned to for solace after her sexual
encounter with deposed PTL leader Jim Bakker, was sentenced today
to six months in jail for witness tampering and tax charges.
   Hahn had helped put together the case against Profeta after
being promised immunity from prosecution.
   Under a plea-bargain agreement, the Long Island minister also
got five years' probation and was also ordered to pay about $26,000
in back taxes, interest and fines. He will be required to stay away
from Hahn, his former church secretary.
   Profeta, 52, was sentenced this morning by state Supreme Court
Justice Joseph Harris, who denied a request from Profeta's lawyer,
Stephen Scaring, that the minister be sentenced to community
service instead of a jail term.
   In January, just before his trial was to begin, Profeta entered
a surprise guilty plea to two of 18 charges against him. He
admitted he tried to get Hahn to lie to the grand jury about his
financial dealings and filed a false 1986 income tax return.
   Hahn, Profeta's onetime secretary, has said she and he became
lovers after her sexual encounter with Bakker in 1980 because she
was emotionally upset about the experience.
   Two years ago, revelations about the encounter and the money
paid to Hahn afterward to keep quiet about it toppled Bakker from
his PTL ministry.
   Under his plea bargain agreement with state Attorney General
Robert Abrams, charges that Profeta had skimmed church funds were
dropped. Also, tax evasion charges against his wife, Glenda, were
dismissed.
   About 150 people from Profeta's congregation made the trip from
Long Island to Albany to show support for the minister. Some sat in
the hallway outside the courtroom crying while others shouted
``Praise the Lord!''
   He preached to his Long Island ministry on Easter Sunday, after
the judge agreed to delay sentencing to allow him to appear there
on the holiday.
</TEXT>
