<FIRST>r i PM-Afghanistan     03-27 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels Say 53 Soldiers Killed, Five Aircraft Shot Down</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem guerrillas killed 53 Afghan
army troops and shot down five aircraft in fighting around
Afghanistan's strategic eastern city of Jalalabad, the insurgents
claimed today.
   However, Mohammad Nabi Amani, an Afghan government spokesman in
Kabul, said 190 insurgents died in the fighting around Jalalabad
and that two government soldiers and three civilians were killed.
   The contradicting claims could not be independently reconciled.
   The guerrilla-run Afghan News Agency said 53 communist troops
died, 98 were wounded and five deserted in heavy fighting since
Saturday. Insurgents shot down four helicopters and one airplane
and captured several posts north of Jalalabad, the agency claimed.
   It gave no estimate of guerrilla casualties.
   The guerrillas said heavy fighting continued around the city of
Jalalabad, the airport to the southeast and in suburbs to the
north. It said the Afghan air force has retaliated with heavy
bombing, causing many high civilian casualties.
   Jalalabad is the target of the guerrillas' first major offensive
since Feb. 15, the date Soviet troops ended nine years of
involvement in the Afghan war. Afghan government forces hold the
country's key cities but guerrillas reportedly control about 90
percent of the countryside.
   The guerrillas are fighting to oust the communist government and
establish an Islamic republic of Afghanistan.
   Afghan officials claim that Pakistani troops, and U.S. and Saudi
Arabian military advisers, are fighting with the Pakistan-based
guerrillas.
   All three countries supply the guerrillas but have denied that
their military personnel are fighting in Afghanistan.
</TEXT>
