<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Lucan     03-27 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Lucan,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pathologists Checking Skeleton Found Near Place Lord Lucan Last Seen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEACHY HEAD, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pathologists today examined a human
skeleton found near the place Lord Lucan last was seen alive
following the murder of his children's nanny more than 14 years ago.
   But Sussex police said they thought it unlikely the remains were
those of the missing earl. ``I would treat that with a great deal
of skepticism,'' a police officer said, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   Police said until tests are completed on the skeleton, they will
not know the age and sex of the person, the cause of death or how
long ago it occurred.
   The skeleton was discovered Saturday in thick undergrowth on the
Beachy Head coastal promontory.
   Lucan was last seen alive at Uckfield, on Britain's south coast,
Nov. 7, 1974, the day Sandra Rivett was battered to death and Lady
Lucan was attacked at the Lucan family's London home. A car he
borrowed was found abandoned at Newhaven, near Beachy Head, 18
miles south of Uckfield.
   The police believe Lucan killed the nanny in a dark basement,
mistaking her for his estranged wife. They believe he then attacked
Lady Lucan when he discovered his error.
   Five days later, Scotland Yard issued a murder warrant for
Lucan's arrest, the first ever for a British peer.
   At an inquest, Lady Lucan accused her husband of being the man
who attacked her, and a jury found him guilty of murder.
   Lucan has been reported alive in various parts of the world, but
police have not located him. Many believe Lucan killed himself.
</TEXT>
