<FIRST>r w PM-DoubleTransplant 1stLd-Writethru a0494 03-27 0501</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Double Transplant, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0494,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Recipent of First Heart-Pancreas Transplant Recuperating</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs pvs 13th graf, ``The pancreas,'' with 2 grafs to elaborate
on diabetes-heart disease connection</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A longtime diabetic whose pancreas had
virtually destroyed his heart has been given another chance to live
after doctors transplanted both organs in what is believed to be
the first such operation ever.
   Barry Katz, 45, was listed in serious condition today at the
Washington Hospital Center, and a spokeswoman said he was given an
80 percent chance of surviving a year.
   But before the surgery Saturday, the Silver Spring, Md.,
physicist's chances of living even a week were slim.
   ``He was slipping away,'' his wife Kay said. ``When you see a
loved on slipping away, you grab at anything that can help him ...
I knew this was it. This was his last chance.''
   Katz's body has shown no signs of rejecting the organs, doctors
said. And if all continues to go well, he could leave the hospital
within weeks and eventually return to work as a senior scientist
for the Pentagon's Strategic Defense Initiative program, they said.
   Katz had undergone heart bypass surgery seven years ago, but the
organ had begun deteriorating again over the past several months.
He was hospitalized a week before a local donor was found.
   ``This is very fast,'' said Lori E. Brigham of the Washington
Regional Transplant Consortium. ``He was very, very fortunate in
terms of timing.'' Doctors refused to identify the donor.
   Katz's doctors decided to transplant his pancreas as well as his
heart because they believed his severe diabetes would make
management of a new heart difficult or impossible.
   Although the hospital does not have permission from the District
of Columbia's State Health Planning and Development Agency to
transplant the pancreas, surgeons went ahead with the double
transplant anyway, fearing Katz would die if they waited.
   ``To our knowledge it's the first (heart-pancreas transplant)
ever done,'' said hospital spokeswoman Sarah Dodge.
   Dr. Hans W. Sollinger, a Wisconsin surgeon considered one of the
leading experts in pancreas transplants, was flown in by private
jet Saturday morning. The procedure, which was divided into
separate operations for each transplant, lasted the entire day.
   ``Everything proceeded wonderfully,'' said Dr. Jimmy A. Light, a
member of the surgical team. ``The pancreas is working, and we
think his diabetes is cured.''
   The pancreas is supposed to produce insulin, the hormone that
regulates the body's metabolism of sugar. When the organ doesn't
function properly, patients develop diabetes, and often have to
rely on insulin injections and constant monitering to survive.
   ``Diabetes can destroy the vascular system,'' said Ms. Dodge.
``Severe heart disease is a complication of diabetes.'' The
one-year survival rate for patients receiving a new pancreas has
been about 50 percent, compared with 85 percent for other organs,
Light said.
   But improvements in management of anti-rejection drugs for the
pancreas should improve Katz's outlook, making his chances of
surviving one year about 80 percent, doctors said.
</TEXT>
