<FIRST>r w BC-ScotusAt-a-Glance     03-27 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Scotus At-a-Glance,380</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are highlights of actions
taken Monday by the Supreme Court.
   
   HOSPITAL CHAPLAIN
   
   The court let stand a ruling that a public hospital does not
violate the constitutionally required separation of church and
state by having a chaplain on its payroll.
   The court, without comment, refused to hear an appeal by three
Iowa atheists who said taxpayers should not be forced to fund a
chaplain's salary at a county-run hospital.
   The case is Carter vs. Broadlawns Medical Center, 88-128
   
   DEATH PENALTY
   
   The court said it will restudy how far states may go in limiting
a jury's discretion to choose life or death for convicted murderers.
   The court agreed to decide whether Pennsylvania's death penalty
law violates the Constitution by improperly limiting jury
discretion.
   Pennsylvania's death penalty statute says: ``The verdict must be
a sentence of death if the jury unanimously finds at least one
aggravating circumstance ... and no mitigating circumstance.''
   The case is Blystone vs. Pennsylvania, 88-6222.
   
   JUDGE`S LAWSUIT
   
   The court refused to review a Pennsylvania judge's lawsuit
against two newspapers that reported on what was to have been a
confidential state investigation of him.
   The court, without comment, let stand rulings that dismissed
state Supreme Court Justice Rolf Larsen's suit against The
Philadelphia Inquirer and The Pittsburgh Post-Gazette.
   The case is Larsen vs. Philadelphia Newspapers, 88-1274.
   
   LIQUOR
   
   The court agreed to decide whether states may impose labeling
and reporting requirements on liquor sold at U.S. military bases
within their borders.
   The court said it will review a ruling that such North Dakota
regulations of liquor sold at two military bases in that state
violates federal policy.
   The case is North Dakota vs. U.S., 88-926.
   
   MEDICAL EXAMINER
   
   The court let stand a $300,000 award won by Oregon's former
chief medical examiner from the woman who fired him following news
reports that he had sold body parts to finance parties in the
morgue.
   The justices, without comment, refused to hear arguments by
Kristine Gebbie, administrator of the State Health Division, aimed
at overturning the award won by William J. Brady.
   A federal jury ruled that Gebbie deprived Brady of his
constitutionally protected liberty interests without due process of
law when she fired him in 1985.
   The case is Gebbie vs. Brady, 88-1299.
</TEXT>
