<FIRST>u a PM-ManchinImpeachment     03-27 0371</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Manchin Impeachment,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>W.Va. House Panel Recommends Impeachment Articles Against State Treasurer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By A.V. GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state House Judiciary Committee
today formally sent to the full House articles of impeachment
against Treasurer A. James Manchin stemming from losses of $279
million in a fund under Manchin's control in 1987.
   The committee voted 17-7 to recommend the impeachment after
adding two additional articles to the 16 it voted for last
Wednesday.
   The popular, flamboyant Manchin, 61, is in his second term as
state treasurer. He is a Democrat, and his party also controls the
House of Delegates and state Senate.
   House Speaker Chuck Chambers said the body could vote on
impeachment as early as Wednesday. If it passes the House, the case
would then go to the Senate for a trial.
   Senate President Larry Tucker, anticipating that a majority of
the House will vote to impeach Manchin, has told his colleagues to
be prepared to hear the case in May and estimated the trial would
take three to four weeks.
   The last time a West Virginia treasurer was impeached and
removed from office was in 1876.
   Also today, the House Judiciary Committee then voted 22-3 to
censure state Auditor Glen Gainer for his role in the losses.
   The articles recommend that Manchin be impeached for
maladministration, incompetence, neglect of duty and high crimes
and misdemeanors for his role in the investment fund losses and for
conspiring to cover them up.
   The two articles added today accuse him of putting an
unqualified person in control of the state's investment portfolio
after two previous treasury employees left and having the
treasurer's office charge a service fee for handling investments in
the fund.
   Manchin, Gainer, and former Gov. Arch Moore made up the Board of
Investments when the losses occurred in the consolidated investment
fund. The board had general supervisory control over the fund.
Manchin's office had direct investment powers.
   Committee members were angered by statements Gainer made to them
during 10 days of testimony on the impeachment issue. They believed
he should have been more active in the fund's supervision. Moore
left office in January after being unseated by Gaston Caperton in
last year's general election.
</TEXT>
