<HEAD>New International Airport Opens in Minsk</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new international airport opened Monday in the
Byelorussian capital of Minsk, halfway between Moscow and Warsaw,
Tass reported.
   The new airport, Minsk-2, was constructed ``to meet the rapid
growth of passenger traffic brought about by the development of
foreign tourist travel and direct business contacts,'' the official
news agency said.
   First flights from the airport will be to East Germany, and
service will expand to Warsaw later this month. Charter flights
will be added later this year, the news agency said.
   ``The new airport increases flying safety,'' Tass said. ``If
Moscow airport is declared closed due to unfavorable weather
conditions, our Minsk-2 will be available as a reserve haven.''
