<SECOND>AM-BRF--Korea-Warship,0166</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seoul Says North Korean Warship Violates South Korea's Waters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A North Korean navy warship violated
South Korea's territorial waters in the Yellow Sea, the Defense
Ministry announced Monday.
   There was no military clash in the brief confrontation Saturday,
a spokesman for the ministry said. The North Korean vessel changed
its course and retreated when South Korean ships approached, he
said.
   The North Korean warship apparently sailed into South Korean
waters in an effort to identify a Japanese merchant ship that was
being checked by South Korean naval craft, the spokesman said.
   The Japanese ship, the 200-ton Yakusimaru, was sailing to North
Korea's western port of Haeju when it was ordered to stop for
inspection by the South Korean navy, he said.
   South Korea will lodge a protest with North Korea through the
Korean Military Armistice Commission, a watchdog of the 1953 Korean
War truce accord, operating in the border village of Panmunjom, he
said.
