<DOCNO> AP890327-0077 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-27-89 1233EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-TrailofTears Bjt   03-27 0740</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trail of Tears, Bjt,0762</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cherokees Observe 150th Anniversary of End of Tragic Removal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIL BROYLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAHLEQUAH, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It is no celebration the Cherokees plan
this week, although spring brings a special joy in the adopted
homeland where the tribe ended its greatest tragedy 150 years ago.
   In the winter of 1838-39, thousands of Cherokees died on a
forced march from their homes in the southeastern United States to
what is now northeastern Oklahoma. The path is known as the Trail
of Tears.
   On Friday and Saturday, the tribe observes the sesquicentennial
of that time. The last of 14 groups of Cherokees escorted by
federal troops arrived in late March 1839.
   Wilma Mankiller, chief of the nation's second-largest Indian
tribe, said Cherokees decided to mark the sesquicentennial after
some hesitation because of the sensitivity that lingers over those
days.
   The tribe settled on a commemoration only after wagon hobbyists
not affiliated with the tribe re-traced the Trail of Tears last
fall. Ms. Mankiller noted most Cherokees made the trek by foot,
some in shackles.
   ``It wasn't a friendly removal,'' she said.
   ``I think there are a number of people who have concerns,'' said
Ms. Mankiller, chief since 1985. ``I think it's healthy for us to
look back (and show) respect for our ancestors.
   ``It helps to place our present problems in a historical
context. But I certainly understand the concerns of people about
looking at this issue.
   ``I think for us it's a very solemn, very emotional time. We
look at it as something that happened to our family.''
   Ms. Mankiller said the observance provides ``a chance to do some
public education about our history.''
   ``There's so little accurate information about what modern
American Indians are like. There's a vacuum,'' she said.
   Most Americans know only the Indians they see depicted in John
Wayne movies, Ms. Mankiller said.
   In the tribe's capital of Tahlequah, a university city of
10,000, there will be speeches, story-telling and flute playing. A
tree will be planted in honor of the estimated 4,000 Cherokees who
died along the trail.
   Donated hogs will be cooked in huge black kettles on the grounds
of a historic home. There will be free corn bread and beans, eggs
and wild onions.
   ``This is what the Indians of the hills eat ... whatever food
they could find and forage,'' said John Ketcher, deputy chief of
the tribe, who remembers when his own relatives would not discuss
the tragedy.
   Those forced westward included Cherokees who owned plantations
and had assimilated into the dominant white culture. But the tribe
had its own government and its own written language when President
Andrew Jackson ordered the Cherokees removed from land sought by
white settlers.
   Ketcher's great-grandparents were on the trail, uprooted from
northern Georgia.
   ``I never did hear about the trail when I was growing up _
nothing, not anything,'' Ketcher said. ``Was it just an attempt to
shut it out _ like it never happened?
   ``Many of them would just prefer to forget the whole thing,
because it was such a tragic event in the lives of our people.''
   Ms. Mankiller, who keeps busy with speaking engagements
nationwide, said the sesquicentennial should remind tribal members
of their resiliency.
   ``It is intended to be sort of a solemn occasion .... But also
at the same time look back about what happened after the Trail of
Tears. We were able to bounce back in the 1800s,'' she said.
   A commemorative plaque depicts a legendary Phoenix bird arising
from ashes to assume the form of a Cherokee warrior.
   The tribe arrived in Oklahoma politically divided over removal.
But the tribe rebounded to re-form a government, enforce tribal
laws and erect government buildings that still stand. It
established some of the first schools west of the Mississippi,
including a school for women.
   ``Lots of people in Oklahoma believe that Oklahoma history began
with the Land Run (of 1889). We had been here for a couple of
generations. We had made this area hospitable. We had settled it,''
she said.
   Today the Cherokee Nation's concerns focus on education, health
care and employment, Ms. Mankiller said. Cherokee Nation Industries
has a booming greenhouse operation in Tahlequah, a defense
contracting plant in Stilwell and industrial tracts, but economic
development in the rural areas remains a major concern.
   ``I share that frustration, I think, with every other small town
in America,'' Ms. Mankiller said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
