<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Japan-Soviet     03-27 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Japan-Soviet,0198</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan TV Employee Will Fly on Soviet Space Station</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Japanese television network has reached agreement
with Soviet authorities for one of its employees to go aboard the
Soviet space station Mir by the end of 1991, a network official
said Monday.
   The agreement was signed between Kiichi Nakamura, of the Tokyo
Broadcasting System, Inc., and Oleg Firsyk, vice president of
Glavkosmos, the Soviet commercial space agency, said the official,
who refused to be identified.
   To mark the network's 40th anniversary, one of its employees
will be flown to the space station aboard a Soyuz spaceship. During
the six-day stay aboard the Mir, live broadcasts of the staffer's
activities will shown daily in Japan, he said.
   The official refused to say how much the broadcaster will pay
the Soviets.
   Employees at the network are signing up to be considered for the
flight. ``Everybody wants to go,'' said one reporter.
   The Mir station was launched in 1986 and has a capacity of six.
   Three Japanese astronauts are undergoing training in the United
States, and one is scheduled to board a U.S. space shuttle flight
by July 1991.
