<FILEID>AP-NR-03-27-89 1234EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-HomeSales     03-27 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Home Sales,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rising Interest Rates Dampen Home Sales</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Fed-Interest Rates Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of existing homes fell in February for
the second straight month as higher interest rates pushed buyers
out of the market, a real estate trade group said Monday.
   Sales of existing single-family homes dropped 3.1 percent last
month to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 3.44 million units,
the slowest pace since the 3.38 million rate recorded last March,
the National Association of Realtors reported.
   February's decline followed an even sharper 9.4 percent sales
drop in January.
   The Realtors attributed the recent weakness in sales to the
Federal Reserve Board's yearlong campaign to drive up interest
rates in an effort to slow the economy and ease inflationary
pressures.
   ``The Fed's credit stance is working,'' said Realtors President
Ira Gribin. ``Interest rates are pushed up and buyers are pushed
out.''
   Fixed-rate home mortgages last month averaged between 10.55
percent and 10.78 percent, according to the Federal Home Loan
Mortgage Corp. On one-year adjustable rate mortgages, lenders were
asking an average initial rate of between 8.56 percent and 8.73
percent.
   By last week, the rates were up to 11.22 percent and 9.30
pecent, respectively.
   Because lower-income buyers generally were the ones pushed out
of the market by the higher rates, the median price of existing
homes sold last month increased, the Realtors reported. The median
rose $3,400 to $93,100, meaning half sold for more and half for
less.
   ``Generally, in times of rising rates, the people left in the
market tend to be upper-income buyers who can buy the house they
want regardless of less affordable financing,'' said John Tuccillo,
chief economist for the group.
   He said the resale pace is not expected to drop much further
because economic growth appears to be slowing to a level acceptable
to the Fed.
   February's decline in home sales was led by a sharp drop in the
high-priced Northeast, where the market began to cool last year
after an earlier surge in prices.
   Resales in the region were at a seasonally adjusted annual rate
of 580,000 last month, down 18.3 percent from the previous month.
The median price of a home in the Northeast was $142,600, down
$1,200 from the previous month.
   The higher interest rates ``probably will prolong stagnation in
some of those markets,'' Tuccillo said.
   Sales in the South were down 0.8 percent to an annual rate of
1.3 million units last month, with the median price in that region
rising $6,100 last month to $88,500.
   Sales dropped 1.1 percent in the Midwest to an annual rate of
920,000 units, while the median price rose $2,100 to $69,900.
   The West was the only region to record an increase in sales last
month, with the annual rate rising 3.2 percent to 650,000 units.
The median price in the region was $133,700, up $3,000 from January.
   ``Strong economic growth in the West has made it better prepared
to withstand credit tightening,'' Tuccillo said. ``This region
contains some of the hottest markets in the country now, and buyers
there seem to be less affected by hikes in interest rates.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890327-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-27-89 1235EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Election-Monitor     03-27 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Election-Monitor,0457</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Group Says System Appears Efficient, but Abuses Possible</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Election, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN IAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. human rights group that monitored the
Soviet parliamentary elections said Monday the system appeared to
be efficient but there were flaws that could have led to rigging
the results.
   Soviet newspapers reported some voters were disenfranchised
because of election difficulties. Igor Orlov, the chairman of the
Moscow election commission, acknowledged some snags developed in
Sunday's voting, the first multicandidate elections in the Soviet
Union in 70 years.
   David Carliner, an attorney with the U.S.-based International
Human Rights Law Group, told a news conference that six delegates
visited 17 polling stations in eight election districts.
   ``The process appeared efficient and officials took their duty
quite seriously,'' he said. ``It was clear that they did not try in
any way to influence the voters.''
   Voters interviewed by the delegation ``were satisfied that their
ballots were secret and sacred and would be counted,'' Carliner
said.
   There were possibilities to commit election fraud, however,
mainly because there weren't enough Soviet observers to monitor all
polling stations, he said.
   At several polling stations, there were no observers or
officials present by late afternoon. ``The lack of observers left
open a chance to cheat,'' Carliner said. ``Anyone could have walked
in, marked up a bunch of ballots and stuffed them into the box.''
   In addition, special voting passes had been given to many people
such as businessmen and tourists, allowing them to vote away from
their residences, he said. That left the system open to abuse, he
said.
   ``We ran up against masses of absolutely new moments, currents
and problems,'' Orlov said from the Moscow City Council
headquarters. ``Some things we did satisfactorily, some things did
not get done until the end.''
   Soviet newspapers carried complaints of people who said they
were denied a chance to vote.
   ``In some election districts, a few disabled people were denied
the voting right because of the inefficiency of voting
commissions,'' Komsomolskaya Pravda said.
   In past elections, the disabled could request a ballot box be
brought to their residences. If a person could not get to a polling
station, a relative could take the person's internal passport and
cast the vote by proxy.
   The newspaper said the election commission of the
Cheremushkinsky district responded to the complaint by saying,
``They only had two portable ballot boxes and they were short of
time.''
   In other districts, residents did not receive the special mailed
invitation cards needed to cast a ballot, it said.
   The U.S. group has monitored elections in Nicaragua, Uruguay,
Grenada, El Salvador, South Korea and Zimbabwe.
</TEXT>
