<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     03-27 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAPLEWOOD, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As Hollywood gets ready for its yearly
orgy of self-congratulation, where is a jaded journalist to go for
the other side of the story _ the detached, indifferent, listless
and world-weary side?
   Alan Caruba, a public relations consultant, is meeting that
need. As creator of The Boring Institute, he says his phone has
been ringing constantly with interview requests prompted by his
satirical ``most boring'' lists.
   Caruba's latest, released March 20, was the ``Most Boring Film
Awards,'' a sendup of the Academy Awards.
   Eddie Murphy is a big winner for his two 1988 releases, ``Raw,''
and ``Coming To America,'' which Caruba says, ``run the gamut from
merely vulgar to monotonously obscene.''
   The institute will surface again in July with ``National
Anti-Boredom Month,'' followed in September by ``Fearless Forecasts
of TV's Fall Flops.'' The ``Most Boring Celebrities of the Year''
in December resulted in 200 radio interviews for Caruba.
   Caruba, a 51-year-old bachelor who still lives with his parents
in the house where he was raised, says the popularity of his
lampoon confirms his beliefs about America's media-glutted society.
   ``The American public is being exploited cynically by film
producers and people who choose what television programs they see.
   ``We are asked to live our lives vicariously through others,
primarily on television,'' he said.
   The irony of The Boring Institute, of course, is that Caruba's
diatribes are approaching the level of exposure that he is
criticizing.
   ``It's a kind of commentary on our times,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The newest member of the Stillwagner family,
Stephanie Ann, won't have to wear any hand-me-down dresses unless
they're antiques. She is the first girl in the family in 119 years.
   ``We asked the doctor if he was sure it was a girl, we were just
so shocked,'' said her mother, Debra Stillwagner.
   ``We have enough witnesses and I know what girls look like,''
said Dr. Marwan Hajj.
   ``Everybody's still walking around in shock,'' said Mrs.
Stillwagner of suburban Baltimore, who gave birth Thursday at
Greater Baltimore Medical Center.
   Added her husband, Dennis, ``We're pretty speechless.''
   Charles E. Stillwagner Sr., of Miami, Stephanie's 92-year-old
great-grandfather, says the baby is the first girl since his aunt
Eileen was born in 1870.
   ``My father had two boys. I had two boys. One of my boys had two
boys. And one of his boys had two boys,'' he said. ``I'm awfully
happy, since they wanted a girl.''
   Stephanie Ann has two brothers, Kevin, 8, and Christopher, 7.
</TEXT>
