<DOCNO> AP890327-0092 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-27-89 1324EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-TankerSpill 3rdLd-Writethru a0524 03-27 1294</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tanker Spill, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0524,1328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Captain Should Have Been Piloting Tanker, Exxon Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 27 grafs to UPDATE with winds forcing postponement
of cleanup efforts; further company comment on whereabouts of captain;
NTSB slating hearings for next week, other detail. Picks up 23rd graf,
`This oil...'.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AGX1, LaserGraphic NY5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A crewman without proper certification was
in command when an Exxon tanker apparently hit two rocks and ran
aground, causing the nation's biggest oil spill, the company said.
   Officials said a third mate was in command, against company
policy, at the time of Friday morning's accident that sent an
estimated 10.1 million gallons of crude oil into Prince Williams
Sound south of here and prompted the governor Sunday to declare the
sound a disaster area. The Exxon Valdez crewman did not have the
proper license to legally operate such a large ship in the sound,
officials said.
   Exxon Shipping Co. spokesman Brian Dunphy said Sunday that the
captain, Joseph Hazelwood, was in the cabin at the time of the
grounding. But today he said ``the captain's whereabouts are
uncertain throughout the entire incident. It is known he was not on
the bridge for the complete time.''
   Both he and another company spokesman, Sharon Curran-Wescott,
said that even if Hazelwood was present during part of the time on
the bridge, he was not in command.
   ``We do know the captain was not in command,'' Ms.
Curran-Wescott said. ``He apparently may have been physically
present on the bridge.''
   Dunphy said Hazelwood was consulting an attorney.
   Meanwhile, winds topping 25 knots this morning forced
postponement of efforts to clean up the sound with chemicals to
disperse the oil or fire to burn it off.
   ``Some of the cleanup operations, such as the use of skimmers
and also dispersants and the burn technique, have been put on
hold,'' Dunphy said. He said he was unsure if the weather would
improve enough to allow cleanup to begin later in the day.
   He said crews using three pumps had managed to move 78,000
barrels of oil from the Exxon Valdez to another tanker, the Exxon
Baton Rouge, as of 6 a.m., and workers planned to bring in four
more pumps todayto speed up the rate of unloading.
   Based on the findings of divers, the company believes the tanker
had struck one rock a glancing blow and was already leaking when it
struck a second time and ran around, said Exxon Shipping Co.
President Frank Iarossi. ``We're surmising there had to be two
events,'' he said, but he didn't know how many minutes apart they
might have taken place.
   Coast Guard officials said they could not confirm whether the
tanker hit bottom more than once or say what crew memers were on
the bridge at the time of the accident.
   Oil traders and analysts predicted crude oil prices would rise
temporarily because it forced the closing of the port of Valdez,
southern terminus of the Alyeska pipeline that carries all crude
oil from Alaska's North Slope, cutting U.S. crude supplies by a
quarter.
   In today's early trading, the May contract for West Texas
Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil, was up 57
cents from Thursday's close, trading at $20.72 per 42-gallon barrel
on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   Alaska Gov. Steve Cowper on Sunday declared the wildlife-rich
sound a disaster area and said he would seek federal funds to help
with the spill, which the Coast Guard estimates has affected about
100 square miles. Oil has washed up on two islands, and sightings
were reported of dozens of crude-coated birds.
   Also Sunday, officials said the government authorized use of
chemicals and fire to combat the massive slick.
   Before winds forced postponement of the effort, Iarossi had said
officials planned to use a C-130 aircraft today to spray chemicals
to disperse patches of oil in a 5-square-mile area of the sound.
The company also planned to burn ``fingers'' of the slick by
igniting them with a laser.
   ``The volume of oil released in the water is, for all intents
and purposes, beyond control by mechanical means alone,'' Iarossi
said.
   Iarossi said the latest estimate of damage to the tanker is
eight damaged oil cargo tanks and two damaged ballast tanks.
   At the time of the disaster Friday, third mate Gregory Cousins
was in command and his actions violated federal regulations, said
Ms. Curran-Wescott.
   ``He didn't have a proper pilot's license for that. He wasn't
authorized by the company, nor was it legal,'' she said.
   Neither Hazelwood nor Cousins could be located in Valdez by The
Associated Press for comment.
   The National Transportation Safety Board took over the
investigation Sunday, one day after issuing subpoenas for
Hazelwood, Cousins and helmsman Robert Kagan, the third member of
the bridge crew. Results of routine drug and alcohol tests
administered to the three weren't immediately available, officials
said.
   The NTSB slated hearings for next week in Anchorage.
   Hazelwood was relieved of his command, but to give him rest, not
as a disciplinary measure, officials said.
   The 987-foot tanker Exxon Valdez, carrying 1.2 million barrels
of North Slope crude oil, ran onto a reef 25 miles from port early
Friday after swinging out of a traffic lane to avoid ice. Valdez is
at the southern end of the 800-mile Alaska oil pipeline.
   Estimates put the spill at 240,000 barrels of oil, or about 10.1
million gallons, making it the biggest U.S. spill on record. The
only larger oil-related accident in U.S. waters involved 10.7
million gallons of oil when two ships collided in Galveston Bay in
1979, but that oil burned as well as spilled.
   ``This oil spill may well be the greatest disaster to hit Alaska
since the Good Friday earthquake 25 years ago,'' Cowper said.
   A wildlife specialist toured the sound and observed 75 ducks and
two otters coated with oil, said U.S. Department of Interior
spokeswoman Pamela Bergmann.
   A station was set up to clean birds, and a mammal-cleaning
station also was planned.
   Fishermen fearing lost income have sought compensation from the
shipping company, Exxon officials said.
   ``We're not ready to absorb any loss,'' said Riki Ott,
spokeswoman for United Fishermen of Alaska. ``We expect full
compensation.''
   More than four miles of floating boom has been placed in an
effort to contain the oil, the Coast Guard said. Skimming boats
worked to remove the oil.
   The transfer to a second ship of oil remaining aboard the Valdez
resumed during the weekend, and the Coast Guard said it could take
seven days to unload the damaged vessel.
   Iarossi said 36,000 gallons of chemicals that were to be used to
break up the oil were in Anchorage and 19,000 were to be flown from
Texas. Fishermen and other users of the resource-rich sound have
expressed concerns about additional damage that could be done by
chemicals.
   Environmentalists, the governor and other state officials have
accused Exxon and Alyeska Pipeline Service Co. of responding too
slowly to the spill. Alyeska operates the oil-loading terminal at
Valdez.
   Both companies said they were satisfied with how the problem was
being handled.
   ``We're proceeding cautiously,'' said Exxon spokesman Tom
Cirigliano. ``We want to make sure we don't make any mistakes in
cleaning up the spill.''
   Under the terms of the law authoritizing the Alaska pipeline,
the owner-operator of an oil tanker has strict liability for the
first $14 million in damage from a spill, according to Oil Spill
Intelligence Report, a weekly publication in Arlington, Mass.
   If damage exceeds $14 million, claims are paid out of a reserve
that is funded by a tariff on oil companies' Alaskan production.
The reserve has $300 million and can pay up to $100 million per
spill.
</TEXT>
