<SECOND>AM-False Threat,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Arrested for Alleged False Reporting of Bomb on Jetliner</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of threatening to blow up an
airliner has a history of mental problems and has been picked up
for similar threats in the past, including ones against President
Reagan, officials said Monday.
   ``We don't feel that the guy's dangerous, but he's causing
people a lot of trouble,'' said Richard Ward, head of the Secret
Service office in New York.
   Scott Sasonkin, 23, was arrested at Kennedy Airport after he
called the airport police information center late Sunday and told
the operator he put a bomb on a London-bound jet, said Bill Cahill,
a spokesman for the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey,
which operates the airport.
   Cahill quoted the caller as saying: ``I want $1 million or many
people will die. I planted a bomb on Pan Am flight 102 to London.
It's already in the air.''
   Cahill said the police kept Sasonkin talking for 20 minutes
while they traced the call to a pay phone in the Pan Am terminal
building. He was still talking when police reached him.
   Sasonkin, of the borough of Queens, was charged with attempted
grand larceny for demanding money, falsely reporting an incident
for telling police a bomb was on the plane, and aggravated
harassment for making the call, authorities said.
   Sasonkin was arrested June 27, 1988, for allegedly threatening
President Reagan, Ward said. He's also been picked up several other
times for making threatening calls and each time was committed to a
mental hospital for observation, Ward said.
   Pan Am said the flight was not affected. Sasonkin retracted his
story and denied placing a bomb on the plane, airline spokesman
Jeff Kriendler said.
