<HEAD>State Department Praises Soviet Elections</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Election, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A State Department spokeswoman on Monday
praised the Soviet elections, calling them a ``move in the right
direction.''
   ``It goes without saying that yesterday's elections were neither
free nor democratic by Western standards,'' said State Department
spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler. ``But they do represent an advance
over the practices of the past in the Soviet Union,'' she added.
   The elections to the new Congress of People's Deputies were ``a
move in the right direction. It's another sign that they're serious
about perestroika,'' she said.
   Perestroika is the process of restructuring the Soviet economy
undertaken by President Mikhail S. Gorbachev. Sunday's balloting
was the first time in 70 years that Soviet citizens had a choice of
more than one candidate.
   Asked what the Soviets should have done to comply with Western
standards, Ms. Tutwiler said they should have held ``the same type
of elections, I guess, that we have.''
   Ms. Tutwiler, who made her debut as the department's spokeswoman
at Monday's daily briefing, declined to go further, saying
elaboration on her comments would ``get me in trouble.''
