<SECOND>AM-Disney Hiring,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tourist Giant Begins Employment Drive for New Attractions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Walt Disney World's most popular
attraction these days is its employment office, where the tourist
giant will be hiring up to 4,000 workers a year over the next few
years.
   The employment drive begins next week with a goal of 2,300 new
workers by the end of the month to begin staffing $1.5 billion in
expanded attractions.
   The first, the Disney-MGM Studios theme park, opens May 1.
   Disney also has a new, highly visible employment office, or
``Casting Center'' to help attract workers in what is considered a
tight job market for entry-level, tourism-hotel-restaurant workers
in the area.
   The $10 million center resembles a Venetian Castle with Disney
touches. Mickey Mouse ears adorn its crenelated top and a rotunda
forming the entryway sports 13 golden-colored Disney characters.
   ``We know the market is tough,'' said Robert Wacker, director of
employee relations. ``But we're confident that when jobs pop up,
people will come looking to find them.''
   Disney has in the past few years raised its starting rates to $5
an hour, while many employers pay the current minimum of $3.35.
   Prospective employees get their first taste of Mickey's world in
the Casting Center with a 12-minute film about what it takes to be
a Disney ``cast member.''
   Disney's dress and grooming rules for men include no beards,
moustaches, long hair, earrings or visible tattoos. For women, eye
shadow and frosted hair is out, and no earrings larger than a
quarter.
