<FIRST>r w AM-Baker-Spokeswoman     03-27 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baker-Spokeswoman,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department Spokeswoman Admits Limited Policy Expertise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Margaret Tutwiler made her debut as chief
State Department spokeswoman Monday, cautioning reporters that she
was not knowledgeable about foreign policy and asking their
``patience and understanding.''
   ``As you all know, I am not, and do not claim to be, an expert
in foreign policy,'' Tutwiler said, reading a statement at the
start of the daily State Department briefing.
   ``But I do claim to have a fair amount of experience in working
with the press, and I do know this president and this secretary of
state very well,'' she added.
   Ms. Tutwiler, 38, served as Secretary of State James A. Baker's
spokeswoman when he was treasury secretary in the Reagan
administration and worked for George Bush when he made his
unsuccessful bid for the Republican presidential nomination in 1980.
   Ms. Tutwiler, who is considered one of Baker's closest advisers,
was confirmed by the Senate earlier this month. She has a tough act
to follow in her job as assistant secretary of state for public
affairs.
   Her predecessor, Charles Redman, is a career foreign service
officer with experience in U.S. diplomatic posts overseas. Redman,
who has been nominated ambassador to Sweden, enjoyed close ties
with former Secretary of State George P. Shultz and was adept at
handling the department's press corps.
   ``I have no intention of ever standing up here and winging it,
or guessing, or misleading,'' Ms. Tutwiler said. ``When I don't
know something, I'll tell you I don't. I sincerely ask for your
patience and understanding.''
   Ms. Tutwiler, speaking in a pronounced southern accent which
appeared to puzzle some of the foreign reporters, was careful to
stick closely to briefing answers prepared in advance by the
department's regional experts.
   She read a statement that praised the Soviet elections but said
they did not comply with Western standards. Asked ``what was
missing,'' she declined to answer, saying, ``You're going to get me
in trouble.''
</TEXT>
