<FIRST>r a AM-NYSWelfare     03-27 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NYS Welfare,0401</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Sues Feds For $157 Million In Welfare Payments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BELLAFIORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York state sued the federal government
Monday for $157 million in welfare reimbursements that state
officials charge Washington has illegally withheld.
   State social service officials charged in the lawsuit, filed in
federal court in New York City, that the federal government has
refused to give state and its local governments money owed for five
separate years, dating to 1979.
   The reimbursements are the federal share of the Aid for Families
with Dependent Children program dealing with children placed in
foster care. State Social Services Commissioner Cesar Perales said
federal officials have never acknowledged that New York filed for
the reimbursements.
   ``We are paying. We are providing the service,'' Perales told
reporters. ``The issue here is that the federal government is not
paying its share.''
   Perales said ``just about every other state is owed money''
totaling about $600 million. He mentioned California and Texas as
two states with a similar problem.
   ``We're talking about a system in which the federal government
says, `We're going to help you finance the care of your children in
foster care,''' Perales said. ``We rely on that trust and
relationship. ... We are relying on the good faith of the federal
government.''
   David Siegel, a spokesman at the U.S. Family Support
Administration, said he had not seen the lawsuit and could not
immediately comment. The agency, part the Department of Health and
Human Services, administers the foster care program.
   The $157 million consists of reimbursements the state claims
it's owed for 1979, 1980, 1983, 1987 and 1988, Perales said. Some
$50 million would go to the state, about $80 million would go to
New York City and $27 million would go to other local governments,
said state Attorney General Robert Abrams.
   The federal government estimates how much the state will need to
run the foster care program each quarter. According to Abrams and
Perales, Washington is supposed to reimburse the state whenever
actual costs for the quarter are higher than the federal estimate,
but didn't in these cases.
   Abrams, a Democrat, accused the Republican Reagan administration
of trying to balance the federal deficit ``on the backs of those
who can least afford to deal with that problem _ individuals who
are vulnerable, who are disabled.''
</TEXT>
