<DOCNO> AP890327-0104 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-27-89 1557EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-Soviet     03-27 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Soviet,0461</SECOND>
<HEAD>China: Differences Will Remain With Soviets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Differences will remain between China and the
Soviet Union even after they resume normal diplomatic relations at
their first summit in 30 years, China's foreign minister said
Monday.
   Soviet support for Vietnam's invasion of Cambodia is regarded by
China as the most serious obstacle to better ties between Beijing
and Moscow, and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen said the issue will be
high on the agenda when Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev
visits China in May.
   Qian told a news conference that the visit will lead to normal
diplomatic relations, but there will still be ``some way to go and
some efforts to be made'' before two countries resolve all their
differences.
   Qian said China, which supports the anti-Vietnamese resistance
in Cambodia, backs the dispatch of a U.N. peacekeeping force after
Vietnam ends its 10-year occupation.
   He said China is not preparing to send troops to Cambodia to
participate in a proposed peacekeeping force.
   The Chinese-Soviet summit, the first since Nikita S. Khrushchev
and Mao Tse-tung met in 1959, follows the withdrawal of Soviet
troops from Afghanistan and a Soviet announcement this month it
would withdraw of 75 percent the 50,000 Soviet forces from Mongolia
_ two Soviet moves to ease its long-strained relationship with
China.
   Khrushchev and Mao later clashed over ideology, and Soviet and
Chinese troops clashed in the 1960s and 1970s along the 4,670-mile
border.
   At the news conference, Qian said Sino-U.S. relations have
progressed smoothly since diplomatic ties were formed a decade ago.
Relations, he said, ``enjoy vast potential and the prospects are
very good.''
   But he also called on a ``new pattern'' of relations based on
mutual trust, and had sharp words for members of the U.S. Congress
who have criticized China's lack of democratic reform and its human
rights record in Tibet.
   ``A small number of people in the American Congress are actually
very ill-informed about the situation in Tibet. They have very
strong prejudice.''
   China last week criticized both the European Parliament and the
U.S. Congress for statements concerning the declaration of martial
law in the Tibetan capital of Lhasa following pro-independence
riots this month.
   Qian said the Lhasa rioters were trying to split the Chinese
nation and foreign nations that raise the human rights question are
interfering in China's internal affairs.
   Human rights, he added, are a matter of basic questions such as
providing adequate food and education and ``are inseparable with
the actual condition of the country involved.''
   He noted China still has 200 million illiterate people. ``There
are things that can be easily achieved in some countries but not in
others.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
