<FILEID>AP-NR-03-27-89 1820EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Dole-Dropouts     03-27 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dole-Dropouts,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>Labor Secretary Urges Removal Of Bureaucratic Barriers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole on Monday urged
breaking down bureaucratic barriers between programs aimed at
preventing school dropouts, saying a ``fragmented, piecemeal,
programmatic approach'' doesn't work.
   She began a 10-city fact-finding tour of Labor Department
regional offices during which she is meeting with officials and
students in youth job training and employment programs. The tour
ends April 4 in Boston.
   ``We need a way to tie together the programs both federally and
most definitely at the community level,'' she told civic leaders,
teachers and students in Atlanta's Exodus program, founded in
Atlanta in 1971 to combat Georgia's 34 percent dropout rate. The
program now is in 31 cities.
   She said her tour is designed to help learn which programs work
and which do not.
   Mrs. Dole said the information will be used to start programs to
identify needs of individual students in 12 cities to be picked
later. These are to be converted to model programs in five cities.
   She said current programs often overlap or duplicate each other
and lack follow-up studies.
   Mrs. Dole said much of what she referred to as the ``skills gap
and the motivation gap'' is rooted in a time when there were fewer
possibilities for young people in the job market and when
expectations were lower.
   ``Everyone can have a job today who wants a job if he has the
skills,'' she said. ``But you've got to have the skills.
   ``It's a new day,'' Mrs. Dole said. ``We've got a real mission
here together to accomplish this.''
   Mrs. Dole said she believes her primary goal is to ensure that
the United States has the best-trained labor force in the world.
But she noted that youth unemployment nationally is at 16 percent
and that minority youth unemployment is at 35 percent, or even
higher in some areas.
   ``We must look at our own situation,'' she said, adding that she
will urge other federal departments, such as Education and Health
and Human Services, to tie programs together with the Labor
Department. ``Are we training people for the jobs of yesterday or
the jobs of tomorrow?''
</TEXT>
