<FIRST>r a AM-ManchinImpeachment     03-27 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Manchin Impeachment,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>Committee Endorses 18 Impeachment Articles Against W. Va. Official</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By A.V. GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Articles of impeachment were sent
Monday to the full House against state Treasurer A. James Manchin,
who was charged with improper handling of a fund that lost $279
million and covering up the losses.
   Neither Manchin, 61, a popular, flamboyant Democrat in his
second term as treasurer, nor his lawyer would comment immediately
on the 17-7 vote by which the House Judiciary Committee recommended
18 impeachment articles to the House.
   The committee also voted 22-3 to recommend censure of state
Auditor Glen Gainer for his role in the losses in the consolidated
investment fund, which was under the overall control in 1987 of a
board upon which Gainer and Manchin served. The fund was under the
direct investment power of the treasurer.
   House Speaker Chuck Chambers said the 100-member House is
expected to take up the resolution Wednesday. A simple majority is
needed to send it to the Senate.
   Senate President Larry Tucker, anticipating Manchin's
impeachment by the House, told the Senate last week to be prepared
to sit as a jury in late May.
   It would take 23 ``yes'' votes in the Senate _ two-thirds of the
34 members _ to convict. That could lead to Manchin's removal from
office and loss of a pension estimated at at least $2,128 a month.
   The judiciary committee voted 19-6 last Wednesday to formalize
16 impeachment articles and the final vote on the document was
taken Monday.
   Added Monday were articles charging that Manchin put an
unqualified person in control of the state's investment portfolio
after two previous treasury employees left and that the treasurer's
office charged for handling investments in the fund.
   The articles charge Manchin with failing to supervise the fund,
delegation of his power and authority, making improper investments
of state funds, paying out funds that were not earned, and covering
up the losses, which occurred mainly in April, May and June 1987.
   Manchin's chief defender on the committee, Delegate Jim Pitrolo,
said a minority report signed by six members is being prepared to
present to the House. ``We don't feel there is evidence to
impeach,'' said Pitrolo.
   Gainer's censure motion, which amounts to a public reprimand,
said he failed to adequately supervise the fund and to fulfill his
public duties.
</TEXT>
