<SECOND>AM-People-Cheers,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>NBC Bringing Back `Cheers' For Another Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sam Malone, Rebecca Howe, Carla Tortelli,
Woody Boyd and the other denizens of Boston's favorite watering
hole are returning for an eighth season of ``Cheers,'' NBC
announced Monday.
   The highly rated Thursday-night comedy stars Ted Danson, Kirstie
Alley, Rhea Pearlman and Woody Harrelson behind the bar and George
Wendt, John Ratzenberger, Kelsey Grammer and Bebe Neuwirth on the
stools.
   Joan Severence joins the cast later this season as Rebecca's
sister, Susan Howe, a former Miss San Diego, who will become a love
interest for Malone. She will be back next season in at least five
episodes.
   Contrary to the supermarket tabloids, Shelley Long is not
returning to the show, said Maggie Begley, a spokeswoman for
Paramount Television. Long played Diane Chambers on ``Cheers'' in
the 1982-87 seasons, then left to pursue a career in movies. She's
currently starring in ``Troop Beverly Hills.''
   The Long rumor began when a reporter overheard her and Danson
talking at the premiere of ``Cousins,'' which stars Danson.
   The conversation was a ``wouldn't it be nice'' kind of talk
about Long's return, said Begley. There has never been any
discussion between the producers and her representatives about her
return to the show.
