<FIRST>r w AM-US-Angola     03-27 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Angola,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Urges Positive Angolan Response To Rebels' Peace Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHIGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department on Monday urged the
Marxist government of Angola to accept a peace proposal put forth
by U.S.-backed rebel leader Jonas Savimbi.
   The proposals by Savimbi's National Union of the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) ``are a significant step in that
direction, and are deserving of broad support,'' State Department
spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said.
   She said the United States urged the government in Luanda ``to
respond positively to UNITA's gestures and offer of peace.''
   Savimbi, who has been fighting the government for 14 years, has
called a four-month halt to attacks on Cuban-aided government
troops in order to bring about peace talks.
   He also has pledged not to interfere with reconstruction of the
strategic east-west Benguela railway, destroyed by rebel attacks,
and he said he would be willing to release 100 captured government
soldiers.
   The United States, which gives UNITA an estimated $15 million in
weapons annually, has been embarrassed by recent reports of human
rights violations by Savimbi.
   Savimbi has denied the reports, which include allegations that
he ordered the torture and killings of rebel dissidents, and U.S.
officials say they are investigating.
   UNITA wants to take advantage of a recently signed,
U.S.-sponsored agreement for the withdrawal of Cuban troops from
Angola in order to start talks on power sharing with the government.
   But so far, the government has refused to negotiate with the
rebels, even though there is little prospect for a military victory
by either side. Savimbi acknowledges he cannot win a conventional
war against the Cuban-backed government forces, but his rebels have
for years controlled about a third of the country.
</TEXT>
