<FIRST>r w AM-TreasuryBills     03-27 0173</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Treasury Bills,170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rates Highest Since Late 1984</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities rose in Monday's auction to the highest levels in more
than four years.
   The Treasury Department sold $7.2 billion in three-month bills
at an average discount rate of 9.1 percent, up from 9 percent last
week. Another $7.2 billion was sold in six-month bills at an
average discount rate of 9.12 percent, up from 9.04 percent last
week.
   The rates were the highest since three-month bills sold for 9.38
percent and six-month bills averaged 9.59 percent on Oct. 29, 1984.
   The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors
_ 9.44 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling
for $9,770.00 and and 9.69 percent for six-month bills selling for
$9,538.90.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Monday that the
average yield for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index
for making changes in adjustable rate home mortgages, rose to 9.78
percent last week after averaging 9.56 percent the week before.
</TEXT>
