<FIRST>r a AM-OilSpill-Glance     03-27 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Spill-Glance,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Tanker Spill Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a look at some other major oil spills and their effects.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>FRANCE-AMOCO CADIZ</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The 220,000-ton tanker Amoco Cadiz, owned by a subsidiary of
Standard Oil of Indiana, ran aground March 16, 1978, after tow
lines snapped, impaling the vessel on rocks two miles off the
western French coast.
   At least 68 million gallons of light Gulf crude oil spilled out
along about 100 miles of Brittany coastline. The spill created an
oil slick 18 miles wide and 80 miles long, blackened beaches, and
killed thousands of birds and millions of sea creatures. Local
industries such as tourism, fishing, and particularly the oyster
industry, were seriously affected.
   The French government has paid out as much as $100 million in
clean-up costs and compensation to those affected by the spill. In
February, a judge recommended a $115.2 million judgment against
Amoco Corp., with the French government slated to recieve $44.4
million and affected towns about $7.5 million.
   Today, Brittany's beaches are again clean, the fishermen are at
work again and the oyster beds productive. But insidious damages,
like the death of small animals which other fish had fed from, have
caused the gradual disappearance of certain species, and officials
say the total fallout from the pollution has not yet been evaluated.

</TEXT>
<NOTE>NANTUCKET-ARGO MERCHANT</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The Argo Merchant, a Liberian tanker, was lost in the early
morning darkness on Dec. 15, 1976, when it ran onto a shoal off
Nantucket Island in Massachusetts. Winds and waves battered the
ship while the Coast Guard tried to save it. The tanker leaked oil
until it finally broke apart nine days later and lost the rest of
its cargo. A total of 7.6 million gallons of residual oil (not
crude) were spilled.
   Winds were blowing offshore, and the oil drifted into the open
ocean. A few months later, no oil could be found on the ocean
bottom. No serious harm to the waters or fish were detected.
   In 1980, a federal court ruled that the Argo Merchant was an
unsafe ship, citing general mismanagement, neglect, and navigation
errors.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>PACIFIC NORTHWEST-BARGE</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Approximately 231,000 gallons of heavy bunker oil spilled from a
barge off the southwest Washington coast on Dec. 22, 1988, after
the tug towing the barge struck it while maneuvering to secure a
towing line.
   The spill fooled officials, who predicted it would be broken up
in heavy seas. However, a few days after the accident, a storm
pushed the oil back toward land, where it washed up on hundreds of
miles of beaches, including pristine wilderness beaches in Olympic
National Park and Canada's Pacific Rim National Park.
   A massive cleanup effort followed, involving professional and
volunteer crews. Still, up to 10,000 birds died and effects of the
pollution will linger for years.
   The Oregon company whose tug was towing the barge, Sause
Brothers Ocean Towing Co., agreed to pay cleanup costs. The state's
cost to date is $350,000, of which Sause Brothers has paid $115,000.
   A marine resource damage-assessment team is investigating the
spill's effects on everything from surf smelt and sea otters, to
subsistence seafood harvesting by Indian tribes. A price tag will
be put on the whole package, including a cost per dead bird and for
such ephemeral items as lost recreational opportunities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
