<FIRST>r a AM-BookmakingBust     03-27 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bookmaking Bust,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agents Arrest 33 In Interstate Bookmaking Operation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 33 people have been arrested
in Central Florida in a multimillion-dollar, interstate sports
betting ring, state and federal officials announced Monday.
   Those arrested allegedly accepted or placed bets in Florida with
an operation based in Louisville, Ky., ranging from hundreds to
thousands of dollars on events in college and professional
basketball, football and baseball, and horse races.
   While arrests were made in Florida, the FBI in Louisville was
seizing six facilities associated with the operation and began
serving search warrants on suspected leaders of the organization,
said Peter Antonacci, Florida's statewide prosecutor.
   Phone taps were used in the investigation, which began in late
1987.
   ``We've got calls where thousands were bet by one person on one
game,'' said Don Marblestone, assistant statewide prosecutor.
``We're not talking people betting 10, 20, 30 bucks.''
   Arrested and accused of leading the operation's Florida division
were Robert Kopp, 45 and his wife, Shirley, 32, of Orlando.
   According to information gathered through the wiretaps, the
Kopps were salaried employees of the Kentucky organization and
earned $150,000 a year, said Marblestone.
   They face charges of racketeering, conspiracy to commit
racketeering and 30 counts of bookmaking. Kopp's bond was set at
$250,000 and Mrs. Kopp's was set at $50,000. If convicted, Kopp
faces up to 22 years in prison and Mrs. Kopp faces up to seven
years, said Marblestone.
   Most of the other people arrested were bettors. They face
misdemeanor charges.
</TEXT>
