<FIRST>u i AM-Yeltsin Bjt   03-27 0860</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yeltsin, Bjt,0883</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yeltsin Victory Proves Popularity, Not Power</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boris N. Yeltsin completed a stunning political
comeback with his landslide victory over a candidate who symbolized
power and prestige.
   Yet, his broad base of political support translates to little
real power in his bid to challenge the government and the Communist
Party bureaucracy.
   Yeltsin rolled up more than 89 percent of the vote to defeat
technocrat Yevgeny Brakov for a seat representing all of Moscow in
Sunday's first multicandidate national balloting in 70 years of
Soviet power. Together with the defeats of high-ranking officials
in other areas of the country, it is a warning of popular
discontent with entrenched officials and their privileges.
   The victory restored the burly, 58-year-old Sverdlovsk native to
a place of prominence in Moscow, giving the onetime protege of
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev a parliamentary seat representing
the city he used to run as Communist Party chief.
   But it is only one of 2,250 seats in a body that meets once a
year to elect a president and a new, more active legislative body:
the Supreme Soviet.
   Gorbachev has said he wants all members of the congress to serve
one year of their five-year terms in the Supreme Soviet, but there
is no guarantee when Yeltsin will be elected to the practically
full-time lawmaking body.
   Yeltsin has been on the outs politically since losing his job in
November 1987 following his blunt criticism of the party's style of
leadership and warnings of a Stalin-like cult developing around
Gorbachev.
   During his populist campaign against the privileges of the party
elite and the failure of Gorbachev's reforms to put food on the
tables of ordinary people, however, Yeltsin was careful not to
challenge Gorbachev's leadership. He repeated that disclaimer after
his victory.
   ``I didn't consider myself, I don't consider myself, and I don't
want to be an alternative candidate to Gorbachev,'' Yeltsin told
hundreds of workers Monday at the State Construction Committee,
where he serves as first deputy chairman.
   Accused in the Communist Party's Central Committee of advocating
a multiparty system, Yeltsin has denied the charge and said it was
an effort to undermine his campaign. But he gave a clue about how
he plans to push his program, saying deputies must form interest
groups if they expect to accomplish anything.
   ``It is impossible to carry out 2,250 programs, as many as there
are deputies,'' he said Monday. Yeltsin said he foresaw ``some
based on ecology, some on social issues, some on the economy. In
this way they can be formed to strengthen that trend, that voice.''
   ``And just the opposite, they can stand as a strong barrier
against those trends that people don't need, which hurt our people
and the government too,'' he said.
   Yeltsin ran hard in the Soviet Union's most visible electoral
district against what he said is an entrenched power structure that
enjoys special privileges while creating shortages for the masses
by mismanaging the economy.
   He said the leadership has failed to meet its top priority of
improving living conditions because reforms have not gone far
enough. Yeltsin campaigned for eliminating most government
ministries and cutting the Moscow bureaucracy to improve local
autonomy.
   His campaign was built on his popularity gained while serving as
Moscow Communist Party chief in 1985-87. It also served as a
lightning rod for discontent that is surfacing as Soviets are
increasingly allowed to voice their opinions.
   Yevgeniya Tonkonovye, 62, said Sunday that she voted for Yeltsin
because he visited the clinic where she worked and because he used
public transportation. ``You feel his earthiness,'' she said.
   Brakov, in contrast, came across less naturally and recited a
campaign program that closely followed mainstream Communist Party
calls for improved food and consumer goods.
   In his short term as Moscow party chief, Yeltsin was a close
supporter of Gorbachev, especially of his calls for greater
openness. But it was Gorbachev who criticized his one-time protege
for being overly ambitious and presided over the meeting at which
Yeltsin was fired.
   Yeltsin has criticized Gorbachev's electoral reforms as not
being democratic enough, and he chastised the party for nominating
100 candidates for an equal number of seats in the congress.
Gorbachev was among the 100.
   In contrast, three-quarters of the 1,500 congress members chosen
Sunday had competition.
   ``Democracy in society has gotten ahead of democracy in the
party, judging by the election law,'' Yeltsin said.
   But Yeltsin's popularity with a program that criticized
Communist Party policies could conceivably help Gorbachev, and the
Soviet leader appeared to acknowledge that in comments he made to
correspondents after voting Sunday.
   Asked about the charges made against Yeltsin in the final days
of the campaign, Gorbachev said the former Moscow party leader must
be willing to accept criticism along with everyone else in a freer
atmosphere.
   But he also said those who supported Yeltsin's attacks on
bureaucracy were ardent supporters of continuing reforms.
   Gorbachev might be able to use the strong showing by Yeltsin and
losses suffered by conservatives elsewhere to show the
conservatives still in the power structure thatay     *#*  *#* 
