<FIRST>r w AM-ShrubBank     03-27 0168</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shrub Bank,160</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gene Bank Set Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gene and data bank for shrubs and other
woody landscape plants has been established at the National
Arboretum, the Agriculture Department said Monday.
   Arboretum director H. Marc Cathey said plant researchers and
nurseries will use the bank to find and obtain landscape specimens
at other arboretums and nurseries around the country _ as well as
in the National Arboretum.
   Cathey also said collections of plants at the 444-acre arboretum
will be expanded as part of a new national woody landscape plant
repository. A new computer bank will make it easier to develop new
and better specimens.
   The new repository is the first of its kind at the national
level, he said. The arboretum is operated by the department's
Agricultural Research Service.
   Cathey said public interest in gardening has expanded rapidly
since 1978, including an increase of almost a third in the sales of
landscape plants. Those sales were estimated at more than $7
billion last year.
</TEXT>
