<FIRST>u w AM-WhiteHouseEggs     03-27 0600</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-White House Eggs,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Youngsters Throng White House Lawn for Egg Roll Without Commercials</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEXANDER G. HIGGINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, his wife, children and
grandchildren joined thousands of youngsters on the sunlit South
Lawn of the White House Monday for an Easter egg roll lacking much
of the commercialization of recent years.
   ``What we were trying to do was basically bring back good kid
entertainment and take some of the commercial out of it,'' said
Debbie Romash of the White House visitors center.
   Ms. Romash said White House security estimated nearly 40,000
children and parents came through the gates for this year's event,
about 5,000 more than last year.
   The Bushes were accompanied by two of their children, Neil and
Doro, and six grandchildren. Vice President Dan Quayle hid wooden
eggs in straw for younger children, and his wife, Marilyn, and
10-year-old daughter, Corinne, read stories.
   Nancy Sununu, wife of White House Chief of Staff John Sununu,
also joined the story readers.
   Actor Christopher Reeve and his two sons, Alexander and Matthew,
joined the first family at the egg roll, as did actors playing
Little Red Riding Hood and the Wolf from the Broadway show ``Into
the Woods.''
   The president squatted down to explain to 2-year-old
granddaughter Ellie LeBlond how to use a plastic kitchen spoon to
roll a hard-boiled egg 20 or so feet down a lane drawn on the White
House lawn for the occasion.
   Then he blew a whistle to start the round.
   Egg-rolling is a technique that may have fallen into disuse
since 1878, when the children of Washington persuaded President
Rutherford B. Hayes to allow them to compete at the White House
after they had been banned from the grounds of the Capitol.
   The eggs are to stay rolling through the lush grass for the
distance, but some of the older children _ the top age allowed is 8
_ sailed their eggs across the finish line with one flick at the
whistle. Some of the littlest competitors needed help from a parent.
   No one seemed to be keeping track of who won the events, but it
didn't matter, because all the participants in the White House egg
rolls win a souvenir wooden egg. This year they bore the signatures
of the first couple.
   Bush talked with Reeve, bystanders and others, then blew the
whistle for a second race. At its conclusion, he headed back to the
White House, shaking hands along the way.
   ``Our goals this year were to, one, accentuate the family
because that is so much of the Bushes and, two, increase the
involvement of the kids in the basic activities that they come
for,'' Ms. Romash said.
   ``A Family Easter at the White House, 1989'' said the brochure
and sticker given each child upon arrival. Afterward, each was
given a single Easter Card with a story about the Easter Bunny, not
the bags of candy and other goodies of recent years.
   Gone were the actors dressed up as TV cartoon characters or
well-known brands of candy that were a feature of the event during
the years Ronald Reagan lived in the White House.
   Instead, clowns, some volunteers from the Ringling Bros. and
Barnum &amp; Bailey Circus, made up the bulk of the costumed
entertainers who mingled with the little ones this year,
distributing helium-filled balloons of pink, yellow or white and
signing autographs.
   It was a day with much standing in line for most guests, an
average of two hours just to get in plus additional waits to
participate in the most popular events.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
