<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Uganda-Rustlers     03-27 0179</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Uganda-Rustlers,0186</SECOND>
<HEAD>Uganda Sends in Troops Against Cattle Rustlers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government sent army troops to
northeastern Uganda against marauding cattle rustlers who chased
13,000 people from their homes, Radio Uganda reported Monday.
   Maj. Gen. Elly Tumwine was quoted as saying army units would be
left permanently in besieged Usuk county, 180 miles northeast of
Kampala. The troops were to fight the heavily armed rustlers who
are Karamajong tribesmen, according to the broadcast.
   He did not say how many troops were deployed.
   The rustlers moved into Usuk county three weeks ago after
government troops were withdrawn from the area. They since have
tortured and killed villagers, burned their huts, and stolen cattle
and other property, the radio said.
   An estimated 13,000 Usuk villagers fled the raiders to nearby
Soroti, where they are living in makeshift camps, the radio said.
   The Karamajong are cattle rustlers who raided military barracks
after the fall of dictators Idi Amin in 1979 and Milton Obote in
1985. They stole machine guns to boost their traditional arsenal of
spears and arrows.
</TEXT>
