<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Japan-Immigration     03-27 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Japan-Immigration,0193</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan Turns Away, Deports Record Number Of Foreigners</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan last year turned away or deported 17,854
foreigners for carrying fake passports or working illegally,
according to a Justice Ministry report Monday.
   For the first time in 10 years, the number of males deported for
violating immigration law exceeded that of females and was 90
percent higher than in 1987, the report said. The number of women
deported fell by 16 percent, the report said.
   Of the total, more than 16,000 foreigners overstayed visas and
14,300 of these were employed without proper working papers, the
report said.
   The remaining foreigners were turned away at borders with fake
papers, the report said.
   The largest national group deported was from the Philippines,
followed by illegal workers from Bangladesh, Pakistan and South
Korea, the report said.
   In the last three years, people from developing Asian nations
have flocked to Japan, where they usually find illegal work on
construction sites, in restaurants or in small factories, a Justice
Ministry official said. They earn far more than they would in their
own countries, the official said.
</TEXT>
