<FILEID>AP-NR-03-27-89 2011EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SouthAfrica     03-27 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa,0321</SECOND>
<HEAD>Detainee Halts Hunger Strike After 38 Days</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DURBAN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A detained black activist ended a
38-day hunger strike Monday, drinking milk and eating two slices of
toast to end the longest of a wave of fasts protesting detention
without trial.
   Sandile Thusi said he would consider resuming the hunger strike
if Law and Order Minister Adriaan Vlok refused to free him.
   ``I'm just giving Mr. Vlok a chance, a few days so he can think
about my release,'' Thusi, 26, said from his bed at St. Aidan's
Hospital in Durban, where he was visited by his mother, aunt and
sister-in-law.
   Thusi lost about 57 pounds, one-third of his normal weight, in
the hunger strike, and doctors had said he risked brain damage and
blindness if he did not resume eating immediately. He was fasting
to protest his nine-month detention without trial.
   The Law and Order Ministry said last week that Thusi's release
would not be considered while he continued his fast. There has been
no response from the ministry to his decision to resume eating.
   Thusi said he would suspend the fast after a meeting Saturday
with the Rev. Frank Chikane, a prominent anti-apartheid leader.
   Chikane also spoke Saturday to Vlok about Thusi, who has staged
the longest fast of the estimated 600 detainees participating in
hunger strikes since January to demand their freedom.
   Thusi, a university researcheundations and
contributions from 100,000 members, has 40 staff lawyers.
   ``I guess we would have more than effective legal counsel in any
litigation,'' said Meyerhoff, who is a lawyer.
   ``Unless there was some showing of bad faith or malice here on
our part, the law is clear that a lawsuit like that could be
successfully defended,'' he said, adding such a lawsuit could be
considered frivolous by the courts.
   The NRDC report on pesticide residues in childrens' food was
released in late February, and concluded that eating apples treated
with the growth regulator Alar increased cancer risk in children.
   The report has been widely disputed, and the federal government
has said apples are safe to eat. The industry has accused the NRDC
of unfairness because only 5 percent of the crop is treated with
Alar. Alar is the trade name for daminozide, and is still legal to
use.
   Nevertheless, the report caused an uproar, prompting some school
districts to temporarily ban apples, hurting exports and retail
sales.
   The exact economic impact has not yet been measured, but prices
for the top grade of red apples have dropped about $2 per box in
recent weeks, and apple shipments from Washington dropped by over
300,000 boxes in the past two weeks.
   Warehouses in Washington, which produces half the nation's
supermarket apples, still have 17.7 million boxes of red apples
from the fall harvest in storage.
   Multiplying that by $2 per 42-pound box produces an economic
loss of $35.4 million for the rest of the season, even if prices
drop no further.
   ``The basic problem in the industry now is they've (NRDC)
smeared the red apple so bad on the Alar thing that it's rolling
over into the non-Alar-treated fruit,'' McPherson said.
   ``Everytime a housewife sees red apples she could be seeing red
herself,'' he said. ``I don't know how you can measure that.''
</TEXT>
