<FILEID>AP-NR-03-27-89 2012EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Bearings-Dumping     03-27 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bearings-Dumping,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agency Says Imports Being Sold in U.S. at Less than Fair Value</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Commerce Department said Monday it had
made a final determination that imports of anti-friction bearings
from nine countries are being sold in the United States at less
than fair value.
   The department's ruling covered imports from West Germany,
France, Italy, Japan, Romania, Singapore, Sweden, Thailand and the
United Kingdom. The agency also ruled that bearings from Singapore
and Thailand were being subsidized.
   As a result of earlier preliminary rulings in the case, cash
deposits or bonds are being imposed on imports from the nine
countries to offset the price advantages and subsidies.
   If the U.S. International Trade Commission makes a final ruling
that the low-priced imports harm U.S. industry, the Commerce
Department will instruct the Customs Service to collect the final
anti-dumping and countervailing duties.
   The department began its investigation after the Torrington Co.
in Torrington, Conn., filed a petition last March on behalf of the
U.S. bearing industry, alleging that massive dumping by the foreign
countries was damaging the domestic bearing industry. Torrington is
the nation's largest producer of a range of bearings.
   David Gridley, the company's industry marketing manager, said
several studies had found that a ``substantial number of bearing
factories closed and workers were laid off while at the same time
imports from these foreign countries have been increasing.''
   Gridley said the company was very pleased with the ruling and
with the department's in-depth inquiry. The petition resulted in 34
anti-dumping and 10 countervailing duty investigations covering
several kinds of bearings.
   The department said the investigations were the most technical
and complex in several years, and covered more than 25 foreign
companies.
   Imports of anti-friction bearings from the nine countries were
estimated at about $650 million in 1988. Anti-friction bearings are
used in the aircraft, automotive, machinery and electronics
industries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
