<FIRST>u i AM-Baltics     03-27 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baltics,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reform Organizations Run Strong In Elections In Baltics</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Election Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VILNIUS, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A political group seeking greater
autonomy from the Soviet Union defeated government leaders in
elections in Lithuania, and similar organizations made strong
showings in Latvia and Estonia.
   Voters in the three Baltic republics used Sunday's balloting _
the first multiple-candidate elections in the Soviet Union in 70
years _ to express support for reform.
   The official Tass news agency said that in Lithuania, President
Vitautus Astrauskas and Premier Vitautus Sokolauskas were defeated
by candidates supported by Sajudis, the Lithuanian Restructuring
Movement.
   Sajudis claimed it won or forced runoff elections in all 39
districts it contested. Sajudis leaders saw the voting for
positions in the new Soviet parliament, the Congress of People's
Deputies, as a referendum on its call for more sovereignty.
   The organization did not run candidates against Algirdas
Brazauskas, the leader of Lithuania's Communist Party, or his
deputy, Vladimiras Beriozovas. Sajudis regards them as reformers.
   Virgilijus Chapaitis, a Sajudis leader, said of the vote: ``In
principle it means the public backs independence. It means we want
to say what will happen in Lithuania.''
   Some Sajudis supporters want an independent Lithuania, but the
organization has stopped short of calling for secession. ``Any
question of secession is for the future'' while the republic works
toward creating democratic institutions, Chapaitis said in an
interview.
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev ``need not fear this
election,'' he added.
   Chapaitis noted that many Sajudis members also are members of
the Communist Party. ``Its not a victory against the (Communist)
party. It's a victory of the progressives,'' he said.
   In Latvia, Janis Vagris, head of the Latvian Communist Party,
won in a multicandidate struggle that included Yuris Dobelis, a
founder of the Latvian independence movement, Tass said.
   Dobelis said he hoped to get enough votes to force a run-off. He
said Vagris had taken advantage of heavy exposure on state-run
television in the week before the elections.
   In Estonia, Popular Front candidates ran well.
   Edgar Savisaar, a People's Front leader, took more than 80
percent of the vote to defeat Allik Jaak, a Communist Party chief
in the city of Viljandi.
   Marju Lauristen, another People's Front candidate, also won with
more than 80 percent of the vote in her race against Walter Toots,
the editor of a Russian-language newspaper in the university town
of Tartu, said officials of the Estonian Foreign Ministry.
   Rein Vederman, the No. 2 official in the Estonian Communist
Party, faces a runoff against Yevgeny Kogan, the leader of
Interfront, a political group that promotes the interests of
non-Estonians living in the republic.
</TEXT>
