<DOCNO> AP890327-0144 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-27-89 1829EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Egypt-Peace     03-27 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Egypt-Peace,0553</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mubarak Confers with Saudi King Before Washington Trip</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAURICE GUINDI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   King Fahd of Saudi Arabia arrived Monday for
meetings with President Hosni Mubarak in the quest by moderate Arab
governments and the PLO for a common position on Middle East peace.
   Mubarak is scheduled to meet with President Bush in Washington
next Monday. Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir will confer with Bush
three days later, and King Hussein is to visit Washington on May 2.
   Hussein and Yasser Arafat, chairman of the Palestine Liberation
Organization, conferred with Mubarak on Saturday to coordinate
strategy in seeking an energetic U.S. role in Middle East peace
efforts.
   Foreign Minister Esmat Abdel-Meguid said Monday he told a group
of visiting U.S. senators: ``It is vital that the United States
play its role in helping to achieve permanent and comprehensive
peace in the Middle East. President Mubarak's U.S. visit is aimed
at pushing the peace effort forward.''
   Mubarak, Hussein, Fahd and Arafat favor an international
conference on Middle East peace, which Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir of Israel has opposed. It would include the parties involved
and the five permanent members of the U.N. Security Council: the
United States, Soviet Union, China, Britain and France.
   Egyptian officials said privately that Mubarak and the others
believe the United States can convince Israel to reverse its
position on such a forum and its refusal to deal with the PLO and
hope the conference can begin this year.
   Saudi Arabia is considered a key because of its political
influence in the Arab world, friendship with the United States,
financial aid to the PLO and poorer Arab states, and position as
custodian of Islam's holiest shrines.
   The 10th anniversary the U.S.-mediated peace treaty between
Egypt and Israel occurred Sunday. No other Arab country has made
peace with the Jewish state.
   Egypt is involved in current peace efforts in hopes of acting as
``a bridge'' and ``because the parties want us there,'' Mubarak has
said.
   Fahd's four-day official visit is the first by a Saudi monarch
to Egypt in 15 years. The Egyptian officials said the meetings with
Fahd, Hussein and Arafat should strengthen Mubarak's hand with Bush.
   After the Ismailiya discussions, Mubarak, Hussein and Arafat
renewed the demand for an international peace conference and
praised the current U.S. position on Middle East peace as
``positive.''
   Hussein said: ``We believe the United States is giving great
attention to this problem and we hope the American position will
crystallize very soon. ... We all hope to see progress toward
comprehensive peace in the region and we believe the international
conference is the only means to this end.''
   Bush renewed his promise of action twice last week.
   In an interview published Friday, he told The Washington Times
he planned to tell Shamir ``we have got to move the peace process
forward.''
   In a White House statement released Saturday, he said the 10th
anniversary of the Egyptian-Israeli treaty ``turns our minds toward
the still more daunting challenges ahead. ... We must commit
ourselves, as Anwar Sadat and Menachem Begin did, to fresh
thinking.''
   President Sadat and Begin, then Israel's prime minister,
negotiated the treaty. Sadat was assassinated in 1981.
 
</TEXT>
</DOC>
