<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     03-27 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Leader Says Rightists Seek Catastrophe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leader Kim Dae-jung said
Monday that ultrarightists in the government and military oppose
democratic reforms and are ``attempting to bring about a catstrophe
by any means.''
   They fear losing their hold on power and ``feel as if their
throats are being choked by demcoratic reforms,'' he said in an
address to the Foreign Press Club.
   Kim also said he is opposed to a referendum on President Roh
Tae-woo's administration and that he favors the presence of
American troops in South Korea until peace can be secured with
communist North Korea.
   In other developments:
   _Police detained 23 dissidents who tried to reach the North
Korean border for a reunification meeting with communist delegates
at Panmunjom, the truce site established in the demilitarized zone
under the cease-fire that ended the Korean War in 1953. The
dissidents had defied a government order barring South Koreans from
going to the meeting.
   _Government prosecutors said that a dissident leader, the
Rev.Moon Ik-hwan, would be arrested if he returns to Seoul from an
unauthorized visit to North Korea.
   They said Moon would face prosecution under national security
laws and if convicted could be sentenced to up to 10 years in
prison.
   Moon arrived Saturday in Pyongyang, the North Korean capital,
after a trip to Japan and China. South Korean officials denounced
Moon for a speech he made in Pyongyang in which he called North
Korean leader Kim Il Sung a ``respectable president.''
   Roh announced on March 20 that he was indefinitely postponing
the planned midterm referendum on his government's performance, but
Kim Dae-jung urged the president not to hold such an election.
   He said a referendum could plunge the nation into chaos and
allow extreme rightists to seize control.
   Roh has said he postponed the referendum because radical
leftists were plotting a revolution.
   Kim Dae-jung, leader of the Party for Peace and Democracy, said
it would be premature to conduct a refereundum because Roh has not
carried out all of the democratic reforms he promised during the
election campaign.
   ``Our goal is not to expel him (Roh), but to complete work for
true democracy,'' he added.
   Some observers believe Kim Dae-jung does not want a referendum
because polls show he is trailing rival opposition leader Kim
Young-sam.
   They said if the people voted against Roh's administration it
could have forced an election and Kim Young-sam had the best chance
of winning.
   Roh, a former general, won the election in December 1987 after
Kim Dae-jung and Kim Young-sam split the opposition vote.
   Kim Dae-jung rejected the anti-Americanism of many radical
groups that are demanding the withdrawal of the 43,000 U.S.
military personnel based in South Korea.
   He said he favored Amerian troops remaining here until a
permanent peace with North Korea is assured.
</TEXT>
