<HEAD>Eds: Adds new last graf with additional appointment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush plans to nominate Alfred A.
DelliBovi, a former New York state legislator who was a
transportation official in the Reagan administration, as
undersecretary of housing and urban development, the White House
announced Monday.
   DelliBovi has been administrator of the Urban Mass
Transportation Administration since 1987. Before that, he had been
deputy administrator since 1984 and regional administrator for New
York from 1981 to 1984. He was a member of the New York State
Assembly from 1971 to 1978.
   The White House also announced that the president intends to
nominate William G. Rosenberg to be an assistant administrator of
the Environmental Protection Agency. Rosenberg has been chairman of
The Investment Group in Ann Arbor, Mich., and Washington since 1982.
   In addition, the White House said the president will nominate
Francis Anthony Keating II, the outgoing associate attorney
general, as general counsel of the Department of Housing and Urban
Development. Keating was assistant secretary of the Treasury for
enforcement from 1955 to 1958 and before that was U.S. attorney for
the Northern District of Oklahoma.
   In another personnel announcement, the White House said Bush
will nominate John C. Weicher, associate director for economic
policy in the Office of Management and Budget since 1987, to be
assistant secretary of housing and urban development for policy
development and research.
