<FILEID>AP-NR-03-27-89 2126EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-TMI-Kemeny     03-27 0614</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-TMI-Kemeny,0632</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chairman Of Presidential TMI Panel Praises Nuke Industry Progress</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-TMI Remembered, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MOKRZYCKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HANOVER, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the presidential commission
that investigated the Three Mile Island accident said Monday that
the nuclear power industry apparently has heeded the panel's
recommendations and become more safety conscious.
   ``We warned them that unless they changed their attitude
completely they would be out of business, and it sounds to me as if
they took it to heart,'' John Kemeny said on the eve of the 10th
anniversary of the nation's worst atomic power accident.
   Kemeny, a former Dartmouth College president, based his
assessment on a recent report by the Institute of Nuclear Power
Operations, a group the industry established after Three Mile
Island to work on safety issues. The institute concluded that the
nation's 111 nuclear power plants now licensed are safer and more
efficient.
   ``I'm not saying that every problem has been fixed,'' Kemeny
said in an interview. But he said it was ``very hard for me to
believe that it's the same industry we really tore apart 10 years
ago.''
   Still, Kemeny said he was concerned that the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission may have become even more mired in a maze of regulations
that don't necessarily insure safety.
   Referring to reports that the NRC mandated 149 changes based on
his commission's recommendations, Kemeny said: ``That's typical
madness to me. I wish they had mandated 40 important (changes).
They'd have a much better chance of compliance.''
   Kemeny, 62, is a mathematician who had a small role in the
Manhattan Project that developed the first atomic bomb during World
War II, and who later worked as a research assistant to Albert
Einstein. President Carter appointed Kemeny to head a 12-member
commission to investigate the Three Mile Island accident.
   The panel spent six months investigating the March 28, 1979,
partial meltdown at the nuclear power plant in Middletown, Pa.
   Among its recommendations that the NRC adopted were establishing
10-mile evacuation-planning zones around commercial reactors and
requiring an array of new control-room equipment to better apprise
operators of a plant's safety status.
   Rep. Edward Markey, D-Mass., charged during the weekend that
nearly four out of five U.S. atomic plants still have failed to
complete all the changes.
   Kemeny did not dispute Markey's allegations, but reached a
different conclusion, noting an NRC official's statement that more
than 97 percent of the changes have been completed.
   ``Remember, these are all changes, none of which were in place
10 years ago,'' Kemeny said. ``I think that's substantial change.''
   Ten years ago Kemeny called the NRC ``the worst government
agency that existed.'' He said he still has concerns.
   ``What we found (then) was that they had such a huge number of
regulations _ they regulated everything, even minute things _ that
many (nuclear plant officials) ... spent all their time making sure
that they met all the regulations, rather than worrying whether
their plant was safe,'' Kemeny said.
   ``I don't mean that those two things are inconsistent, but just
because you meet all the paper regulations does not mean your plant
is safe.''
   Kemeny said he hasn't followed the commission closely in recent
years, but noted that the private Institute of Nuclear Power
Operations duplicates much of the information sharing, inspection
and training that the NRC does, sometimes with stricter standards.
   ``To me that's a suggestion that the industry itself feels that
the NRC is not sufficient,'' Kemeny said.
   ``Let me say one thing for the NRC,'' he added. ``I don't think
regulation alone can solve this problem. Unless the industry has a
commitment to safety, no amount of regulation can solve it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
