<HEAD>Engine Problems Force 747 Back To Airport</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUCKLAND, New Zealand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A United Airlines Boeing 747 jumbo
jet was forced to return to Auckland Airport on Monday night with
engine problems, a spokesman for the American carrier said.
   Flight 812 was on its way to Honolulu carrying 280 passengers
and 18 crew when one of its four engines malfunctioned, United
spokesman Wayne Dodge said Tuesday.
   The engine was shut down and the captain dumped fuel before
landing safely 45 minutes after takeoff. Some passengers and
witnesses on the ground reported seeing flames, the New Zealand
Press Association reported.
   ``I saw a flash of flame in the pilot's far right-hand engine
and then there was a big boom like a sonic boom. The flame seemed
to last a few seconds,'' the news agency quoted witness Bob McElroy
as saying.
   Dodge, the airline's New Zealand general manager, said there was
no fire. Sometimes there is ``a bit of a flash'' when an engine was
shut down, he said.
   Last month, nine people were sucked to their deaths when a
fuselage section ripped off a United Boeing 747 en route from
Honolulu to Auckland.
