<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 100 passengers on a Continental
Airlines flight bound for Los Angeles had to return here and spend
the night after their flight was aborted when an engine
malfunctioned moments after takeoff.
   The jet touched down early Monday morning at Houston
Intercontinental Airport 10 minutes after takeoff, officials said.
   The 113 passengers were given overnight accommodations and
rescheduled on later flights, said Continental spokesman David
Messing.
   Only 10 to 20 seconds after leaving the runway, the pilot
radioed the airport tower, saying one of the Airbus A300's two
engines was not working.
   ``She sounded real good _ no problems,'' Richard Lackey, an air
traffic control specialist, said of the pilot. ``She just said they
shut down No. 2 engine and they were going to come back and land.''
   A Continental spokesman said the engine was not completely shut
down, but put on what would be the equivalent of idle. He said he
did not know what caused the problem.
