<FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     03-27 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Warm Weather in East, Midwest, Thunderstorms in Texas, Oklahoma</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Warm air spread through the Northeast and Great Lakes states on
Monday, toppling temperature records and causing some spring
flooding. Texas and Oklahoma were pounded by thunderstorms and hail.
   Tornadoes were spotted in southwest Oklahoma during a storm that
packed 70 mph winds and caused damage at a trailer park near
Woodward. Hail the size of tennis balls fell amid the thunderstorms
at Giles, Texas.
   Tornado watches were in effect from east central and south
central Kansas to far western Oklahoma and the eastern part of
Texas panhandle and portions of southwest Texas.
   An unseasonably warm air mass carried spring weather into the
Great Lakes and along much of the Eastern Seaboard.
   It was 78 degrees in Rochester, N.Y., the highest temperature
there since last Oct. 1. Records for the date also were set in at
least 25 other places, including Dulles International Airport in
Washington, where it was 78; Buffalo, N.Y. (72); Alpena, Mich.
(65); Cleveland (80); Greer, S.C. (78); Youngstown, Ohio (77);
Charleston, W.V. (80); and Meridian, Miss (85).
   The high of 80 degrees in Des Moines, Iowa, tied a 94-year-old
record for the date.
   The warm weather caused a rapid snowmelt in northern sections of
Minnesota, Wisconsin and Michigan. Some flooding was reported in
Wisconsin as creeks swelled due to the melted snow.
   Dense fog formed overnight from eastern portions of the Dakotas
to the upper Mississippi Valley and the northern Great Lakes.
   There were thunderstorms in the northern Great Lakes and light
rain from the lower Ohio Valley into western Tennessee. Rain also
was reported in the Pacific Northwest, and there were scattered
showers in the northern Rockies.
   Sunshine and relatively cool temperatures prevailed in the
Southwest, where Yuma, Ariz., and Palm Springs, Calif., reported
temperatures of just 70 degrees at 11 am PST.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 pm EST ranged from 31
degrees at Yellowstone, Wyo., to 90 degrees at Harlingen, Texas.
The nation's low was 15 degrees at Flagstaff, Ariz.
   The forecast for Tuesday called for showers and thunderstorms
from Texas to the Mississippi and Ohio valleys, the southern Great
Lakes; scattered showers in the northern Great Lakes and northern
New England; widespread rain from the Pacific Northwest to Idaho
and western Montana; and windy conditions in the northern Rockies,
the Intermountain West and the Pacific Northwest.
   High temperatures were predicted in the 40s from eastern North
Dakota to northern Minnesota and northern Michigan; 70s and 80s
from Southern California to the desert Southwest and from the
southern Plains to the lower and middle Mississippi Valley, the
middle and south Atlantic coastal states; 70s extending north into
parts of New York state and southern New England; and in the 50s
and 60s elsewhere.
</TEXT>
