<FIRST>u i AM-DividedCouple 1stLd-Writethru   03-27 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Divided Couple, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0563,0456</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Says She'll Give Birth in Camper in Front of Chinese Embassy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with Italian Embassy in Beijing saying
China ready to let husband leave. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman said Monday she will give birth in a camper
parked outside the Chinese Embassy to protest China's refusal to
let her husband join her in Italy.
   Chinese authorities are ready to let Zhu Juwang leave the
country, but first want him to clear up what they regard as
slanderous charges against the government, an Italian Embassy
official in Beijing said.
   Patrizia Riccardi is expected to give birth to the child's
second couple within days.
   She said she met her husband at a reception in 1986 in
Switzerland, where Zhu was employed with the Chinese delegation to
the United Nations.
   Zhu and Ms. Riccardi were married in Beijing two years later,
after the birth of their first child, David, and after Zhu
renounced the diplomatic post that under Chinese law prevented him
from marrying a foreigner.
   Ms. Riccardi, 33, said the Chinese government has confiscated
her 28-year-old husband's passport and won't allow him out of the
country. She said she had written to Pope John Paul II and Italian
Foreign Minster Giulio Andreotti seeking their intervention.
   In Beijing, Embassy First Secretary Maria Assunta Accili
Sabbatini said, ``We've been told several times by the Chinese
government that they are willing to permit him to join his wife''
once a dispute over his departure from his U.N. post in Geneva in
resolved.
   She said Zhu was in Shanghai waiting for permission to leave
China.
   Chinese authorities have accused Zhu of slandering the
government in a letter written to the United Nations in which he
reportedly says he was forced to quit his job because of his
marriage to a foreigner, Mrs. Sabbatini said.
   The Chinese government says Zhu resigned voluntarily and that
they replaced his diplomatic passport with an ordinary one after
his marriage. The second passport was confiscated after he wrote
the letter to the United Nations, officials say.
   Mrs. Sabbatini said the Chinese told the embassy they were
discussing the matter with U.N. officials in Geneva and New York
and would issue Zhu a passport once the question of his resignation
is clarified.
   She said the Chinese ``don't like very much what his wife is
doing in Italy.''
   Ms. Riccardi has been living in the camper near the embassy for
several days and the police haven't done anything about it. When
informed of her plans to have a baby in the camper, a police
officers said she has a right to do in it what she wants.
</TEXT>
