<FILEID>AP-NR-03-27-89 0755EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-APArts:VendingMachineArt Adv28   03-27 0556</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP Arts: Vending Machine Art, Adv 28,0569</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 28</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tues PMs, March 28 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Vending Machine Gallery Big Hit In Europe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The night is dark and dismal on Dresdener Street.
Suddenly, bizarre lights and music burst from a rusty old vending
machine as miniature monsters stare sinisterly from inside.
   No, this is not ``The Twilight Zone.''
   It's the ``Blumenautomat Galerie,'' where a few coins buy
strange, tiny sculptures created by Georg Glueckman and Suwan
Laimanee, and a show that keeps fans coming back for more.
   In its previous life, the ``Blumenautomat Galerie'' (Flower
Automat Gallery) was an after-hours vending machine that dispensed
posies to passers-by.
   But now it is one of the most talked about multimedia art events
in Europe, pulling its creators out of years of obscurity.
   Glueckman and Laimanee came up with the idea as an alternative
means of promoting their modernistic concept of art, and say it is
Europe's only 24-hour art gallery.
   ``This is not what you would call a conventional exhibition.
It's not what you would call a normal thing,''' acknowledged the
wry, 37-year-old Laimanee, who is originally from Thailand.
   The man-size automat is bolted to a wall on dimly lighted
Dresdener Street, a cul-de-sac in one of the poorest sections of
West Berlin. Placed inside the machine's 12 compartments are
toy-like creations made by Laimanee and Glueckman at the
made-to-sell price of about $3.80 each.
   The Flower Automat Gallery is a humble but eerie-looking
machine. Indeed, sometimes it seems to have a life of its own.
   Laimanee deposits coins and pulls a bug-eyed monster sculpture
from one of the compartments. The left-hand side of the rusty
machine bursts into a brilliant light show, to the accompaniment of
strange music put together by Laimanee and Glueckman on a tape
recorder. Two minutes later, the show is over and the vending
machine has returned to a state of repose.
   ``Our Flower Automat Gallery is really a work of art in
itself,'' said Laimanee.
   Every four weeks the artists change the miniature creations and
play host for the premiere of a new show. Laimanee also has to fill
up the machine every day because of the great public demand.
   The Flower Automat Gallery has captured the curiousity of arts
enthusiasts across Europe. Articles have been written by the
Munich-based New Art in Europe magazine, West Germany's respected
Die Zeit weekly newspaper and other publications. Laimanee and
Glueckman have been interviewed in television programs that have
reached audiences from Belgium to Austria.
   Their fame last year resulted in an invitation to show their
larger works _ creations known as ``room installations'' _ in
Warsaw, Poland.
   For years, Laimanee and Glueckman took the traditional route of
displaying their larger works in rented Berlin rooms.
   Their break came in 1987 when they noticed the flower vending
machine across the street from the up-and-coming Zwinger Art
Gallery. They picked up the automat free of charge from a flower
shop that no longer used it.
   The Flower Automat Gallery was an immediate success when it
opened in October 1987, thriving on the ready market of curious
patrons of the Zwinger Gallery.
   ``It's not big money and we're not getting rich, but we can pay
our bills,'' Laimanee said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Tues March 28</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890327-0172 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-27-89 0807EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i PM-RhodesianSoldier Adv03   03-27 0991</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rhodesian Soldier, Adv 03,1017</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon PMs April 3 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Former Rhodesian Soldier Lambasts Former White Rulers in Book</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIDRIKKE SCHANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As a Rhodesian soldier, Bruce Moore-King
believed the good were white, the evil were black and the war he
fought was a noble struggle waged in the name of Christian
democracy.
   A decade later, he is convinced the war to prevent black
majority rule was immoral and looks back with shame at how he and
thousands of other white Rhodesians accepted ``simplistic,
jingoistic nonsense'' from their leaders.
   Far worse, he says his fellow whites still hold blacks in
contempt and he fears they are throwing away their last chance for
peace in the land now called Zimbabwe.
   Once a member of an elite counterguerrilla force, the Grey
Scouts, Moore-King has written the first published reproval of the
seven-year war by a former supporter of white rule.
   In ``White Man Black War,'' Moore-King accuses the leaders _
``Elders,'' he calls them _ in what was the breakaway British
colony of Rhodesia of an inflexibility that led to the deaths of
1,400 whites and 27,000 blacks before the white minority gave up
power under British pressure in 1978.
   ``These Elders valued the comfort of their lifestyles beyond the
lives of their children,'' Moore-King writes in the book published
by Zimbabwe's year-old Baobab Books. ``It was greed that sent us to
war.''
   The 134-page volume has caused a stir among blacks and whites
who fought or lived through the conflict that ended with Rhodesia's
transition to independent, black-governed Zimbabwe. It provoked
numerous reviews in the local media, with one white lawyer saying
the book ``was like peeling a scab off and seeing how well the
wound was healing.''
   Moore-King's unforgiving and brutal accounts of war atrocities
form the basis of his scathing indictment of Rhodesia's leaders. He
particularly assails Ian Smith, the prime minister of Rhodesia,
calling him the whites' ``High Priest.''
   ``Mr. Smith, along with the farmers, businessmen, and other
politicians told us that we were not fighting to persecute,
oppress, or deny our black countrymen _ we killed and burned to
save them from communism,'' Moore-King writes.
   ``The shameful part of our history is not that we were wrong,
just that we were so childishly thoughtless,'' Moore-King said in
an interview at his modest home in Ruwa, about 20 miles east of
Harare (formerly Salisbury), the capital. The house is off a dirt
road surrounded by African bush and black neighbors.
   Moore-King, 36, said the book, published in December and now
into its second printing, was born of anger and fear he felt after
returning to his homeland in 1985 after a seven-year absence.
   ``I feared the whites in this country were screwing up the
opportunity to live in this land,'' he said. ``They have been given
a second chance in a way.''
   An estimated 90,000 whites remain in Zimbabwe out of the 250,000
or so in the early 1970s.
   ``The irony is that having lost the war, we haven't lost the
lifestyle,'' Moore-King added.
   Most whites in Zimbabwe live in spacious homes, many with
swimming pools and tennis courts and cared for by black servants.
   Smith, who still lives in Zimbabwe, said he does not intend to
read ``White Man Black War'' and dismissed Moore-King as a
``crank.''
   ``It seems at one time he was a great Grey Scout,'' said Smith
in a telephone interview. ``Now he's turned against everything he
once believed.''
   Moore-King, who is bearded, broad and imposingly tall, was a
sergeant in the Grey Scouts, a mounted infantry unit used as a
mobile fireforce and specializing in high-speed tracking.
   In flowing, impressionistic style, his book recounts wanton
destruction, torture and pointless massacres.
   Soldiers mistakenly bomb a schoolhouse in which black civilians
have taken refuge, and 123 are killed. A ``nanny and two pics''
walking home late at night are gunned down by inexperienced young
soldiers who mistake them for guerrillas. A black man hangs
spreadeagled on a steel bed-frame while a soldier sends electric
jolts through wires attached to his scrotum and a nipple.
   Moore-King left Rhodesia in 1978 and wandered around Europe for
several years, still believing the war was a noble affair.
   ``I swore I wasn't a racist and justified it by saying I didn't
hate black people, they just weren't ready for independence,'' he
said.
   Moore-King's attitude began to shift when he went to South
Africa in the early 1980s and worked at an insurance agency on an
equal basis with blacks.
   When he returned to Zimbabwe upon the death of his parents he
feared retaliation by the black government. Instead, he said, he
was welcomed back by blacks who treated him with respect.
   But he found attitudes little changed among whites.
   In his book, Moore-King tells of a moment soon after his return
when his landlord found him sharing tea on his porch with a black
neighbor. Not only were Moore-King and his wife evicted, but the
landlord locked the vegetable garden Moore-King had left to his
black friend. The book paints the pitiful scene of the hungry black
man looking longingly through a fence at tomatoes rotting on the
vine.
   ``It was one of a number of things that I thought were repugnant
morally, but also dangerous and stupid the way anger was being
stirred up in blacks,'' said Moore-King, who plans soon to leave
his job as a Harare insurance agent to work on his second book.
   ``I can understand now why our countrymen took up arms against
us,'' he wrote in his first book. ``And if these actions and
attitudes and forms of selective ignorance displayed by my tribe
once caused blood and fire to spread across the land called
Rhodesia, what will these same actions and attitudes and forms of
selective ignorance produce in this land called Zimbabwe?''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Mon PMs April 3</NOTE>
</DOC>
