<FIRST>a a BC-History Adv04   03-27 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-History, Adv04,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv04</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tuesday, April 4</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Tuesday, April 4, the 94th day of 1989. There are 271
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   On April 4, 1968, civil rights leader Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.
was shot to death in Memphis, Tenn., where he had gone to support a
strike by sanitation workers. He was 39.
   On this date:
   In 1818, Congress decided the flag of the United States should
consist of 13 red and white stripes and 20 stars, with a new star
to be added for every new state of the Union.
   In 1841, one month after his inaugural, President William Henry
Harrison succumbed to pneumonia, becoming the first U.S. chief
executive to die while in office.
   In 1850, the city of Los Angeles was incorporated.
   In 1887, Susanna Medora Salter became the first woman to be
elected mayor of an American community, Argonia, Kan.
   In 1902, British financier Cecil Rhodes left $10 million in his
will to provide scholarships for Americans at Oxford University.
   In 1949, 12 nations, including the United States, signed the
North Atlantic Treaty, which laid the groundwork for the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization.
   In 1969, a surgical team in Houston led by Dr. Denton Cooley
implanted a temporary artificial heart in a 47-year-old patient
while awaiting a human donor heart. The patient, Haskell Karp, died
April 8, one day after receiving a human heart.
   In 1974, Hank Aaron of the Atlanta Braves tied Babe Ruth's
home-run record by hitting his 714th round-tripper in Cincinnati.
   In 1975, more than 130 people, most of them children, were
killed when a U.S. Air Force transport plane evacuating Vietnamese
orphans crashed shortly after take-off from Saigon.
   In 1977, 72 people were killed when a Southern Airways DC-9
crashed in New Hope, Ga.
   In 1983, the space shuttle ``Challenger'' roared into orbit on
its maiden voyage.
   Ten years ago: Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, the deposed prime minister
of Pakistan, was hanged after he was convicted of conspiring to
murder a political opponent in 1974. Several nations, including the
United States, had urged the Pakistani government to spare Bhutto.
   Five years ago: In a statement that drew a sharp response from
Democrats, President Ronald Reagan told reporters that Congress had
to ``take a responsibility'' for undermining U.S. policy in
Lebanon, where more than 260 Marines were killed during
peacekeeping duty.
   One year ago: The Arizona Senate convicted Gov. Evan Mecham of
two charges of official misconduct, and removed him from office.
Mecham became the first U.S. governor to be impeached and removed
from office in nearly six decades.
   Today's Birthdays: Former dance teacher Arthur Murray is 94.
Broadcaster John Cameron Swayze is 83. Composer Elmer Bernstein is
67. Author-poet Maya Angelou is 61. Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind., is
57. The commissioner of major league baseball, A. Bartlett
Giamatti, is 51. Actress Catherine Spaak is 44. Actress Christine
Lahti is 39. Actress Nancy McKeon is 23.
   Thought for today: ``Injustice anywhere is a threat to justice
everywhere.'' _ Martin Luther King Jr. (1929-1968).
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for use Tuesday, April 4</NOTE>
