<HEAD>$Adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 9</HEAD>
<HEAD>EAGLESWOOD TOWNSHIP, N.J.: their property.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Newsletters from the Pinelands Landowners Society accused the
state of ``trying to preserve land by essentially confiscating
it...Meanwhile, taxes continue to be paid by landowners held
hostage by the plan.''
   Researchers continue to study the Pinelands' fragile ecosystem,
right down to the rare Pine Barrens tree frog and the curly grass
fern.
   Medical research also has been conducted in the Pinelands. Last
year, Squibb Corp. microbiologists announced that a new family of
microbiotics could be developed from Pinelands soil.
   But for all the Pinelands' beauty and benefits, it is
overshadowed as a tourist destination by the popular shore region
and relatively few people take advantage of the reserve. Scattered
through the scenic Pinelands are attractions such as the historic
Batsto Village, a preserved iron-making facility, and a host of
hiking trails and rivers for canoeing.
   ``I don't think there is enough of an understanding in the state
as to what the Pinelands means and how important it is,'' Moore
says. ``Most people think it's just a boring, flat landscape.''
   Although the Pinelands' significance may not be widely and fully
appreciated, and its preservation fought by some, the Pinelands
Management Does Tanya have any advice for her sister?
   ``Stay in school and don't have kids until you finish school.''
   Samantha Jones, a 17-year-old graduate of Beach Channel High
School in Rockaway, says the pregnant teen-agers she knows ``really
don't understand that once that baby's born, it's going to be hard
to feed them and clothe them and take 'em places and stuff like
that. And that they can't really do the things that they used to
do.''
   But when asked if she used birth control, she said, ``Sometimes,
but not really. No. But I'm supposed to start on it soon. But not
now.''
   Katie Trieller, the clinical nurse specialist at Woodmere, says
that kind of carelessness is common among teen-agers of every
stripe.
   ``In the last five years, with the media talking about herpes
and AIDS, adults are being more careful about sex,'' she says.
``It's not affecting the adolescent population because they think
they're omnipotent. That's their modus operandi: `I'm not going to
get pregnant. I'm not going to get VD.'''
   Sharon Redman, the Valley Stream teen who learned the hard way
that she was not immune to pregnancy, laments her abortioo kill a baby,''
she says, ``but I
was only 17 at the time and still in school and I was working and
my boyfriend was still in school at the time, and his mother never
knew. She'd probably be upset if she ever found out.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 9</NOTE>
