<FIRST>s i BC-ContinentinCrisis-Argentina Adv02-2Takes   03-27 0819</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Continent in Crisis-Argentina, Adv 02-2 Takes,0837</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv02</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 2, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>CONTINENT IN CRISIS: Argentina _ The Long Fall from Riches</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto, LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   To look at Argentina is to look at a nation that
has everything going for it. But nothing is. This is one of a
series of periodic reports by The Associated Press on the economic,
social and political turbulence that has turned South America into
a continent in crisis.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By ED McCULLOUGH</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The way things are today, it is
hard to believe that after World War II Argentina was one of the
wealthiest nations in the world.
   Many Argentines today date the steady decline of their economic
fortunes since then to a day in February, 1946, when Gen. Juan
Domingo Peron visited the Central Bank after being elected
president and came out marveling at the pile of gold bars he saw
inside.
   ``You can hardly walk through the corridors,'' he remarked.
   Argentines still cite those words in looking back.
   They still have as high a standard of living as anyone in South
America, but they no longer are rich and many blame that on Peron
and his policies which still exerting influence long after his
heyday and 14 years after his death.
   He nationalized industries, regulated wages and prices and work
conditions, expanded public employment and social welfare programs,
convinced millions of Argentines that big government was best. He
created a political party that bears his name to carry out his
vision.
   Today, one worker of every six is employed by the government _
about 2 million overall in a population of 30 million. The state
subsidizes an estimated 300 companies. The budget usually is in
deficit. Natural resources go untapped. Private industry chafes at
myriad regulations.
   ``The state, from 1945 to now, has gotten a little bigger every
year, and it has long since reached the point where it can be
sustained,'' says Juan Jose Cresto, chairman of the department of
economics at the University of Buenos Aires.
   ``Everyone realizes what the problem is, but there is no general
agreement on a solution,'' says Enrique Szewach, chief economist at
the independent Latin America Research Foundation.
   The dominance of the state has been one constant in a political
and economic maelstrom that has hampered development in a country
blessed with resources.
   Over the years, soldiers ousted civilians and democratic rule
gave way to dictatorship. The political and economic ``rules of the
game'' changed quickly and often.
   New regimes have tried to wipe out what came before rather than
build on what may have been achieved.
   Economically, currency-exchange rates have been undervalued and
then overvalued. Business has been protected and then forced to
face international competition. Wages and prices have been
controlled and then set by market forces. Exports have been favored
and then imports, agriculture and then industry.
   Meanwhile, the country slipped into decline _ despite fertile
cropland and a temperate climate, rich fishing grounds, abundant
deposits of oil, natural gas and uranium, rivers that can be tapped
for hydroelectric power, and a literate population not divided by
language, religion or race.
   The gross domestic product has stagnated at about $80 billion
for a decade. Annual per capita income dropped to the equivalent of
$1,630 in 1988 from $1,990 in 1980, according to the World Bank.
   Raul Alfonsin, 62, an attorney and human rights leader, has been
president since December 1983. Already, he has outlasted all his
predecessors since Peron, but his tenure has been rocky.
   The military, which unseated Peron in 1955, Arturo Frondizi in
1962, Arturo Illia in 1966 and the widow Isabel Peron in 1976, has
had minor revolts in its ranks three times in the past two years.
Human rights groups and other critics maintain the military is
agitating again for political power.
   The radical left also has not given up, despite the brutal
crackdown on subversives beginning with Isabel Peron's government
in 1974 and carried on by the 1976-83 military regime in which at
least 8,963 Argentine civilians were arrested, never seen again and
presumed executed, according to the findings of a commission set up
by Alfonsin. But human rights groups, among them Amnesty
International, estimate the number of people who disappeared _
``desaparecidos'' _ at 10,000 to 30,000.
   Few expect any outbreak of violence such as that recently in
Venezuela, but if it happens the spark might come from an economy
that neither soldiers nor civilians have been able to control.
   Inflation has been at triple-digit rates in 13 of the past 14
years _ climbing from 24.39 percent in 1974 to 688 percent in 1984
and down to 387.70 percent last year. Unemployment and
under-employment stand at a combined 14 percent. The austral
currency is devalued every month, and wages often fail to keep up
with inflation.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
