<DOCNO> AP890327-0194 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-27-89 1355EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-ContinentinCrisis-Argentina Adv02-1stadd   03-27 0612</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Continent in Crisis-Argentina, Adv 02-1st add,0628</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv02</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 2, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>BUENOS AIRES: with inflation.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Looming over everything is the nearly $59-billion foreign debt,
for which there is almost nothing to show. The military borrowed
heavily to balance the budget in the late 1970s.
   It also used the money to buy military equipment, build highways
through Buenos Aires, subsidize military-run industries and inject
money into chronically inefficient state-owned companies. It used
some of the money to play host to the World Soccer Cup tournament
in 1978.
   Alfonsin has borrowed mostly to pay the interest on the debt
but, by his own admission, has paid only 50 percent of the interest
due. Argentina's international credit rating now is classified as
``substandard'' and is on the verge dropping to ``value impaired''
because of noncompliance with interest payments.
   Debt repayment now costs $6 billion a year and consumes _ or
would if the government paid it _ more than one-half of total
export earnings. The Central Bank is $2.5 billion in arrears.
   In human terms, people who used to drive to work now take the
bus or subway. Home ownership for many is out of the question.
Vacations are shorter and closer to home. University graduates are
emigrating in increasing numbers to Europe or the United States.
   Wage strikes by public employees are common and schoolchildren
stay home, mail doesn't get delivered, businesmen go to work in car
pools.
   The General Labor Confederation has staged 13 general strikes
since Alfonsin became president.
   The 4-million-member confederation, which was forged by Peron,
is lending considerable support to the Peronist Party's candidate,
Carlos Menem, in the presidential elections set for May 14.
   Perhaps Alfonsin's biggest accomplishment has been to hold
together a fragile democracy and fractious republic for five years.
A main goal, he has said, is to hand over political power to an
elected successor in December. That has not happened since 1928.
   The biggest failure of Alfonsin's military predecessor was the
war with Britain over the Falkland Islands, the Malvinas to
Argentines.
   Alfonsin's biggest failure has been the economy.
   He has tried without much success to cut the federal budget,
reorganize the banking sector, lower trade barriers, increase tax
collections and sell the state telephone company and the national
airline, Aerolineas Argentinas.
   Alfonsin's second major anti-inflation plan collapsed in
February. In the weeks since, the austral has plummeted by 59
percent against the U.S. dollar. Cars valued in australs now seem
half-priced to those with dollars. Apartments selling for dollars
doubled in cost for buyers with australs.
   National elections raise the prospect of more instability.
   Menem, the front-runner, pledges to dramatically improve workers
wages and hints he might not continue payments on the foreign debt.
He talks vaguely of a ``productive revolution'' to spur growth and
a ``social pact'' to resolve tensions.
   His main challenger, Eduardo Angeloz of Alfonsin's Radical Civic
Union, pledges to balance the budget, attract foreign investment
and sell off state companies despite the opposition of unions.
   Compounding matters, the election could wind up in the Electoral
College, where conservative third-party candidate Alvaro Alsogaray
may hold the votes to push one or the other _ probably Angeloz _
past the required 50 percent of 600 electors.
   In a recent television interview, Alsogaray, 75, said his
grandchildren asked him whether they should study for a career in
Argentina, or emigrate.
   ``I told them they should go abroad,'' he said.
   A return to the days of the 1920s and 1930s, when beef and grain
exports to Europe propelled Argentina into the top 10 countries in
per capita income, is beyond anyone's hope now.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 2</NOTE>
<TEXT>
