<FILEID>AP-NR-03-27-89 1357EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-Haiti-Democracy Adv02   03-27 1095</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Haiti-Democracy, Adv 02,1130</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv02</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 2, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Six Months After Coup, Democracy Remains Elusive in Haiti</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANA HAYWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ In a roofless, burned-out church,
the congregation sings hymns in Creole about death and crushed
dreams.
   ``They kill us in the street, they kill us in our homes, they
kill us inside church.''
   The words flowed from 200 or so worshipers during Mass at St.
Jean Bosco Roman Catholic Church in the midst of slum.
   ``The problems of our country make us die like animals.
   ``Democracy. Democracy.''
   In September thugs with machetes, guns and spikes stormed into
St. Jean Bosco during Mass, killing 13 people and wounding 70
others before setting the church afire with gasoline. A week later,
on Sept. 17, rank-and-file soldiers revolted and put Lt. Gen.
Prosper Avril in power.
   They overthrew Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy and stirred hopes for
democracy at last in Haiti.
   The Caribbean-island nation has known almost nothing but brutal
dictatorships since winning independence from France in 1804 _ the
first slave state to become a nation.
   Today, six months after Avril took over and three years after
dictator Jean-Claude ``Baby Doc'' Duvalier flew to exile in France,
there is disillusionment over the pace of promised democratic
reforms, while allegations of human-rights violations continue.
   But Avril, who holds a law degree, has made some, albeit slow,
progress toward his pled an
elected government. His government maintains democracy is the only
path for the poorest country in the Western Hemisphere.
   ``We've had dictatorships for 184 years and we are still the
least developing nation in Latin America. So something is wrong
with how we governed,'' said Foreign Minister Serge Elie Charles in
an interview. ``Democracy is not a choice; it's an imperative.''
   In February, Avril approved the formation of an independent
council to oversee eventual elections and he recently restored 291
articles of the 1987 constitution, suspended in June by Namphy. But
37 articles that mostly restricted the army's role were not revived
because, Avril said, they were inconsistent with a de facto
government.
   ``You can't expect this government to behave like a
democratically elected government,'' sociologist Leopold Berlanger,
head of the Haitian Research and Development Institute, said in an
interview. ``Avril is a product of the system.
   ``The only thing we have to expect is that he assures a secure,
fair and honest democratic process.''
   The 50-year-old Avril was Duvalier's close financial adviser and
people still associate him with the old regime. Many charge he is
making reforms merely to win back $70 million in U.S. economic
assistance. The aid was frozen Nov. 29, 1987, after goonsquads
killed 34 people voting in the country's first election in 30 years.
   The U.S. State Department has said it won't renew aid until
democratic government is in place but Congress could release some
funds in the meantime as an incentive.
   With about 80 percent of the country's 5.5 million people living
in dire poverty, Haiti desperately needs help.
   ``Witholding aid has been very negative,'' said the foreign
minister. ``The social-economic factors have worsened so we cannot
say how these measures have in any way advanced democracy.''
   This year, labor strikes and sporadic demonstrations broke out
in Port-au-Prince, the capital, and in the provinces with demands
for Avril to step down.
   America's Watch and other human rights groups say abuses and
arbitrary arrests by the army and paramilitary groups continue to
be made of people in peasant organizations, labor unions and church
groups.
   ``The basic human rights situation has not changed,'' said
Robert Duval, who was a political prisoner under Jean Claude
Duvalier and today runs a human rights group. ``In the last weeks
we have found one to two bodies a night as a result of the
political situation.''
   Duvalier's feared private militia, the Tonton Macoute, was
disbanded after Jean-Claude fled and some were integrated into the
7,000-member army. But they were chased out by soldiers who brought
Avril to power.
   Although disorganized, the army wields considerable power.
   ``You're not going to get to power if there's not a reasonable
understanding with those guys,'' said presidenial hopeful Marc
Bazin, a former Finance Minister and World Bank economist. ``You
would be killed or disappear one morning.''
   Optimism waned a month after Avril took office when the soldiers
who put him in power were jailed, accused of plotting a coup. Three
months later, they were released. No explanation was given.
   But the tide turned in late December when Avril gave Franck
Romain, the notorious mayor of Port-Au-Prince, safe passage to the
Dominican Republic, which shares the island of Hispaniola with
Haiti.
   Romain, a retired colonel, was believed to have orchestrated the
church massacre and was implicated in the one against voters in
1987.
   ``Giving Romain safe conduct showed the tendency of the
government to preserve the status quo and encourage the
Duvalierists to stay on _ not to pursue the murderers of Nov. 29 or
the church massacre,'' said Louis Dejoie II, son of popular
industrialist who lost to Francois Duvalier, Jean-Claude's father,
in the disputed 1957 election.
   Fears also abound that elections would again be disrupted or
rigged, as was believed the case in the elections Jan. 17, 1988,
when frightened voters stayed home and Leslie Manigat came to power
amid allegations of fraud. Manigat was overthrown by Namphy five
months later.
   ``International pressure would have to be great so they can't
repeat the events of November or of January's sham election,'' said
sociologist Hubert de Ronceray, the runner-up in the 1988 election.
   About a dozen opposition parties and an array of organizations
have emerged since 1986 but are divided.
   ``The democratic process depends on confidence building between
the army and civilians,'' a Western diplomat said. ``Civilians have
to trust the army to take its role but not to take control. And you
have to have the willingness of the existing government, the
quietude of the far left and the tolerance of the far right.''
   No one predicts what will happen.
   The Communist Party, the grassroots ``popular church'' and
leftist unions are influential with peasants and the poor. These
groups want Avril to step down and allow a coalition government to
govern until elections.
   Many say Avril is caught in the middle.
   ``He risks being overthrown if he doesn't make enough progress.
He risks it if he does,'' said the diplomat, speaking on condition
of anonymity. ``So he's trying to maintain an equilibrium.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 2</NOTE>
</DOC>
