<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--FilmReviews Adv00   03-27 0896</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Film Reviews, Adv 00,0927</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>At the Movies: ``Rooftops,'' ``SING''</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ``SING'' opens March 31.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Rooftops''
   
   Let's hear it for the septuagenarian film director.
   Charles Crichton, who made ``The Lavender Hill Mob'' and other
comedy classics, scored an Academy Award nomination at 78 for his
rollicking ``A Fish Named Wanda.'' Samuel Fuller (``Pickup on South
Street'') is starting another action movie at 77. Now Robert Wise,
74, has a new film, ``Rooftops.''
   It's not in the range of Wise's ``West Side Story,'' to which it
is inevitably compared. But ``Rooftops'' is handsomely produced,
directed with kinetic energy and skillfully acted by a youthful
cast.
   Amazingly, ``Rooftops'' was produced on the streets and of New
York City for $8 million. Wise's last movie, ``Star Trek: The
Motion Picture,'' reportedly cost $50 million.
   Like ``West Side Story,'' ``Rooftops'' deals with urban warfare.
The setting is Manhattan's lower East Side, where homeless
teen-agers live on top of abandoned tenements and earn a meager
living by scrounging used plumbing and auto parts. They are at odds
with punk gangs and, on a more sinister level, the venomous drug
dealers.
   A straight-arrow loner known only as T (Jason Gedrick) pumps
iron at his watertower apartment and tries to stay out of trouble.
Then he falls for Elena (Troy Beyer), a virtuous girl who has been
trapped into serving as lookout for her drug-dealing cousin, Lobo
(Eddie Velez). Conflict builds to a violent showdown, with T and a
few allies mismatched against Lobo and his thugs.
   While not a musical per se, ``Rooftops'' is scored to continuous
rock music by David Stewart of the Eurythmics, and Michael Kamen of
Pink Floyd. Plenty of lively choreography is provided by the
capoeira, an Afro-Brazilian exercise that combines karate with
ballet.
   Wise's direction is a marvel, capturing the action while drawing
credible performances. The stumbling point is Terence Brennan's
script, which lacks surprise and explores no new ground in the
struggle of survival in the big-city jungle.
   Jason Gedrick supplies a strong, sullen presence as the hero,
and Eddie Velez is appropriately terrifying as the heavy. Troy
Beyer's unspoiled beauty and dramatic depth indicate a promising
future. Young Alexis Cruz provides bright moments as the
spray-paint artist Squeak.
   The New Visions Picture was produced by Howard W. Koch Jr., and
bears an R rating, for language and violence. Running time: 95
minutes.
   _ By Bob Thomas, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``SING''
   
   Generations of Brooklyn high school students have enjoyed one of
academia's most popular traditions, Sing. The school song and dance
competition between grades at individual schools such as Erasmus
Hall and Midwood was a joyous and spirited event. It bubbled like
the 2 cents plain at Jahn's ice cream parlor.
   Unfortunately, Richard Baskin's recreation of that spirited show
in ``SING'' is as flat as a stale egg cream. It was written by Dean
Pitchford, and has the same situational formulas as his ``Fame''
and ``Footloose.''
   It stars two newcomers, Peter Dobson and Jessica Steen, who are
appealing enough but lack the power and talent to truly carry a
movie. Louise Lasser, heavier and less frenzied than her ``Mary
Hartman, Mary Hartman'' days, co-stars as Steen's mom. Lorraine
Bracco (``Someone to Watch Over Me''), with a heavy Hollywood-style
Brooklyn accent, portrays a street-tough teacher who returns to her
community.
   Singer Patti LaBelle (``A Soldier's Story'') is the only cast
member who has enough high energy to dominate the screen and infuse
some excitement. But her explosive talent is little used in her
role as a teacher who also works with the Sing committee.
   ``SING'' is centered around the threatened closing of an
imaginary Brooklyn high school where the competition has been a
community tradition. Students, faculty and members of the
neighborhood rally to keep the school open so the skits can be put
on, and to retain a way of life.
   At the same time, a local punk named Dominic (Dobson) is forced
into being a Sing leader by his teacher, Miss Lombardo (Bracco),
who is trying to turn him from a life of crime. Dominic falls in
love with Hannah (Steen), a good student and good girl, and it's
like water mixing with oil.
   The movie is sprinkled with enough perky songs to fill an album.
Pitchford wrote all the lyrics, with music by Tom Snow, Rhett
Lawrence, Patrick Leonard, Jonathan Cain, Martin Page, Tom Kelly,
Desmond Child, Diane Warren and Richard Marx. However, there are
more misses than hits.
   The Craig Zadan production for Tri-Star Pictures leaves one
thirsting for ``West Side Story,'' or even ``To Sir With Love.''
And the producers might take lessons from the former Brooklyn
students who poured so much talent into the Sing competitions:
Barbra Streisand, Neil Diamond, Paul Simon, Art Garfunkel and Neil
Sedaka.
   ``SING'' is rated PG-13.
   _ By Dolores Barclay, AP Arts Editor.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
