<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--HomeVideo Adv00   03-27 0671</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Home Video, Adv 00,0703</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Imagine'' (Warner Home Video. VHS-Beta, $79.95. Rated PG)
   
   ``Imagine'' bills itself as ``the definitive film portrait'' of
musician-poet-pop icon John Lennon. It's too early to judge this
film biography as definitive, but it is certainly a comprehensive,
thoughtful and deeply moving study of the most complicated Beatle.
   Produced by David L. Wolper and directed by Andrew Solt, the
film is a compilation of more than 100 interviews with Lennon
himself, Yoko Ono, his first wife, Cynthia, sons Julian and Sean,
the aunt who raised him, manager Brian Epstein and dozens of other
lesser characters.
   The well-paced production (Wolper and Solt previously
collaborated on ``This Is Elvis'') contains footage of Lennon's
early years in Liverpool, the Beatles' first success in Hamburg,
West Germany, the group's phenomenal U.S. tour, the drugs, the
break-up, life with Yoko, alternating between public and private
glimpses of the artist.
   Highlights include a combative _ and hilarious _ exchange
between Lennon and cartoonist Al Capp, and a poignant performance
of the song ``Imagine'' shortly after Lennon wrote it.
   The film wisely does not end abruptly with Lennon's
assassination in 1980 but moves beyond, showing what his music
meant to an entire generation. The soundtrack, with nearly three
dozen songs, is stunning.
   _ Geneva Collins, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``The Thin Blue Line'' (HBO Home Video. VHS-Beta, $89.99)
   
   Errol Morris' singular documentary about the circumstances that
led to a man being convicted of murdering a Dallas police officer
and condemned to death is at the very least harrowing in its
implications.
   Before you say it couldn't happen to you, read on:
   It was Thanksgiving weekend in 1976 when Randall Dale Adams, a
day laborer with no criminal record, fell in with Richard Harris, a
16-year-old juvenile delinquent. They spent the day hanging out.
   Adams says they split up at 10 p.m. Harris testified that they
were together at midnight, when Officer Robert Wood died during a
routine traffic stop, shot to death by a gun Harris had stolen.
   Harris boasted about killing a cop to friends, but when he
fingered Adams for the crime, he was believed. Adams, who has
maintained he is innocent, landed on death row. His sentence later
was commuted to life in prison.
   What's harrowing is the low-key way in which Morris reconstructs
the crime, offers the testimony of witnesses and conducts
interviews with the principals. Very gradually you realize that
Randall Dale Adams got railroaded by police and prosecutors with
the best intentions in the world. They knew he was guilty; it was
just a case of fitting the facts to conform to that truth.
   ``Rashomon'' this isn't, but powerful and persuasive and
chilling it is.
   As a result of Morris' critically acclaimed effort, Adams'
conviction was overturned.
   In December, a Texas state judge recommended that Adams receive
a new trial or be set free. On Feb. 24, Texas refused, for the
eighth time, to parole him and scheduled its next review for
December 1990.
   But on March 1, the Texas Court of Criminal Appeals ordered a
new trial for him, saying a witness had lied and a prosecutor
suppressed evidence. And on March 23, the Dallas County, Texas,
district attorney dropped the case against Adams, citing a lack of
evidence.
   ``You know, Texas wanted to execute me in '79,'' Adams said in
December. ``So each day past that is a day that I'm alive.''
   _ By Scott Williams, Associated Press Writer
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
