<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews Adv00   03-27 0639</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, Adv 00,0663</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Lyle Lovett and His Large Band'' (Curb-MCA) _ Lyle Lovett
   
   So besides large, just what sort of band is this?
   Listen to the album's instrumental opener, ``The Blues Walk,''
and you might think ``large band'' is just a clever name for 1940s
``big band.'' But wait. Next comes ``Here I Am,'' an odd comic turn
combining spoken-word passages with a blues-rock refrain. Now skip
ahead a few tracks and hear that unmistakable country sound.
   So what sort of band is this? Why, it's a
jazz-blues-swing-R&amp;B-country-western-rock band, of course. And the
individual songs on this fun, quirky album are just as tough to
categorize.
   ``I Married Her Just Because She Looks Like You'' comes closest
to following a standard country formula, but its wry lyrics are a
cut above that standard. ``Good Intentions'' is a sort of talkin'
blues number that could easily come from David Bromberg's songbook.
Then there's ``What Do You Do,'' which starts out as a sassy blues
number, turns into a bar-pickup conversation (Lovett in duet with
vocalist Francine Reed) and slides into the 1936 standard ``The
Glory of Love.''
   Tying all of this together is Lovett's peculiar combination of
cynicism and romanticism that adds an edge to his I-love-you songs
(``I Know You Know'') and a softness to his she-done-me-wrong songs
(``Once Is Enough'').
   This Texan's country roots come out more strongly as the album
plays on. The world could do without Lovett's cover of ``Stand By
Your Man,'' but his reworking of the traditional ``Farther Along''
into the lost-love ballad ``If You Were to Wake Up'' has a simple
charm.
   As for the Large Band, it adapts to the needs of each song,
appearing in various sizes and combinations of instruments
including fiddles, cello and saxophones as well as guitars,
keyboards and drums. More than large _ it's grand.
   _ By Dan Murphy, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Wiener Blut'' (Sire) _ Falco
   
   Falco, the one-time classical music child prodigy who had a No.
1 hit with the unusual ``Rock Me Amadeus'' single in 1986, has
returned after a two-year hiatus with ``Wiener Blut.''
   The record is chock full of the synthesizer-based pop rock so in
vogue today, with its fabricated drums and overblown melodies. But
at its base ``Wiener Blut'' rocks solidly, surprisingly.
   On Side 1, the Austrian-born Falco _ nee Johann Holzel _
collaborates with the Dutch brothers Rob and Ferdi Holland, the
producer-arranger-composer duo that was responsible for ``Rock Me
Amadeus.''
   The result is highly orchestral, almost baroque pop _ lush
synthesizer lines backed by a heavy dance beat and punctuated by
stinging guitar solos. The title cut best typifies this style,
while ``Untouchable'' incorporates the television show's theme into
the melody and ``Satellite to Satellite,'' with its
technology-can-save-us lyrics, combines a spacy synthesizer with a
good rock beat.
   Side 2 leaves the Holland brothers behind. Falco takes charge on
most cuts, and the result is a simpler, more satisfying set of
tunes with more of a message.
   ``Walls of Silence,'' the best cut on ``Wiener Blut,'' is a slow
rocker dealing with the inability of nations to communicate. The
wall of the title represents that inability _ probably best
symbolized by the Berlin wall.
   Falco keeps the beat rocking steady with ``(She's My) Solid
Booze'' and ``Wie Sand Am Himalaya.'' He even checks in with a
spirited version of Steely Dan's 1972 hit ``Do It Again'' that
features Falco's best singing on the record.
   Falco is often silly and vapid. That's too bad, because when he
wants to, he makes some pretty fair rock 'n' roll. Here's hoping he
can stick to the beat.
   _ By Curt Anderson, Associated Press writer
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
