<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--BackwardFlower Adv30   03-27 0668</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--Backward Flower, Adv 30,0686</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv30</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thursday, March 30, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Newly Discovered Flower Gets Sex Backward</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Botanists thought they had plant sex figured
out.
   After all, all 248,000 known flowering plants had the pistil _
the female parts _ in the center, and the stamen _ the male parts _
outside.
   But biologist Esteban Martinez, tromping through three feet of
decaying tropical muck in a chigger-ridden jungle, has proved once
again that little can be taken for granted in science.
   Lacandonia schismatica, a flower the size of a sesame seed, has
the stamen in the center, surrounded by about 50 pistils.
   ``It defies all logic,'' said Warren Stevens, head of research
at the Missouri Botanical Garden in St. Louis. He said a paper on
the discovery will appear in an upcoming issue of Annals of the
Missouri Botanical Garden.
   Martinez, who works at the National University of Mexico, found
the star-shaped flower on a fallen tree trunk in the Lacandon
jungle. At first he thought he'd picked up a type of mushroom, and
it took a year to discover and prove it was an exception to the
sexual rule.
   ``It seems to be some sort of massive mutation. One of the
sacred things has been that the female parts are inside the male,''
Stevens said.
   More study is needed to see what advantage a reverse arrangement
could have. The plant appears to reproduce as other flowering
plants do: pollen from the stamen fertilizes the ovaries, which are
part of the pistils. The ovaries turn into fruit, which produce
seeds.
   Martinez and Clara Hilda Ramos agreed to discuss the discovery
before publication because they believe the plant's habitat is
threatened by logging.
   Cutting was banned last year in the 20-acre site where the plant
has been found, but Martinez said he'd heard that members of the
Chol Indian tribe are seeking permission to cut chicle trees,
valued because their wood resists rot.
   The reserve is in Chiapas state near the Guatemalan border.
   ``We've advised all the authorities in Chiapas and the federal
Ecology Department, and we hope they take the proper measures,''
Martinez said.
   Each plant has four to seven flowers 2 millimeters in diameter,
growing along threadlike stems up to 3{ inches long. The flowers
have six tepals _ a kind of petal _ ending in turned-up points.
They are thickish, something like the fleshy leaves of a jade
plant. In the center is a mound of ovaries encircling an average of
three stamen.
   The plant is a brilliant, almost translucent white, ``like
crystal,'' Ramos said. As the ovaries mature, the center turns
yellow, then to the reddish-brown color of its fruit, so tiny
they're like a fine dust.
   Lacking chlorophyll, the plant gets its energy from decomposing
material in the dark, humid jungle with the help of a fungus that
lives in its roots.
   Martinez and Ramos believe the plant doesn't belong to any
existing family and propose that it be categorized as family
Lacandoniaceae, genus Lacandonia and species schismatica, for the
jungle and the fact that it broke with traditional botanical faith.
   Stevens said the plant is clearly a new genus and species, but
he expects it to fall into the existing family of Triuridaceae _
which includes varieties of flowering plants with normally arranged
sexual parts.
   When he spotted the plant in September 1985, Martinez was
collecting for Flora Mesoamericana, a survey run by the National
University, the Missouri Botanical Garden and the Natural History
Museum in London.
   He has been unable to find the plant in other parts of the
jungle, but Stevens thinks it will appear. ``My experience is that
plants don't have ranges that restricted,'' he said.
   The plant has survived for as long as six weeks in the
laboratory, but it then dies, perhaps because it doesn't fertilize
itself and may need insects to carry its pollen to another plant's
pistils.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thursday, March 30</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890327-0207 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-27-89 1403EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--Apples-Chemicals Adv30   03-27 0689</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--Apples-Chemicals, Adv 30,0705</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv30</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thursday, March 30, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>An Apple a Day Might Make the Doctor Sick</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YAKIMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An apple a day really might keep the doctor
away _ especially if the doctor knew what went on it.
   If fruit were labele the label on apples
would list fiber, potassium and vitamin C _ all of which are good
for you. It also might list azinphis methyl, Captan, Supracide,
parathion, Elgetol, Sevin, NAA, NAD, Ziram, diphenylamine, Lorsban
and benzimidazole.
   These might not be so good, but they're among the dozens of
chemicals routinely used to bring apples from fruit trees to fruit
bowls.
   Without some of them, according to Pennsylvania apple grower
John Rice, chairman of the International Apple Institute, ``People
would have to get used to biting into an apple and seeing a whole
or half a worm.''
   Probably the best-known of these chemicals right now is Alar,
the market name for daminozide, which helps apples ripen, extends
shelf life and prevents bruising. Many schools pulled apples from
their lunchrooms this month after the Natural Res
Council said Alar increased the risk of cancer among children,
whose diet contains proportionally more fruit than adults.
   Most schools let apples back in after the claim was disputed by
regulators, Uniroyal Chemical Co. and the industry, which cut its
use of Alar to 5 percent of the $1.2 billion-a-year crop since
concerns were first raised in 1985.
   But dozens of other chemicals are routinely used, and the NRDC
considers several of them to be cancer-causing even though, like
Alar, they are legal.
   A recent Louis Harris Poll found that 84.2 percent of Americans
would choose organically grown food if given the choice. But Rice
said that without the chemicals, an apple ``would be a rather
small, gnarled (object) that kind of resembled an apple. It would
be covered with a black fungus scab, infested with various decay
molds which could have natural carcinogens. It would undoubtedly
have codling bud moths and other types of larvae.''
   Washington's 5,000 growers, who produce about half the nation's
apples, spend an average $449 per acre to buy and apply chemicals
each year, said Brooke Peterson, a Washington State University tree
fruit extension agent.
   Many of the chemicals have been identified as harmful to childen
by the NRDC report, which studied chemical residues on food. But
those findings are in dispute, and the Food and Drug
Administration, Environmental Protection Agency, Department of
Agriculture and Surgeon General have all said apples are safe.
   Here is a typical chemical season for Washington apples:
   In early April, before bloom, an organophosphate spray _
Supracide, Lorsban or parathion _ kills the eggs of European red
mites and also controls the spread of San Jose Scale, a pest which
can kill trees.
   In May, growers will apply Guthion, the marketing name for
azinphis methyl, an insecticide that kills the codling moth larva,
which produces worms in apples and is the most damaging pest in the
orchard.
   Also applied at bloom time is Elgetol, a ``thinner'' that burns
off some of the flowers, reducing the number of apples a tree will
bear. Untreated trees will produce huge crops one year and tiny
ones the next to conserve energy. Another thinner is Sevin, an
insecticide made from the chemical carbarylaced Alar as a ``stop-drop,''
which
farmers would spray about a month after bloom to keep apples on
trees; an apple on the ground is worthless. NAA and NAD are less
effective, and there is no substitute for Alar's ability to extend
shelf life, Peterson said.
   Ziram or Captan, fungicides used to battle bull's eye rot, also
are applied at this time.
   In warehouses, the apples are rinsed, washed with detergent,
rinsed again, sometimes waxed, dried and placed in boxes for
shipment.
   Those destined for storage for three months to a year might be
treated with two chemicals. One is benzimidazole, a fungicide; the
other is diphenylamine, which prevents the red skin from turning
brown.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for March 30</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890327-0208 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-27-89 1536EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--What'sNew-Memory Adv30   03-27 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--What's New-Memory, Adv 30,0438</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv30</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thursday, March 30, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Study: Spoonful Of Lecithin Helps Stop Memory Loss</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Find yourself forgetting names and appointments,
mislaying keys and groping for words with increasing frequency as
you grow older?
   Two daily tablespoons of lecithin, a common health-food staple,
could help.
   ``The medical community accepts that there may be a role for
lecithin in aiding memory,'' said neurologist Barry Baumel of the
Neuromedical Centers of South Florida. Baumel and Florence Safford,
a Florida International University social work professor, studied
the effects of lecithin last year.
   In their study, 41 subjects aged 50 to 80 were given two
tablespoons a day of lecithin for four weeks and 20 others received
placebos. They kept logs of memory-loss incidents the seven days
before and after taking the substance.
   Ninety percent of the lecithin group had a significant decrease
in memory lapses, Safford said. The placebo group had 60 percent
more such lapses, though that may have resulted from increased
awareness because of keeping track.
   In addition, 40 percent of lecithin takers ``reported an
improvement in mood, a decrease in anxiety and a general sense of
well being,'' she said. None of the placebo takers reported any
change in mood.
   The study was limited to people with mild memory loss, not those
with the severe symptoms or Alzheimer's disease, for whom lecithin
already has failed to show significant results, Ms. Safford said.
   Lecithin contains lots of B vitamins, particularly one called
choline, known to improve the work of neurotransmitters _ brain
cells that fire electric charges that make our thought processes
work. ``By adding choline to the diet, you are helping this brain
mechanism to fire faster,'' Ms. Safford said.
   ``There may not be dramatic changes. We're not looking at people
suddenly becoming geniuses. But even if it helps a little bit, we
should try it.''
   But choline needs to pass the blood-brain barrier, which keeps
harmful chemicals from damaging the brain. Lecithin, which is
similar to chemicals in the brain, turns out to be an ideal
transporter. ``It has an emulsifier that allows it to pass through
the blood-brain barrier,'' Safford said.
   The lecithin is taken in granule form, mixed with a liquid like
fruit juice or sprinkled on cereal, rather than in capsules, she
said. ``You'd have to take 16 to 20 capsules a day to equal the
same amount as a tablespoon.''
   The only reported ill effect from lecithin was mild diarrhea.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thursday, March 30</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890327-0209 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-27-89 1537EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--Explorations-Summary Adv30   03-27 0941</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--Explorations-Summary, Adv 30,0969</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv30</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thursday, March 30, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: This is the Explorations package for March 30 in summary form.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Oat Bran Craze Shows No Signs of Tapering Off, Cereal Makers Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nothing helps scenery like ham and eggs, Mark
Twain once remarked, but health-conscious Americans are choosing a
bowl of oat bran instead to brighten up their breakfast horizons.
   Consumer craving for the husk of the oat kernel has opened up a
whole new landscape for cereal makers and bakers, while critics
charge that greedy food companies are unscrupulously capitalizing
on the consumer craze.
   Almost 1{ years have passed since the oat-bran boom began,
ignited by scientific studies indicating that just over an ounce of
oat bran eaten daily as part of a low-fat diet could help prevent
heart attacks.
   Quaker Oats Co., the nation's largest oat miller and maker of
oat bran cereal, is turning out a million pounds of oat bran a
month, compared with a million a year two years ago, and is
introducing a cold oat bran cereal.
   Meanwhile, competitors are jumping on the bran wagon, including
Nabisco Foods Co. of Parsippany, N.J., and St. Louis-based Ralston
Purina Co. Oat bran is going into everything from pancakes to
potato chips.
   The magic of oat bran is that it is one of the best known
sources of soluble fiber, which reduces cholesterol in the blood
and along with it risk of heart disease. Beans like pinto, kidney
and navy; psyllium, a seed grain; rice bran; and fruits with
pectin, like apples and grapefruit, are good sources.
   One of the most important studies of oat bran found that people
with normal blood cholesterol levels who went on a low-fat diet
reduced their cholesterol levels by about 5 percent. But if their
diets included 2 ounces of oat bran or oat meal, the cholesterol
levels dropped 8 percent to 9 percent.
   Every 1 percent decline in blood cholesterol is believed to
result in a 1 percent to 2 percent reduction in heart attack risk,
said dietitian Linda Van Horn, who led the study at Northwestern
University Medical School.
   As little as 34 grams of oat bran _ a little more than an ounce
_ have been found to produce the cholesterol-lowering effect in
scientific studies.
   But that knowledge may be of little help to consumers facing
torrents of advertising hype and a jungle of new oat-bran products.
It can take more than a dozen servings a day of some foods to see
benefits, and some products are full of highly saturated fats that
may drive up blood-cholesterol levels more than the oat bran lowers
them. ``Check the label,'' nutritionists warn.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Newly Discovered Flower Gets Sex Backward</HEAD>
