<DOCNO> AP890327-0210 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-27-89 1538EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--Briefs Adv30   03-27 0965</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--Briefs, Adv 30,0990</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv30</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thursday, March 30, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Researcher Says Climbing Stairs Not Good Exercise For Fatties</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fat people shouldn't climb stairs for
exercise because it can put dangerous stress on their hearts, a
physician says.
   ``Stair climbing is excellent exercise for individuals who are
not overweight. However, stair climbing is not the best way for
overweight people to lose weight,'' said Dr. Marque Hunter, a
University of Texas Medical Branch pulmonary specialist who tested
20 men at or near their ideal weight and 10 who were 30 percent
overweight on a miniature ``escalator'' sold for exercise.
   ``An overweight person must perform an excessive amount of work
to climb stairs even at a modest pace,'' Hunter recently told the
Federation of American Societies for Experimental Biology.
   The men were tested at 40, 50, 60 and 70 steps a minute for five
minutes at each speed, going without a rest from one speed to the
next. Heart rates and oxygen consumption were measured throughout.
   Fifty steps a minute is about normal climbing speed, but only
three of the fat men managed to get past 40 steps a minute, Hunter
said. ``Seven of the 10 reached exhaustion in three or four minutes
at the lowest speed. The other three reached exhaustion in the next
five minutes.''
   Nearly all of the other group got to 60 or 70 steps a minund of a nut
and a bolt. You sew on
the nut part into the front of the eye, then screw the bolt in
through this supporting structure,'' said Barron.
   One major problem, is that rejection sets in faster than many
other sorts of plastic implants, he said. ``It's different than an
artificial heart valve or an artificial hip, where it's totally
enclosed. For the patient to see, it has to protrude partly out.
And the body tries to extrude it.''
   Patients must use an antibiotic ointment on the lens and eyelid
at night, with a pad to protect the lens and ``close'' the eye for
sleep. In the morning, they clean it off with hydrogen peroxide on
a cotton swab. Some implants can last for years, but complications
usually set in after a year or two.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Doctor Claims First Test For Premenstrual Syndrome</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gynecologist says he's developed a test to
detect whether moodiness is a result of premenstrual syndrome, but
others say his work is promising although the sample is too small
to be conclusive.
   Dr. Edward M. Portman, whose clinic in Madison, Wis.,
specializes in PMS and menopausal care, told the Federation of
American Societies for Experimental Biology that he has found low
levels of the antibody for leuteinizing hormone _ the hormone
controlling ovulation _ among PMS sufferers.
   Portman said his is the first biological test for PMS, which is
estimated to affect anywhere from one-tenth to half of all women.
   ``It would be wonderful if we had a test like that,'' said Dr.
Patricia K. Branning, a New Orleans gynecologist. A test would help
doctors convince women whose depression was not due to PMS that
they needed to try other treatment.
   She and gynecologist Mary Francis Gardner said Portman's sample
_ 456 women with PMS and 65 symptom-free controls _ was too small
for conclusive results.
   ``PMS is such a very diffuse problem, it's hard to deal with. It
has such protean manifestations,'' said Branning. ``I think you
aways wonder if it's not more than one thing that we've lumped
together under one heading.''
   Symptoms include depression, distorted thinking, angry
outbursts, headache, food binges and bloating in the weeks between
ovulation and menstruation.
   Without a test, Portman said, doctors must see whether a woman's
symptoms fit PMS and ask her to chart them against her period for
several months.
   ``We are at the very embryonic stage of what we have,'' said
Portman. ``We have a high and statistic significant correlation of
antibody levels and PMS. Hopefully, over the next few years we can
unravel more of this.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thursday, March 30</NOTE>
