<FIRST>u f PM-Polaroid-Shamrock     03-27 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Polaroid-Shamrock,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamrock Holdings Abandons Bitter Takeover Bid for Polaroid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Less than a week after a Delaware court
temporarily stymied its chances of acquiring Polaroid Corporation,
Shamrock Holdings Inc. announced today that it is abandoning its
eight-month, often bitter battle to take over the instant
photography company.
   Polaroid officials said they have entered into an agreement with
Shamrock under which Shamrock will terminate its tender offer and
proxy contest and both companies will end all litigation between
them.
   Shamrock, based in Burbank, Calif., and its affiliate companies
have also agreed not to attempt to gain control of the
Cambridge-based Polaroid for at least 10 years.
   ``We are very pleased that Polaroid and Shamrock have reached an
agreement that will serve the best interests of all Polaroid's
shareholders by freeing Polaroid of the huge future costs of
fighting a disruptive takeover bid and enable all of us to devote
our full energy, creativity and talent to building and realizing
Polaroid's enormous inherent values,'' said I. MacAllister Booth,
president and chief executive officer of Polaroid.
   The settlement includes a provision that Polaroid distribute to
shareholders either through dividends or stock repurchases part of
the after-tax proceeds from a copyright infringement suit against
Kodak.
   Under the agreement, Polaroid will distribute a portion equal to
at least a quarter of the proceeds over $750 million up to $1.2
billion or 33{ percent of proceeds between $1.2 billion and $2.4
billion or 50 percent of proceeds above $2.4 billion.
   The amount that will be distributed will be determined after it
is decided how much Kodak must pay Polaroid. A trial to determine
damages from Kodak is scheduled to begin in Boston next month.
   Polaroid has also bought $5 million worth of advertising on
Shamrock's radio and television stations. The company has also
reimbursed Shamrock for $20 million for out-of-pocket expenses
stemming from the litigation and Shamrock's tender offer.
   Shamrock, which offered $45 a share for Polaroid stock, was
thwarted Thursday by a Delaware court decision clearing the way for
Polaroid to repurchase 16 million shares of its own stock for $50
each.
</TEXT>
