<FIRST>u f PM-Eastern 1stLd-Writethru f0013 03-27 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0013,0530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Seeks New Pilots In Class, Old Ones In Court</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with judge setting hearing for Thursday after
meeting with lawyers; airline saying 40 pilots beginning training. No pickup.
Adds byline. Also moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRACY FIELDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge today set a hearing on a key issue
in Eastern Airline's efforts to force its pilots back to work,
while the strikebound carrier began its first class in training
replacement pilots.
   U.S. District Judge Edward Davis said this morning he would hear
arguments Thursday on whether the pilots' strike was only a refusal
to cross Machinists' picket lines, or was a primary strike, which
could be illegal under the Railway Labor Act.
   The 11th Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta had asked the judge
for a decision on the issue, which is central to Eastern's legal
efforts to end the 3-week-old walkout.
   ``As I see it, I need to make a determination whether refusal to
cross the picket line is a `pretext,''' the judge said today. ``I
must determine what the appeals court means about `pretext.'''
   Air Line Pilots Association attorney James Linsey asked for
Thursday's hearing during the judge's meeting with lawyers.
   ``We don't think that Eastern has shown in the previous hearings
that ALPA's action was a pretext,'' Linsey said.
   ALPA claims the Railway Labor Act gives its members the right to
show sympathy for the striking Machinists. The appeals court
agreed, but added that ``a claim of a sympathy strike cannot be
used as a pretext to shield conduct that otherwise would be a clear
violation of the Railway Labor Act.''
   Eastern lawyer David Ross said today that the judge already had
enough evidence, unsuccessfully arguing for Davis to immediately
forward to the appeals judges the finding that the pilots' walkout
was not allowed.
   Meanwhile, Eastern spokesman Jim Ashlock said the first six-week
training class for about 40 replacement pilots was beginning today
with an organizational session. All but 200 of Eastern's 3,600
pilots have refused to work since the strike began March 4.
   ``I have heard that they're even coming from other airlines,''
Ashlock said of the new pilots. ``They're coming over because they
can make seniority faster.''
   Eastern has been operating only about 10 percent of its daily
pre-strike schedule of 1,040 flights, concentrating on routes from
the airline's Miami hub to the Northeast and from Florida to the
Caribbean, which were the most heavily traveled on Eastern's past,
said spokeswoman Karen Ceremsak.
   The pilots union continued to play down Eastern's efforts to
hire replacement pilots, saying there simply aren't enough pilots
to fill available airline slots, especially at Eastern and
Continental Airlines, which are operated by Frank Lorenzo's
Houston-based Texas Air Corp.
   ``Young pilots know better than to go to work for Frank
Lorenzo,'' said Capt. Jack Saux, a Delta Airlines pilot and
chairman of ALPA's education committee. Saux said in a news release
that he and other ALPA members have been meeting with pilots from
regional airlines and corporations as well as student pilots.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
