<FIRST>r f PM-Earns-GeneralNutrition     03-27 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Earns-General Nutrition,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>GNC Considers Selling Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Nutrition Inc. said today it has
retained two investment banking firms to explore ways to increase
the value of its stock, including selling or recapitalizing the
company.
   Chairman and Chief Executive Jerry D. Horn said no commitment
has been made to any course recommended by Lazard Freres &amp; Co. or
C.J. Lawrence, Morgan Grenfell Inc.
   The health food retailer, meanwhile, reported fourth-qaurter
profit of $4.9 million, or 16 cents per share, on sales of $116
million.
   A year earlier, GNC lost $3.9 million, or 12 cents per share, on
sales of $114 million.
   Horn said he is confident of achieving 1989 per share earnings
of 50 to 60 cents.
   Net income for the year that ended Feb. 4, totaled $12.6
million, or 39 cents per share, on sales of $361 million, compared
to 1988 earnings of $404,000, or a penny per share, on sales of
$350.9 million.
   ``Three years ago we began the restructuring process of General
Nutrition. The operational portion of that restructuring has been
substantially completed with the transformation of the company's
retail business from a commodities orientation to one of specialty
retailing, with the 1988 consolidation of our manufacturing
operations and the recent sale of our mail order unit,'' Horn said.
   ``We now are in a position to focus our efforts on further
increasing value through restructuring on the financial side,'' he
said.
   GNC says it is the nation's largest seller of vitamin and
mineral supplements and nutritional, personal care and
health-related products.
</TEXT>
