<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Lower On Rain Forecasts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were mostly
lower in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade in
reaction to forecasts for rain in some of the nation's major crop
areas.
   The corn and soybean markets registered the sharpest early
losses amid predictions for thunderstorms in the Midwest during the
next few days and above-average precipitation in the region next
week.
   The central and southern Great Plains also were expected to
receive rain tonight and Tuesday, which would help the maturing
winter wheat crop.
   There was little news of export business in the market this
morning.
   ``With a lot of the world not working today because of people
still celebrating the Easter holiday, there's not much here in the
way of demand,'' said Dale Gustafson, a grain-market analyst with
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in Chicago.
   Prices likely will be influenced this week by position-evening
ahead of Friday's Agriculture Department report on quarterly grain
stocks and spring planting intentions, analysts said.
   In early trading, wheat was } cent lower to } cent higher with
the contract for delivery in May at $4.29 a bushel; corn was 1\
cents to 2\ cents lower with May at $2.75} a bushel; oats were 1}
cents to 3\ cents lower with May at $2.02 a bushel; soybeans were 3
cents to 4\ cents lower with May at $7.81{ a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mixed while pork futures were mostly lower
in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .15 cent lower to .08 cent higher with April at
78.05 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .32 cent lower to .23 cent
higher with April at 81.25 cents a pound; live hogs were .02 cent
to .33 cent lower with April at 42.37 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .10 cent to .48 cent lower with May at 37.67 cents a
pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mixed on Thursday. The
commodity markets were closed on Friday.
