<FIRST>u f PM-MCorp 1stLd-Writethru   03-27 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-MCorp, 1st Ld-Writethru,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>MCorp to Remain Open Despite Bankruptcy Petition by 3 Creditors</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with further background, details on
MCorp, bankruptcy proceedings, editing.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DN5</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   MCorp, one of Texas' largest banking companies,
today announced it would seek protection from creditors under
Chapter 11 of the U.S. Bankruptcy Code, in response to involuntary
bankruptcy petitions filed against it.
   The troubled bank holding company, which last fall stopped
making interest and principal payments on about $470 million of
debt while it attempted to recapitalize, said three noteholders
last week filed a bankruptcy court petition in New York seeking to
have MCorp involuntarily sold off to pay creditor claims.
   MCorp spokesman George A. McCane said the company learned Friday
about the filings for the involuntary Chapter 7 bankruptcy
liquidation.
   ``MCorp deeply regrets that those noteholders ignored our pleas
not to take premature and unnecessary action,'' Gene H. Bishop,
MCorp's chairman and chief executive officer, said in a prepared
statement.
   Bishop said he hoped the action by a very small number of
noteholders seeking to force liquidation of MCorp would not disrupt
or interfere with discussions between prospective investors and the
Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. on terms of a recapitalization plan.
   Under Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy law, MCorp would be
protected from creditor claims while it reorganizes under
bankruptcy court supervision and works out a plan to pay debts.
   MCorp's Chapter 11 filing would supercede the Chapter 7
petition, which calls for the total sale of the company to satisfy
creditors.
   MCorp spokesman McCane said the company has not yet indicated
when it would ask the bankruptcy court to convert the involuntary
liquidation request to a Chapter 11 reorganization case. MCorp has
20 days to convert the petitions once the company is served with
them.
   The company's individual MBanks aren't involved, and the filings
should not affect the company's business, Bishop said.
   ``We want all of the depositors, customers, employees and
suppliers of MBanks to know that our 86 offices will remain open
for business as usual,'' Bishop said.
   Since last fall, Bishop said, MCorp representatives have met
several times with noteholders and urged them not to take action
prematurely despite the moratorium on payment of principal and
interst on borrowed money while the company proceeded with efforts
to recapitalize.
   The Wall Street Journal identified the three creditors who filed
the Chapter 7 petitions as S.N. Phelps &amp; Co., a Greenwich, Conn.,
bond broker that claims to hold $2 million principal amount in
MCorp debentures; and Janice M. Eberhardt and Carol R. James, each
of whom claims to hold $5,000 in debentures.
   I. Walton Bader, an attorney for the holders, told the Journal
his clients decided to file for Chapter 7 liquidation for fear that
MCorp would be forced to pump its holding company assets into the
failing MBanks, thereby putting the money out of reach of creditors.
   The Journal quoted analysts as saying MCorp's move complicates
the FDIC's efforts to arrange a sale of MCorp. The FDIC had set an
April 3 deadline for bids to acquire MCorp.
   The FDIC has the authority to sell or otherwise dispose of
insolvent banks once they have been closed by the U.S. Comptroller
of the Currency, but a bankruptcy filing would make any plan to
sell the company subject to a bankruptcy judge's approval.
   FDIC records show that 25 banks owned by MCorp posted a $213
million fourth-quarter loss and lost $903 million in 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
