<FIRST>u f PM-Eastern-Examiner     03-27 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Examiner,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trustee Looking at Dozen Candidates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. trustee administering the Eastern
Airlines bankruptcy said today he is considering about a dozen
candidates for examiner in the complex case, and sources said the
list includes former Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci and top
securities fraud lawyer Leon Silverman.
   U.S. Trustee Harold Jones said in a telephone interview he hopes
to make a decision by late this week or early next on his choice of
a bankruptcy examiner for Eastern, whom he will recommend to U.S.
Bankruptcy Court Judge Burton Lifland. An examiner would have broad
powers over the strike-crippled Miami-based airline.
   Jones declined to name people on the list. But the candidates
include former secretary of defense Frank Carlucci and Leon
Silverman, who represented some claimants in Manville Corp.'s
Chapter 11 proceeding starting in August 1982, sources close to the
situation said today. The sources spoke on condition they not be
identified.
   Silverman, a Washington-based securities lawyer, also is one of
the lead defense attorneys for imprisoned insider trader Ivan F.
Boesky.
   Carlucci is now vice chairman and managing director of The
Carlyle Group, an investment banking firm in Washington, D.C.
   Carlucci's secretary said he was unavailable to comment.
Silverman said he wasn't aware he was on the list.
   On Thursday, Lifland said he would appoint an examiner with
sweeping powers who would try to mediate the bitter dispute between
Eastern and its unions. The examiner also will review financial
transactions between Eastern, its parent Texas Air Corp. and sister
carrier Continental Airlines.
   Eastern workers struck the airline March 4 and it sought
bankruptcy court protection March 9.
   Jones said the candidates under consideration were recommended
to him either by Eastern management, the airline's unions or the
committee of 15 Eastern creditors which he named last Wednesday. In
addition, some of the people he is interviewing put themselves
forward for the position, he said.
   Jones said the ideal examiner would be ``someone who can play
the role of statesman.''
</TEXT>
