<DOCNO> AP890327-0225 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-27-89 1432EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-OPEC Bjt   03-27 0646</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-OPEC, Bjt,0669</SECOND>
<HEAD>OPEC Ministers Meet To Review Oil Situation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subroto cq as full name. Will be led with closing West Texas
Intermediate price.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OPEC ministers gather this week to
review a recently-strengthened world oil market and the impact of
the cartel's strategy for cutting production to help boost crude
prices.
   Eight ministers of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries were scheduled to begin talks Wednesday at cartel
headquarters in Vienna.
   Subroto, secretary-general of the 13-nation organization, told
reporters last week that the ministers _ members of a monitoring
committee _ would review the market and make certain the new accord
was working well.
   The cartel agreed last November on a new quota system limiting
each member's output in the first half of this year in an attempt
to support a price of $18 a barrel. The overall production level
was set at 18.5 million barrels a day, well under the actual output
at year's end.
   Many analysts had been skeptical the OPEC countries would comply
with their quotas, but now say most nations generally have met
their targets.
   ``They've done better adhering to (their quotas) than most had
expected,'' said Fergus MacLeod, oil analyst at Barclays de Zoete
Wedd in London.
   ``Prices have looked amazingly good,'' he said.
   The average price of a basket of crudes monitored by OPEC
reaching $17.50 a barrel last week, up more than $5 from late
November when the output deal was struck.
   In U.S. futures trading, the May contract for West Texas
Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude, was up 45 cents at $20.60 a
barrel Monday on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   Although Monday's price was inflated by speculation stemming
from the closing of the Alaskan pipeline at Valdez due to a major
offshore oil spill, it still reflected the crude's sharp surge from
the two-year low of $12.60 reached last Oct. 5.
   Subroto said, ``My feeling is that there seems to be a bullish
expectation in the market to see a strong price level. So we will
enter the second quarter, which is usually a weak quarter, with a
stronger demand than had been foreseen.''
   Independent producing nations also were expected to curb exports
by a total of less than 300,000 barrels daily in the April-June
quarter to support OPEC's efforts.
   The Soviet Union, the world's largest crude producer, said it
would join the cuts in the second quarter, when prices generally
decline with the onset of warmer weather in oil-importing countries.
   With the good wintertime results, the ministers also likely will
hold initial discussions on production levels for the second half
of this year. Those quotas won't be set until a full meeting of all
OPEC ministers June 5 in Vienna.
   Sheik Ali Khalifa al-Sabah, Kuwait's oil minister, told the
Middle East Economic Survey that OPEC should boost its production
ceiling by 1.5 million barrels a day to 20 million barrels in the
last six months of the year.
   He said in an interview published Monday that the cartel's price
target should be maintained at $18 a barrel.
   Since the production accord, OPEC has reported that 12 of the
nations complied with the agreement in January and February by
curtailing output for the international market.
   The cartel said the 12 nations pumped 17.4 million barrels of
oil a day in February, compared with the daily ceiling of 17.51
million barrels set for those dozen countries.
   The statement said the United Arab Emirates had not reported
supply figures in January or February. That country persistently
has exceeded its daily quota of 988,000 barrels. Analysts estimate
its current production at more than 1.5 million barrels a day.
   Ministers who form the monitoring committee represent Algeria,
Indonesia, Iran, Iraq, Kuwait, Nigeria, Saudi Arabia and Venezuela.
Other OPEC members are Ecuador, Gabon, Libya, Qatar and the United
Arab Emirates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890327-0226 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-27-89 1536EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-OilSpillCleanup     03-27 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Spill Cleanup,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mechanical Means Still Most Popular in Oil Spill Cleanups</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tanker Spill Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists are experimenting with new uses of
chemical agents to aid in the cleanup of oil spills, but mechanical
methods such as vacuum pumps, ``skimmer'' boats and absorbant pads
are still the most widely used.
   At the spill in Alaska's Prince William Sound, the volume of
crude oil in the water is so large _ 10.1 million gallons _ that
mechanical means are being supplemented with the use of approved
chemicals to disperse some of the oil on the surface.
   Exxon Shipping Co., owner of the tanker that spilled the oil
Friday near the port of Valdez, also planned to burn ``fingers'' of
the oil slick by igniting them with a laser.
   Experiments also are being conducted with the use of a chemical
agent that, rather than dispersing the oil on the water's surface,
causes it to draw together to make it easier to remove with vacuum
pumps, said Harry Schultz, a cleanup expert with the Coast Guard in
Washington.
   Under the best circumstances, some oil remains in the water
after a spill cleanup operation. Wind and wave action emulsify some
of it. Some is consumed by bacteria.
   In an ocean spill, oil on the water's surface can be herded into
one area by skimmer boats that use wing-like devices to guide it.
Vacuum machines then pump it onto floating barges, which take it
ashore in tanks and transfer it to trucks.
   For oil that has washed ashore or entered shallow-water areas in
which skimmer boats cannot be used, cleanup crews can use a string
of absorbant pads that soak up the crude.
   A variety of chemicals, usually in liquid form, also can be used
to break up sections of the oil slick. Some chemical agents are
used to make the oil sink to the bottom, where it poses no direct
threat to birds.
   Burning agents also are used, although questions have been
raised about whether the advantages brought by these and other
chemical agents outweigh the disadvantages of adding more
pollutants to the water or air.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890327-0227 </DOCNO>
