<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   03-27 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Plunge On Rain Forecasts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures closed sharply lower
Monday on the Chicago Board of Trade amid forecasts for wet weather
in the nation's major crop-growing areas.
   Further selling was attributed to technical factors and to
increasingly bearish expectations for Friday's planted-acreage
estimate and quarterly grain stocks report from the Agriculture
Department.
   The soybean market appeared to lead the decline, with much of
the selling in that market stemming from Friday's 6-to-10-day
forecast from the National Weather Service predicting above-average
rainfall March 30-April 3 in most of the central and all of the
eastern United States.
   Oats for May and July delivery fell the permitted daily limit of
10 cents a bushel on rain forecasts.
   ``There seems to be just a perception that the weather is
getting better and it comes in a very timely fashion for oats,
which are just getting ready to be seeded,'' said Dale Gustafson, a
market analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   At the close, wheat was } cent to 4\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in May at $4.27{ a bushel; corn was 6} cents
to 7} cents lower with May at $2.71 a bushel; oats were 9\ cents to
10 cents lower with May at $1.95\ a bushel; soybeans were 12 cents
to 15{ cents lower with May at $7.69 a bushel.
</TEXT>
