<FILEID>AP-NR-03-27-89 1615EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Polaroid-Shamrock     03-27 0517</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Polaroid-Shamrock,Bjt,0534</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamrock Holdings Abandons Bitter Takeover Bid for Polaroid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shamrock Holdings Inc. abandoned its
eight-month-old struggle to acquire Polaroid Corp. Monday, less
than a week after a Delaware court dealt the company a fatal blow
in its attempt to gain control of the instant photography giant.
   Polaroid officials said they entered into an agreement with
Shamrock under which Shamrock would terminate its $3.2 billion
tender offer and proxy contest and both sides would end litigation
resulting from the Shamrock bid.
   Shamrock, based in Burbank, Calif., and its affiliate companies
also agreed not to attempt to gain control of Polaroid for at least
10 years.
   Shamrock, which offered $45 a share for Polaroid stock, was
stymied Thursday by a Delaware court decision clearing the way for
Polaroid to repurchase 16 million shares at a premium price of $50
each.
   ``We are disappointed and frustrated by the Delaware courts,''
Shamrock president Stanley Gold said Monday. ``It's certainly not
good news for folks who are trying to do what we did.''
   Some analysts said the Delaware ruling allowing the Polaroid
purchase could signal a new era in the kinds of defensive
strategies planned by takeover targets.
   ``Up until now, attacking companies have been able to peel away
layer by layer of companies' defenses,'' said Brian Fernandez,
managing director of Brean Murray, Foster Securities Inc. in New
York. ``This is one of the first ways anyone's found to be
successful.''
   As part of its defense, Polaroid placed an estimated one-third
of its shares in friendly hands through the stock buyback, an
employee stock ownership plan and the sale of preferred shares to
Corporate Partners L.P., an investor group formed to help companies
fight hostile takeover bids.
   The moves were designed to frustrate Shamrock's attempt to
unseat the Polaroid board at the company's annual meeting and its
tender offer.
   Under the settlement, Polaroid will distribute to shareholders
part of the after-tax proceeds from a copyright infringement suit
against Eastman Kodak. A trial to determine damages from Kodak is
scheduled to begin in Boston next month.
   Polaroid also bought $5 million worth of advertising on
Shamrock's radio and television stations and reimbursed Shamrock
for $20 million in expenses connected with the litigation and
tender offer.
   Shamrock accumulated 4.95 million shares of Polaroid during the
takeover battle and tendered all of those shares before the
midnight deadline last Thursday.
   According to filings with the Securities and Exchange
Commission, Shamrock paid an average price of about $31 a share for
its stake in Polaroid. By selling 27 percent of its shares back to
Polaroid for $50 each, Shamrock can expect to receive approximately
$67 million.
   Shamrock's remaining 3.6 million shares of Polaroid would
conservatively be worth more than $130 million, yielding a profit
of approximately $42 million before legal fees, financing costs and
other takeover expenses.
   Polaroid said the final number of shares tendered under the
buyback offer, and the definitive pro-rating formula, will be
determined April 4. Payments will go out to stockholders as soon as
possible after that date, the company said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
