<FILEID>AP-NR-03-27-89 1658EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-Bankruptcy 1stLd-Writethru   03-27 0573</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Bankruptcy, 1st Ld-Writethru,0593</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carlucci, Silverman Said To Be Candidates for Eastern Examiner</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: ADDS new 12th graf with Manville comment; picks up 12th graf
pvs bg'ng, Jones said ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former defense secretary Frank Carlucci and Wall
Street attorney Leon Silverman are among those being considered for
the influential role of examiner in the Eastern Airlines bankruptcy
reorganization, sources close to the situation said Monday.
   The examiner, who will have what experts say is an unusually
broad mandate for overseeing a bankruptcy case, will be charged
with reviewing Eastern business transactions and mediating disputes
among the parties involved in the case, including strike-bound
Eastern, its unions and its creditors.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Court Judge Burton Lifland, who is overseeing
Eastern's Chapter 11 reorganization, on Thursday ordered the
appointment of an examiner with expanded powers, saying it was in
the public's interest to do so.
   Eastern sought bankruptcy court protection from creditors on
March 9 becuase of a cash drain stemming from a strike by its
Machinists, pilots and flight attendants that has virtually
paralyzed the Miami-based airline.
   U.S. Trustee Harold Jones, who is administering the Eastern
bankruptcy case, said he was considering about a dozen candidates
for examiner in the complex proceeding. He said he hoped to decide
by late this week or early next week on an examiner to recommend to
Lifland.
   In addition to mediating disputes among parties in the case, the
examiner will review financial transactions between Eastern, its
parent Texas Air Corp. and sister carrier Continental Airlines.
Eastern's unions claim that Texas Air has been attempting to funnel
Eastern assets to Continental, a non-union carrier.
   The ideal examiner would be ``someone who can play the role of
statesman,'' Jones said in a telephone interview Monday.
   Jones declined to name people on the list. But the sources, who
asked not to be identified, said the candidates include Carlucci
and Silverman, who represented some claimants in Manville Corp.'s
Chapter 11 proceeding that began in August 1982 and ended this past
January.
   Silverman, a securities lawyer, is one of the lead defense
attorneys for imprisoned inside trader Ivan F. Boesky.
   Carlucci, also a former chairman of the National Security
Council, now is vice chairman and managing director of Carlyle
Group, an investment banking firm based in Washington, D.C.
   Carlucci's secretary said he was unavailable to comment and
Silverman himself declined comment Monday.
   Silverman ``was a very effective and important part of the
resolution of our bankruptcy,'' said a Manville spokesman who
wished not to be identified further, speaking from the company's
headquarters in Denver.
   Jones said the candidates under consideration were recommended
to him either by Eastern management, the airline's unions or the
committee of 15 Eastern creditors he appointed last week. Some of
the candidates put themselves forward for the position, he said.
   ``It's a mediator with clout,'' said William Ury, associate
director of the program on negotiation at Harvard Law School.
   Bruce Simon, an attorney for the Air Line Pilots Association,
said the unions are looking for ``a strong public figure beholden
to no specific interest, including our own.''
   The examiner will need to ``bang the parties' heads together to
see if a solution can be achieved here,'' Simon said.
   Harvey Miller, Eastern's lead bankruptcy attorney, said the
company would like an examiner who ``has somewhat of a national
reputation,'' is impartial and has a strong legal or financial
background.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
