<FIRST>r f BC-BankAmerica-JCB     03-27 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-BankAmerica-JCB,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan's Major Bank-Credit Card May Deal in U.S. Through BofA</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Dwane is cq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bank of America is negotiating with Japan's
largest bank card company for the exclusive right to honor the JCB
credit card at more than 100,000 outlets in the United States, bank
officials announced Monday.
   ``This historic agreement would allow Japanese tourists and
business travelers visiting the United States to use their most
popular credit card throughout our extensive merchant base,'' said
Joe Fontana, senior vice president in charge of merchant services
at the San Francisco-based bank.
   Bank of America says it can perform all sales and servicing of
JCB International Co. Ltd. card accounts through its existing
credit card programs and will bill merchants for JCB use through
Bank of America statements.
   Under the deal, no other bank can honor the JCB card in the
United States.
   JCB's six sponsoring Japanese banks, which are not prohibited
from setting up their own servicing programs with U.S. merchants,
currently have no such programs. Through independent arrangements,
JCB is accepted at about 20,000 U.S. businesses, most of them on
the West Coast and in Hawaii.
   ``This deal will greatly expand the utility of our card for our
holder dramatically, both for visitors and Japanese nationals now
living or working in the United States,'' said JCB Dwane Krumme in
Los Angeles.
   Fontana indicated BofA's move is the first step toward expanding
merchants' ability to accept various bank cards without having to
arrange service programs with each sponsoring company.
   ``We feel this will be a significant step in providing merchants
with a convenient, consolidated service for different card types,''
said Fontana.
   JCB is Japan's largest bank-related credit card issuer and has a
card base of more than 13 million and a merchant network of more
than 1 million establishments worldwide. The JCB card currently is
accepted in 102 countries and territories, although most of the
company's business remains limited to Asia.
   Fontana said the agreement is expected to be signed within 90
days and would apply to 60,000 businesses with 100,000 outlets
nationwide. If approved, BofA will be the first major overseas
partner of JCB.
</TEXT>
