<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     03-27 0676</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0699</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Plunge On Rain Forecasts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices fell sharply Monday on the
Chicago Board of Trade amid forecasts for April showers in the
nation's major crop-growing areas.
   On other markets, orange juice futures surged for the second
straight session; energy futures advanced sharply; precious metals
were lower and livestock and meat futures were mixed.
   Wheat futures settled 1 cent to 4\ cents lower with the contract
for delivery in May at $4.27\ a bushel; corn was 6\ cents to 7}
cents lower with May at $2.71{ a bushel; oats were 9\ cents to 10
cents lower with May at $1.95\ a bushel; soybeans were 12 cents to
16 cents lower with May at $7.68{ a bushel.
   The selloff in the grain and soybean markets was widely seen as
a reaction to Friday's 6-to-10-day National Weather Service
forecast for above-average rainfall March 30-April 3 in most of the
central and all of the eastern United States.
   The winter wheat crop in the central and southern Great Plains
is in need of precipitation and rain also is needed to replenish
soil moisture in the Midwest, where corn, soybean and oat planting
will soon begin.
   Further selling was attributed to internal market influences and
to increasingly bearish expectations for Friday's planted-acreage
estimate and quarterly grain stocks report from the Agriculture
Department.
   ``The combination of the threat of precipitation and that very
important government report just triggered a lot of liquidation,''
said Pat O'Connell, a grain-market analyst with Refco Inc., a large
Chicago-based futures brokerage.
   A new 6-to-10-day National Weather Service forecast issued after
the close called for mostly dry weather in the Great Plains and
parts of the Midwest April 2-6.
   The soybean market appeared to lead the collapse but oats
registered the steepest relative losses. Oats for May and July
delivery fell the permitted daily limit of 10 cents a bushel.
   Frozen concentrated orange juice futures soared the
5-cents-a-pound limit on the New York Cotton Exchange on buying
linked to reports that some of Florida's largest orange-juice
processors had raised or planned to raise their wholesale prices to
$1.60-$1.65 a pound from $1.50.
   The price increase may cause a scramble for near-term deliveries
but projections for abundant supplies from Brazil should ensure
against supply tightness, said analyst Judy Ganes of Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc.
   Orange juice settled 4.70 to 5 cents higher with May at $1.609 a
pound.
   Oil futures rose sharply on the New York Mercantile Exchange
amid supply-shortage fears linked to the massive oil spill in
Alaska. The spill forced a shutdown of Alaska's Port of Valdez,
cutting the pipeline output of Alaskan crude oil by more than half.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled .13 cent to .42 cent
higher with May at $20.53 a barrel; heating oil was .86 cent to
1.06 cents higher with April at 57.58 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .35 cent to 1.83 cents higher with April at 59.75
cents a gallon.
   Gold and silver futures fell on New York's Commodity Exchange,
reflecting a continued easing of inflation fears.
   Gold settled $1.70 to $2.10 lower with April at $391.60 a troy
ounce; silver was 5.7 cents to 6 cents lower with May at $6.003 a
troy ounce.
   Cattle futures finished mostly higher on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, led by a surge of speculative and commercial buying in
the feeder cattle market amid indications strong consumer demand.
   Pork futures ended the day lower with most of the selling
stemming from Friday's USDA cold-storage report, which showed a
record number of pork bellies in cold storage for the fourth
consecutive month.
   Live cattle settled .25 cent lower to .35 cent higher with April
at 78.15 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .28 cent to 1.10 cents
higher with April at 81.97 cents a pound; live hogs were .10 cent
to .43 cent lower with April at 42.27 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .18 cent to .98 cent lower with May at 37.17 cents a
pound.
</TEXT>
