<DOCNO> AP890327-0241 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-27-89 2055EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-AmericanMedical     03-27 0593</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-American Medical,0611</SECOND>
<HEAD>Health Care Company Ponders Buyout, Restructuring Bids</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Medical International
Inc., which Monday was weighing a $1.7 billion buyout bid against a
management-proposed reorganization, likely will sell some of its 75
hospitals in either case, analysts said.
   The cash-and-stock bid to take the company private was revealed
Sunday by Dr. M. Lee Pearce, a Miami physician and investor who
owns about 10 percent of American Medical's 72 million shares. The
offer from Pearce and two former American Medical officers, which
presumes acceptance of management, is for $24 a share _ $20 to $22
of that in cash and the rest in securities.
   The buyers would assume $1.4 billion in long-term debt.
   At the same time Pearce's proposal was announced, the company
revealed it was considering a restructuring plan it said would
boost the company's value to $25 to $29 per share. The company
refused to reveal further details of the restructuring.
   A special committee of the board began weighing the proposals
Monday. Spokesman Mick Taylor said the study was expected to take a
few weeks.
   American Medical led the New York Stock Exchange's most-active
list, jumping $3.62{ a share to $21.50.
   The company owns 55 acute-care and psychiatric hospitals in the
United States and 20 oversease in the United Kingdom, Switzerland,
Spain, Greece and Singapore. The domestic hospitals are in 15
states, most of them in California, Florida and Texas. All have AMI
in their names.
   Pearce's offer was made with Shamrock Investments, a Los Angeles
partnership including former American Medical executives Charles
Reilly and Michael Gallagher. It is unrelated to Roy E. Disney's
Shamrock Holdings Inc., which Monday abandoned a bid for Polaroid
Corp.
   American Medical, under pressure from Pearce and others to boost
flat earnings and improve its stock price, has over the last two
years sold more than 40 hospitals and laid off 2,000 employees.
Further efforts to pare the company down to a profitable core
include sale of non-hospital subsidiaries including outpatient
surgery centers, AMICARE Insurance health plans, and alcohol and
drug rehabilitation services.
   Asset sales are likely under either the buyout or the
reorganization, particularly of the company's overseas hospitals.
   Pearce's New York attorney, Seymour Chalif, said the potential
buyers would expect to sell non-core businesses, possibly including
the foreign operations.
   American Medical refused to release any details of its proposed
restructuring, but analysts suggested that plan, too, would involve
sale of assets.
   ``Basically, we're talking about scaling back to a group of the
most attractive hospitals,'' said analyst Rae Alperstein, who
follows the company for Bateman Eichler, Hill Richards Inc. a Los
Angeles securities firm.
   She called $24 a fair price apresent, but suggested an
aggressive restructuring effort that includes sale of unprofitable
hospitals could boost the company's value into the high $20s per
share in a year.
   Sale of the overseas hospitals could bring $450 million, Ms.
Alperstein estimated.
   In addition to asset sales, the restructuring plan could include
moving the headquarters out of expensive Beverly Hills, a direct
cash dividend to shareholders and a stock buyback, said Todd
Richter, who follows the company for Dean Witter Capital Markets in
New York. He values the company at $25 to $30 a share.
   American Medical reported Friday that its earnings declined to
$18.1 million, or 26 cents per share, for the three months ending
Feb. 28, on revenues of $678.2 million. During the same period a
year earlier, earnings were $24.1 million, or 30 cents per share,
on revenues of $766.1 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
