<FIRST>r f AM-SEC-Stahl     03-27 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SEC-Stahl,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>SEC Plans Action Against Convicted Ex-Shearson Exec</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission said
Monday it plans administrative action against convicted former
Shearson Lehman Brothers Inc. executive Mark L. Stahl that could
bar him from the industry.
   Stahl, who admitted to an $18 million check-kiting scheme, was
sentenced to five years in prison last year on fraud charges.
   According to Lawrence Iason, regional administrator of the SEC's
New York office, a hearing before an administrative law judge will
determine whether Stahl's 1987 conviction on four counts of wire
fraud exposes him to civil SEC sanctions.
   Martin Kuperberg, the SEC's associate regional administrator,
declined to say what specific action the commission would bring
against Stahl, but said options ranged from censure to a permanent
bar from the securities industry.
   He said a tentative earing was scheduled for April 19.
   Employed by Shearson since 1979, Stahl, 46, of Manhattan, was
fired by the firm on the day of his arrest in April 1987.
   He pleaded guilty to fraudulently transferring a total of $1.031
million in Shearson funds to various bank accounts he controlled in
Boston, Hartford, Conn., and Elizabeth, N.J., but admitted
defrauding the firm of a ``litte less'' than $19 million.
   Shearson Lehman Brothers is now known as Shearson Lehman Hutton
Inc.
</TEXT>
