<DOCNO> AP890327-0243 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-27-89 1853EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Spill-Exxon     03-27 0518</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spill-Exxon,0535</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exxon May Pay Up Willingly To Avoid Damaging Controversy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tanker Spill Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exxon Corp. is likely to pay willingly for the
cleanup of the Alaskan oil spill to avoid controversy that could
hurt its opportunity to explore for oil in an arctic wildlife
refuge, oil analysts said Monday.
   Exxon is so big that even if it had to pay $100 million out of
its own coffers for the cleanup its earnings would be lowered by
only a nickel a share, said Frank Knuettel, an analyst at
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   A bigger priority for the company is winning congressional
approval for oil companies to explore in the pristine Arctic
National Wildlife Refuge in northeastern Alaska, Knuettel said.
   The oil spill from the tanker Exxon Valdez has slowed momentum
for the authorization, which passed a Senate committee earlier this
month, aides to senators on both sides of the issue said Monday.
   ``They'd want to handle this as quickly and efficiently as
possible'' to limit the damage to its image, Knuettel said. ``This
obviously is a setback.''
   The Exxon Valdez, carrying 1.2 million barrels of North Slope
crude oil, ran onto a reef 25 miles from port early Friday.
Estimates put the spill at 240,000 barrels of oil, or about 10.1
million gallons, making it the biggest U.S. spill on record.
   Reflecting investors' lack of concern about the spill, Exxon's
stock closed unchanged at $44.50 a share in consolidated New York
Stock Exchange trading.
   A long delay in resumption of shipping from the Valdez terminal
could hurt Exxon and other producers if it forced them to cease
production temporarily, cutting into their revenue, said
Constantine Fliakos, an analyst at Merrill Lynch &amp; Co.
   As for the cleanup itself, Exxon is liable for the first $14
million in damages under terms of the Trans-Alaska Pipeline
Authorization Act. Up to $86 million more could be paid out of a
Trans-Alaska Pipeline Liability Fund that was funded by tariffs on
oil production by Exxon, British Petroleum Co., Atlantic Richfield
Co. and several smaller Alaska oil producers.
   However, the administrator of the fund, Edwin Powell, said
Monday that the fund could seek reimbursement from Exxon if there
was evidence Exxon was negligent in the spill.
   Powell, who is treasurer of Unocal Corp., said Exxon might
choose to pay the full costs up front if it wanted to avoid a
controversy with the fund over possible negligence. He said he had
not heard from Exxon on the matter.
   Exxon U.S.A. spokesman Les Rogers said Exxon is a party to two
insurance-related agreements, the Tanker Owners Voluntary Agreement
Concerning Liability for Oil Pollution and the Contract Regarding A
Supplement To Tanker Liability for Oil Pollution.
   But Rogers failed to provide information by late Monday on how
those agreements could diminish the cost to Exxon of the cleanup.
   Knuettel said he did not know if Exxon's admission that an
unlicensed third mate was at the helm of the tanker at the time of
the crash could affect its ability to collect on the insurance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
