<DOCNO> AP890327-0244 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-27-89 1909EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Soho-Seagram     03-27 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soho-Seagram,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seagram Subsidiary Acquires Natural Soda Maker</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Natural Beverge Corp., the maker of the
Soho Natural Sodas brand founded 12 years ago in a Brooklyn
kitchen, has been sold to the giant beverage company Joseph E.
Seagram &amp; Sons, the companies announced Monday.
   Terms of the all-cash deal were not disclosed.
   American Natural has sold more than 100 million bottles of the
sparkling soft drink with the distinctive label named after
Manhattan's artistic neighborhood. The company had more than $30
million in retail sales last year.
   ``My dream for starting this company was to see this brand
become a major brand,'' said American Beverage founder Sophia
Collier, 33. ``I saw that after 11 years the best way to achieve
that was to sell the company.''
   Collier said she decided to sell American Beverage in November
and began discussions in January with Seagram, the U.S. subsidiary
of The Seagram Co. Ltd. of Canada. The company and its 48 employees
will remain based in New York, she said.
   ``The company was growing but the fact is the soft drink
industry is a multibillion-dollar industry,'' Collier said.
``Sometimes you look over the fence and say, `Gee, if we had
another $10 million to promote this we could really do something.'
   ``My philosophy in starting the company was to make an
alternative to Coke and Pepsi. When I started there were no natural
sodas. I thought, just make wonderful sodas with fruit juice and
natural ingredients.''
   Collier _ an artists's daughter who wrote an autobiography at 19
and drove trucks around New England delivering Soho in the
company's early days _ said she will serve as a consultant and
spokeswoman for the soda, which comes in 12 flavors and is sold in
37 states and Japan.
   Soho won a dispute with Anheuser-Busch Inc. in 1987 over the
soda's distinctive diamond-shaped checkerboard logo, which it
introduced in 1982. Anheuser-Busch agreed in an out-of-court
settlement to drop a similar logo it had used for its own seltzer
product.
   Soho is latest addition to Seagram's empire of sprits, wines,
coolers and juices. The company's brands include Chivas Regal,
Crown Royal and Seagram's V.O. Canadian Whiskies, Mumm and
Perrier-Jouet champagnes, Martell Cognac, Barton &amp; Guestier Wines
and Seagram's Coolers.
   Last year, Seagram agreed to buy Tropicana Pure Premium Orange
Juice from its parent, Beatrice U.S. Food Corp., for $1.2 billion.
   ``Soho Natural Sodas have developed a loyal and growing
following in every market they are sold,'' said C. Richard Coffey,
president of the Seagram Beverage Co., of which Soho will become a
unit.
   ``They have achieved an enormous success because Soho sodas are
classic products sold with classic style,'' he said.
   Seagram reported a 1988 profit of $589.5 million on sales of
$5.1 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
