<DOCNO> AP890327-0246 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-27-89 2149EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Motorola-Hitachi     03-27 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Motorola-Hitachi,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Motorola Moves Legal Action Against Hitachi to Texas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Motorola Inc. has dropped a federal
patent-infringement lawsuit filed here against Hitachi Ltd., but
has filed a virtually identical lawsuit in Austin, Texas, officials
of the two companies said Monday.
   The lawsuit filed in January in U.S. District Court here alleged
that Hitachi was engaging in unfair competition with its new H-8
microprocessor.
   ``Hitachi does not know why Motorola no longer wishes to pursue
its claims in Chicago, the site of Motorola's national
headquarters,'' said a statement issued by Tokyo-based Hitachi from
Tarrytown, N.Y., home of its Hitachi America Ltd. subsidiary.
   ``Hitachi believes Chicago remains the proper place for these
lawsuits and it will resist Motorola's tactical maneuvers to avoid
the Chicago courts.''
   But spokesman Charles Sengstock of Motorola, which is based in
suburban Schaumburg, said in a telephone interview that Motorola
has two plants in Austin that make the microprocessors involved in
the lawsuit.
   He said the ``procedural move'' to Austin ``focuses the matter
(to) the center of our ... microprocessor activity and the site of
all the documents, evidence and witnesses.''
   Hitachi also has filed a lawsuit against Motorola in the Chicago
court, alleging that the Motorola 68HC11 microcontroller infringes
on a Hitachi patent.
   Sengstock said Motorola is seeking to have the cases combined in
the federal court in Texas.
   Motorola has said that the alleged unfair competition began
shortly after Motorola granted a patent license to Hitachi for
certain Motorola microprocessors in May 1986.
   The company said the Hitachi H-8 microprocessor series infringes
on at least four Motorola patents.
   Hitachi has denied any wrongdoing.
   Sengstock said Motorola would seek an injunction to stop
distribution of the disputed Hitachi microprocessors in the United
States. The lawsuit also seeks unspecified damages, he said.
   Microprocessors are digital electronic devices that perform
control and arithmetic functions in a computer. They often contain
hundreds of thousands of microscopic transistors on silicon chips
about a quarter-inch square.
</TEXT>
