<FILEID>AP-NR-03-27-89 2047EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-ZZZZBest 1stLd-Writethru f0025 03-27 0785</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-ZZZZ Best, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0025,0806</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Barry Minkow Gets 25 Years In ZZZZ Best Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 19 grafs to UPDATE with Minkow quotes, more quotes
from judge, details on sentence, other details, tighten; picks up 15th
graf, ``The government ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barry Minkow, who once was hailed as a
financial whiz kid, was sentenced to 25 years in prison and ordered
to pay $26 million restitution for fraud by a judge who called him
a charismatic liar.
   U.S. District Judge Dickran Tevrizian handed Minkow, 23, the
maximum penalty sought by the government.
   ``You're dangerous,'' Tevrizian told the 23-year-old Minkow,
``because you have this gift of gab, this ability to communicate
... (and) you don't have a conscience.''
   Minkow, who founded the now-defunct ZZZZ Best carpet cleaning
company, was convicted of 57 counts of securities, credit card and
mail fraud on Dec. 14. The government's sentencing memorandum
described Minkow as a remorseless liar and thief whose schemes cost
victims more than $100 million.
   In arguments during Monday's hearing, Assistant U.S. Attorney
James Asperger said Minkow would probably serve only a third of any
sentence imposed.
   In pleading for a lenient sentence, Minkow compared himself to
former financier Ivan Boesky, who is serving a three-year prison
sentence for his role in the Wall Street insider trading scandal.
   ``This is a great day for this country,'' said Minkow, clad in
blue prison-issue shirt and pants. ``This is a great day for
justice. This is how America works.''
   He commended the FBI, the Securities and Exchange Commission,
and the U.S. attorneys who prosecuted him, saying, ``They got the
right guy. They got the guilty guy.
   ``I see victims here today,'' he said, turning toward the
audience. ``I can only say to them how sorry I am, and I'm going to
get what I've got coming, every bit of it.''
   But the judge was unmoved by Minkow's plea or a similar one by
defense attorney David Kenner, who asked for a sentence of eight to
10 years and psychological counseling for his client.
   ``That would be a joke,'' snapped Tevrizian. ``Here is someone
who has corrupted the financial system. Here is someone who has
lied and cheated. That sentence would be a slap on the wrist.''
   After Minkow's appeal, Tevrizian told him, ``You tell me you're
sorry and I think, `Is he trying to clean my carpet or what?'
   The judge ordered that Minkow serve five years probation
following his release and that the probation would be conditional
on his paying the $26 million restitution as well as any back taxes
or civil judgments against him. The judge also ordered him to
participate in a drug dependency program.
   Kenner said outside court that he would try to get Minkow's
sentence reduced.
   Tevrizian has sentenced 10 other defendants in the case to terms
of a month to eight years.
   In their sentencing memo, Asperger and Assistant U.S. Attorney
Gordon Greenberg said Minkow carried out a ``five-year crime wave''
that ``amounted to a search-and-destroy mission aimed at the trust
and integrity of our financial institutions, securities markets and
the public at large.''
   But Kenner said in a reply memorandum that the young
entrepreneur was a victim himself, browbeaten by mobsters and
emotionally damaged by a ``dysfunctional family'' characterzied by
``physical abuse, emotional neglect, embarassment, secrecy, lying
and mental disorders galore.''
   ``The true story of ZZZZ Best is a young man almost constantly
in debt, struggling to prove that he will not become the failure
depicted by his father,'' Kenner said. ``Look closely and you will
see the picture of a compulsive debtor.''
   Minkow, who launched ZZZZ Best at age 16 in his parents' garage,
has insisted he was a captive of mobsters who took over his company
and forced him to commit fraud.
   The government claimed he was a shrewd con man who convinced
Wall Street investors and TV talk show hosts that he was a teen-age
genius.
   The collapse of ZZZZ Best rocked the volatile U.S. money markets
and exposed the vulnerability of major securities firms and banks,
which bought Minkow's sales pitch and committed millions to his
company.
   At the center of Minkow's confidence scheme was a claim that
ZZZZ Best was making a fortune restoring water- and fire-damaged
buildings. Investors were given badges and hard hats and taken on
tours of alleged restoration projects in abandoned buildings with
which ZZZZ Best had no connection.
   ``The magnitude and seriousness of defendant Minkow's criminal
conduct, coupled with his level of sophistication and ability to
manipulate both his cohorts and victims clearly place him among the
most significant white-collar criminals ever prosecuted on the West
Coast,'' the prosecutors said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
